<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Sunday, Feb. 6, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hijacked Afghan Plane Lands in London
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- No injuries have been reported in the hijacked Afghan
passenger airplane. After a tense journey across Central Asia and Europe, the
plane landed in London's Stansted airport early Monday. The Boeing 727 taxied to
a secluded spot on a runway about half-mile from the main terminal. The Ariana
Airlines plane was seized shortly after take off Sunday, about 12:30 a.m. EST
Sunday, while on a domestic flight from the Afghan capital, Kabul, to the
northern city of Mazar-e-Sharif. The plane made stops in Uzbekistan, Kazakstan
and Russia before arriving in London just after 2 a.m. (9 p.m. EST Sunday).
Essex Police Deputy Chief Constable Charles Clark said that negotiators had made
contact with the plane.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hillary Clinton Launches Senate Run
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Clinton announced her Senate run Sunday in a
university gymnasium, becoming the only First Lady to run for public office. The
race for the seat being vacated by fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan is
likely to pit Clinton against Republican New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in what
could be one of the most combative political campaigns in memory. Over and over
again during her announcement, Clinton pledged, "I'll be on your side" as she
described her commitment to better schools, better health care, environmentalism
and gun control.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russians Seize Last Rebel Stronghold in Grozny
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GEKHI, Russia (AP) -- Federal troops have seized the last rebel stronghold
in Grozny, acting President Vladimir Putin said Sunday, pronouncing an end to
Russia's months-long drive to take the Chechen capital. Putin said federal
troops had taken control of the western Zavodskoi district of the capital and
raised the Russian flag over an administration building there. "A short while
ago, the terrorists' last bastion of resistance was seized," Putin said in an
interview with state-controlled ORT television. "So, we can say the operation to
liberate Grozny is over."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
US Urged To Closely Eye Russia Nukes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. efforts to keep Russia's nuclear weapons materiel
away from rogue nations or terrorists may fail without increased government
money and attention, a bipartisan group of foreign policy experts warns. The
report examined the worldwide threat posed by the potential theft of nuclear
materiel from Russia's haphazardly protected stockpiles. It urges immediate
action by the White House and Congress to expand the U.S. assistance program --
or face a possible catastrophe. The study was based on findings by leading
foreign policy and nuclear weapons proliferation experts, including former
senior officials from past Democratic and Republican administrations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Cleric Denies Terror Links
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DALLAS (AP) -- Lawyers for a Muslim leader in Texas denied accusations by
federal prosecutors that he served as an intermediary for Osama bin Laden's
suspected terrorist network. Moataz Al-Hallak, imam of the Islamic Society of
Arlington mosque, provided only religious advice to a pilot on how to handle the
purchase of a small jet in accord with Islamic law, said his lawyer, Stan Cohen.
The plane crashed in the early 1990s while being used by one of bin Laden's
businesses, Cohen said. Bin Laden, a Saudi millionaire exile, is accused of
masterminding the 1998 bombing of two U.S. embassies in Africa. The attacks in
Kenya and Tanzania killed 224 people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pfizer To Announce Warner-Lambert Takeover
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. has emerged the victor of a three-month
takeover battle for control of Warner-Lambert Co. Pfizer is expected to announce
tomorrow it is acquiring Warner-Lambert Co. for $84.4 billion in stock. The deal
would create the world's second-largest pharmaceutical company. The combined
company's medicine cabinet includes the impotence treatment Viagra and Lipitor,
the blockbuster cholesterol fighting drug. The deal will mark the end of a
takeover battle that started in November when Warner-Lambert announced a $58.3
billion merger with its New Jersey neighbor American Home Products Corp.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Advance
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose moderately in trading Monday. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 111.86 points to 19,874.99 at
the end of the morning session. On Friday, the average closed down 23.29 points.
In New York on Friday, the Nasdaq Composite Index rose 33.17 points to 4,244.15.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 49.64 points to 10,963.80 at Friday's
close.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bulls Beat Clippers 100-90
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rookie Elton Brand scored 21 points and the Chicago
Bulls overcame a 16-point deficit to beat the Los Angeles Clippers for the
eighth straight time, 100-90 on Sunday night. Toni Kukoc had 20 points and 10
rebounds for the Bulls, who dealt the Clippers their fourth straight loss and
18th in 20 games. Maurice Taylor scored 23 points and Troy Hudson added 19 off
the bench for the Clippers. The game marked the first-ever meeting between
Brand, the top pick in the NBA draft, and Clippers rookie Lamar Odom, the fourth
overall pick. Odom was the rookie of the month in November and Brand earned the
honors in January.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE MILLARD
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 0003 </TRAILER>
