<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton starts building grassroots network with house parties  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) - Nancy Denofio thinks the world of Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
<P>
	   On her fireplace mantle sits a picture of Bill and Hillary. She has "Hillary
for Senate" buttons and hats all around her living room and even had a "Hillary
2000" cake made.
</P>
<P>
	   So when Clinton announced her campaign for New York Senate on Sunday,
Denofio called about 20 of her friends and invited them over to watch the event
on television in this New York resort city.
</P>
<P>
	   But it wasn't just a party. Denofio also passed out volunteer cards,
collected donations and gave a quick speech on the virtue of Clinton's campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   In 600 other houses in New York state, people were doing the same. As
Hillary Rodham Clinton was announcing her U.S. Senate candidacy in Purchase,
activists around the state gathered their friends, family and future Clinton
campaign workers in their homes to watch the first lady's announcement on
television and begin setting up a grassroots network for her.
</P>
<P>
	   Denofio, who worked on President Clinton's New Hampshire campaign steering
committee in 1995, placed a speakerphone on the couch and a few seconds later,
Clinton's voice came from the telephone.
</P>
<P>
	   "I want to thank all of you," said the first lady, on a cell phone only
minutes after she announced that she would run for New York's U.S. Senate seat.
"I want to start by thanking the nearly 600 families and individuals who have
hosted these house parties, opening your homes to your friends and your
neighbors to hear my announcement."
</P>
<P>
	   But the first lady wasn't just talking to people in Denofio's home across
from the Saratoga Performing Arts Center. She was conferenced in to all of the
homes at the same time. "I thought it was a misprint when I heard that there
were 25,000 people at all of these house parties but it seems that there is,"
Clinton said. "It is because of your interest and your commitment to this
campaign that I think we have such a great beginning today."
</P>
<P>
	   The first lady soon hung up - cell phone problems, she said - and the
50-year-old Denofio went back to work pitching volunteer work for the Clinton
campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're trying to reach the common person," she said. "While we're also
trying to raise money, it's not about the money. It's about the people instead."
</P>
<P>
	   Denofio had about 25 people in her home during the speech - a cheer broke
out around the dinner table as Mrs. Clinton acknowledged the house parties - and
no one left without signing a mailing list.
</P>
<P>
	   And this isn't the only Hillary party going on here. Across town, Saratoga
Springs' Democratic Mayor Ken Klotz, who upset a two-term incumbent Republican
last year, held one as well.
</P>
<P>
	   This is a unique way of doing this," said Denofio, daughter of former
longtime Republican Schenectady Mayor Frank Duci. "We need the workers and the
volunteers and what better place to find them than from your family and friends?
We hope to have a strong network here for Hillary."
</P>
<P>
	   Denofio shares a similar problem with Clinton - Clinton is a new New Yorker,
Denofio's a new Saratogian, having just moved there in November. When quizzing
her guests about where Mrs. Clinton should visit while in Saratoga Springs,
Denofio suggested Starbucks. An immediate cry went up among the group for her to
be taken to a local coffee shop called Uncommon Grounds instead.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sorry," Denofio laughed. "I just moved here."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-07-00 0015 </TRAILER>
