<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Monday, Feb. 7, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hijacked Afghan Airliner Lands in London
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   STANSTED, England (AP) -- The Afghan passenger airliner forced by
unidentified hijackers on a tense journey across Central Asia and Europe landed
at London's Stansted airport early Monday. So far there have been no reported
injuries. The Boeing 727 taxied to a secluded spot on a runway about half-mile
from the main terminal. Police and emergency vehicles assembled nearby. The
Ariana Airlines plane was seized shortly after take off Sunday, about 12:30 a.m.
EST Sunday, while on a domestic flight from the Afghan capital, Kabul, to the
northern city of Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mrs. Clinton Announces Senate Campaign
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton launched her Senate campaign
Sunday from the state she has called home for only a month, declaring, "I may be
new to your neighborhood, but I'm not new to your concerns." Clinton becomes the
first president's wife to run for office. The race for the seat being vacated by
fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan is likely to pit Clinton against
Republican New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in what could be one of the most
combative political campaigns in memory.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russians Seize Last Rebel Stronghold in Grozny
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GEKHI, Russia (AP) -- Federal troops have seized the last rebel stronghold
in Grozny, acting President Vladimir Putin said Sunday, pronouncing an end to
Russia's months-long drive to take the Chechen capital. Putin said federal
troops had taken control of the western Zavodskoi district of the capital and
raised the Russian flag over an administration building there. "A short while
ago, the terrorists' last bastion of resistance was seized," Putin said in an
interview with state-controlled ORT television.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Urged To Closely Eye Russia Nukes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. efforts to keep Russia's nuclear weapons materiel
away from rogue nations or terrorists may fail without increased government
money and attention, a bipartisan group of foreign policy experts warns. The
report examined the worldwide threat posed by the potential theft of nuclear
materiel from Russia's haphazardly protected stockpiles. It urges immediate
action by the White House and Congress to expand the U.S. assistance program --
or face a possible catastrophe. The study was based on findings by leading
foreign policy and nuclear weapons proliferation experts.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Cleric Denies Terror Links
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DALLAS (AP) -- Lawyers for a Muslim leader in Texas denied accusations by
federal prosecutors that he served as an intermediary for Osama bin Laden's
suspected terrorist network. Moataz Al-Hallak, imam of the Islamic Society of
Arlington mosque, provided only religious advice to a pilot on how to handle the
purchase of a small jet in accord with Islamic law, said his lawyer, Stan Cohen.
The plane crashed in the early 1990s while being used by one of bin Laden's
businesses, Cohen said. Bin Laden, a Saudi millionaire exile, is accused of
masterminding the 1998 bombing of two U.S. embassies in Africa. The attacks in
Kenya and Tanzania killed 224 people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pfizer To Announce Warner-Lambert Takeover
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. has emerged the victor of a three-month
takeover battle for control of Warner-Lambert Co. Pfizer is expected to announce
tomorrow it is acquiring Warner-Lambert Co. for $84.4 billion in stock. The deal
would create the world's second-largest pharmaceutical company. The combined
company's medicine cabinet includes the impotence treatment Viagra and Lipitor,
the blockbuster cholesterol fighting drug. The deal will mark the end of a
takeover battle that started in November when Warner-Lambert announced a $58.3
billion merger with its New Jersey neighbor American Home Products Corp.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Advance
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose moderately in trading Monday. The Nikkei
gained 111.86 points to end the morning session at 19,874.99.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Suns 105, SuperSonics 93
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PHOENIX (AP) -- Jason Kidd had 22 points, 12 assists and seven rebounds and
Rodney Rogers added 22 points as the Phoenix Suns used a dominant third quarter
to beat the Seattle SuperSonics 105-93 on Sunday night. Kidd had 16 points and
eight assists in the second half. Penny Hardaway added 19 points and six assists
for the Suns, who lost in Seattle 94-86 on Friday night.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Trail Blazers 100, Celtics 94
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- Jermaine O'Neal scored 13 points in 13 minutes, pulling down
a team-leading eight rebounds on Sunday night to lead the Portland Trail Blazers
to a 100-94 victory over the Boston Celtics. Steve Smith scored 23 and Scottie
Pippen added 19, hitting a 3-pointer with 2.2 seconds left in the third period
to give the Blazers a lead they never lost.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</P>
