<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dominica Leader To Form Coalition  </HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE FAUL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SPRINGFIELD PLANTATION, Dominica (AP) -- Dominica's new leader is a scion of
the plantation-owning elite who spurned his family's bourgeois ways to fight for
independence and help lead the Caribbean's black power movement.
</P>
<P>
	   At 58, Rosie Douglas has mellowed. He now touts his lush island's glorious
prospects in eco-tourism. But when he condemns the outgoing government's
excesses -- like selling passports to dubious foreigners -- one hears echoes of
the fiery determination galvanized during a stint in a Canadian prison.
</P>
<P>
	   In the early 1970s, Caribbean students at Toronto's Sir George William
University held a sit-in at the school's computer center, alleging they were
being given failing grades because they were black.
</P>
<P>
	   Police moved in, the mainframe computer was destroyed and students were
arrested. Douglas was jailed for 18 months, then deported, although he later
earned a political science degree from Montreal's prestigious McGill University.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was his incarceration in Canada that led to the setting up of the black
power movement throughout the Caribbean and established Douglas as a radical
figure in Dominica and throughout the region,'' said Crispin Gregoire, an
organizer of the campaign that swept the Dominica Labor Party to power in last
Monday's vote.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Many of us, the younger people you see around him now, were in high school
when he began the movement and inspired us to political activism.''
</P>
<P>
	   Back home, Douglas founded the Popular Independence Committee to fight for
freedom from British rule. After independence, he was briefly appointed a
senator. But when Hurricane David devastated the island in 1979 and he invited
Cuban troops to help, Douglas was fired, apparently as a condition for U.S.
relief.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, his Labor Party boasts of the 400-plus Dominicans educated at Cuban
schools.
</P>
<P>
	   The Labor victory was its first in 20 years, and last Thursday, Douglas -- a
balding man with an infectious smile who looks much younger than his years --
was sworn in as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
	   Ironically, victory came in part because Douglas, a former Marxist who took
control of the fractured Labor Party in 1992, steadily moved the party from far
left to center. In the new government, Labor shares power with a one-time enemy,
the conservative Dominica Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
	   Douglas has indicated he will likely scrap the outgoing government's
controversial policy of selling passports to foreigners. The U.S. State
Department complained last year that Dominica had sold passports to some 300
Russians. Noting this happened at a time when organized crime linked to Russians
had sharply increased, the Americans raised concerns the Russians were
laundering money through Dominica's offshore banks.
</P>
<P>
	   Douglas also said he hoped to transform Dominica into the eco-tourism center
of the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
	   Labor's campaign literature features pictures of Douglas with British Labor
Prime Minister Tony Blair and with members of the French Socialist Party in
Paris. Outgoing Premier Edison James criticized the numerous trips Douglas makes
off the island each year -- he was away 114 days last year -- but the Labor
Party countered that Douglas travels the world ``to make the contacts and meet
the people who can work with Dominica to bring investment, prosperity and create
the jobs we need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 0123 </TRAILER>
