<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani hits talk show circuit ahead of Clinton's announcement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Don't expect Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to announce he's
running for U.S. Senate anytime soon.
<P>
	   Not that he's not running, mind you, he just doesn't feel the need to
formally say so.
</P>
<P>
	   "In 1989, when I ran for mayor, I announced, I lost," Giuliani said on Fox
News Sunday, just hours before first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton officially
launched her campaign for Daniel Patrick Moynihan's U.S. Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani continued: "In 1997, I decided not to announce. And I won with the
largest margin a Republican has ever won in Democratic New York City. So I said
to myself, 'You got to find a better way to do this then, the big kind of
announcement thing."'
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement that there's not likely to be an announcement came during
the mayor's whirlwind tour of five Sunday morning news shows, likely designed to
blunt the impact of Clinton's big party in Purchase during which she told 2,000
cheering supporters she wants to be their senator.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayor did at least strongly imply that he IS in the race.
</P>
<P>
	   "May we assume that you wouldn't be running this Sunday morning gauntlet (of
talk shows) if you were not running?" asked Brit Hume on Fox.
</P>
<P>
	   "Ahhh, yes," the mayor said, hesitating.
</P>
<P>
	   When asked on ABC's "This Week" if he planned to run, Giuliani responded,
"Looks that way."
</P>
<P>
	   And on CNN's "Late Edition," he said: "Well, there's always doubt.
Otherwise, I might as well make some kind of Hollywood-style announcement of
some kind or other. But right now, it's very much a direction we're moving in.
We've raised over $12 million, we have over 90,000 donors."
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani said his campaign would focus on his success in reducing crime and
welfare and cutting taxes and was unlikely to bring up the Whitewater scandal as
a political issue.
</P>
<P>
	   "I doubt it, unless some relevant facts come out," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani also acknowledged that he and Clinton hold strikingly similar
positions on a number of issues - abortion rights, the death penalty, gun
control, gay rights and welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are a lot of issues on which we agree," he said. "There are a lot of
issues in which we disagree. I think there's a fundamental difference ... I
believe in solutions that don't necessarily involve building larger government."
</P>
<P>
	   Another difference between New York's Senate candidates: Clinton has
promised to serve her full six-year term if she is elected; Giuliani refused to
do the same.
</P>
<P>
	   And when asked whether he has the proper temperament for the U.S. Senate,
Giuliani said on "Meet the Press" that he had successfully worked with the
overwhelmingly Democratic City Council to pass budgets and other legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   "I tend to be a leader," he said. "I have strong ideas; I push very, very
hard for those ideas. ... We could use a senator from New York who is a strong
advocate."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
