<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diallo jury to hear from medical examiner  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Prosecutors say an autopsy shows that one of the 19
police bullets that stuck Amadou Diallo tunneled up his leg - a possible sign he
was shot while on the ground.
<P>
	   A medical examiner who did the autopsy on Diallo is expected to present that
finding and others at the close of the prosecution case against four police
officers accused of murdering the 22-year-old street vendor on his Bronx
doorstep.
</P>
<P>
	   The witness could testify as early as Tuesday. The trial resumes today.
</P>
<P>
	   An autopsy found that one of the 41 bullets the defendants fired at Diallo
on Feb. 4, 1999, went into his right leg, traveled upward and lodged behind his
right knee. The bullet's route could help prove prosecutor Eric Warner's claim
last week in opening statements that the officers kept shooting after the West
African immigrant "was falling down or actually on the ground."
</P>
<P>
	   Kenneth Boss, 28, Sean Carroll, 36, Edward McMellon, 27, and Richard Murphy,
27, have pleaded innocent to the second-degree murder charges. If convicted,
they face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The slaying of the unarmed black man by the four white officers produced a
flood of pretrial publicity and protests alleging widespread abuse of minorities
by police. An appeals court responded by moving the case to Albany.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors allege the plainclothes officers made a "conscious decision" to
kill Diallo without warning. But defense attorneys argue the shooting was a
tragic mistake made after the victim ignored orders to stop and pulled out a
black wallet that, because of darkness, appeared to be a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first two days of testimony last week, the jury heard from police and
other witnesses who described the spot where Diallo died as well lighted. One of
Diallo's neighbors, Debbie Rivera, also testified that she heard a volley of
gunfire followed by a brief pause, then a longer, final volley.
</P>
<P>
	   The pause could be used to argue the officers had a chance to cease fire.
But defense attorneys plan to call a sergeant who questioned Rivera on the night
of the shooting. His reports says she heard one continuous burst.
</P>
<P>
	   Other defense witnesses include a paramedic who used a flashlight to view
Diallo's body in a vestibule because, attorneys say, the lighting was so poor.
The defense also said a civilian witness would testify that Diallo was acting
suspiciously before the officers showed up.
</P>
<P>
	   The centerpiece of the defense case will be the officers themselves.
</P>
<P>
	   "You will hear from Ken Boss," attorney Steven Brounstein told jurors. "And
what I will ask you to do is step inside his shoes and try to view what he
viewed and hear what he heard that night."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
