<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Urged To Closely Eye Russia Nukes  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is proposing a sharp increase in
spending to help Russia safeguard its nuclear materials, administration
officials say. But a panel of foreign policy experts warns that might not be
enough to keep the stockpiles away from rogue nations or terrorists.
</P>
<P>
	   The president's fiscal 2001 budget, being unveiled today, includes an
additional $100 million to help Russia increase its protection of nuclear
materials and help create jobs for unemployed nuclear scientists, according to
sources familiar with the proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the additional money -- about $70 million -- will be earmarked for a
new program to help safeguard plutonium from Russia's 29 civilian nuclear power
reactors, said one official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   Programs to help create jobs in Russia's ``nuclear cities'' and to improve
security at facilities where nuclear weapons materials is stockpiled also will
be increased under the proposal, the official said. The Energy Department is
spending $240 million on these programs this year and Clinton is asking Congress
to increase that by about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   But a panel of senior foreign policy and nuclear proliferation experts said
in a new report that even more money and greater high-level priority is needed
to keep Russia's nuclear materials, including hundreds of tons of plutonium and
weapons-grade uranium, from being stolen.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The possibility that the essential ingredients of nuclear weapons could
fall into the hands of terrorists and proliferating states is all too real,''
said the 117-page report produced by the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, a leading Washington foreign policy think tank.
</P>
<P>
	   The study was based on findings by leading foreign policy and nuclear
weapons proliferation specialists, including senior officials of past Democratic
and Republican administrations.
</P>
<P>
	   The report examined the worldwide threat posed by the potential theft of
nuclear materiel from Russia's haphazardly protected stockpiles. It urges
immediate action by the White House and Congress to expand the U.S. assistance
program -- or face a possible catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We must take action to prevent a catastrophe,'' said former Sen. San Nunn,
D-Ga., the center's chairman and head of its global nuclear materials management
program.
</P>
<P>
	   The report urged that the United States spend $1 billion to blend down
highly enriched Russian uranium so it can't be used in weapons. It said
Washington also should step up efforts to help consolidate the more than 1,000
tons of plutonium and uranium now scattered in 300 buildings and 50 sites across
Russia, and name a new high-level official with direct access to the president
to coordinate the Russian assistance effort.
</P>
<P>
	   The theft of just a few pounds of highly enriched Russian uranium or
plutonium ``could allow a rogue state or terrorists group to acquire a nuclear
capability, posing a severe threat to the international community,'' the study
said. It said the ``lack of sufficient funding and senior leadership attention
on the U.S. side'' has prevented swift action to reduce the threat.
</P>
<P>
	   One of the report's authors, Matthew Bunn of Harvard's John F. Kennedy
School of Government, said the money set aside for these programs is ``woefully
insufficient,'' and more spending would be ``tiny in comparison to the cost and
risks of failure to act.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bunn, a specialist in nuclear nonproliferation issues, added in an interview
that ``the window for cooperation may be closing'' with Russia because of
increased hostility toward the West. ``It is clear already that the atmosphere
for sensitive nuclear cooperation is much worse today than it was in 1992 and
1993,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 0203 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
