<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Simon Estes carves niche as one of the finest performers of Wagner  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Simon Estes was flying around the world, singing to
rousing ovations. But back in his hotel room at night, he was "crying like a
baby," says the towering 61-year-old baritone.
<P>
	   "And I had lumps in my throat bigger than grapefruits - before, during and
after the singing," Estes says of the personal struggle after his recent
divorce. "But I thought, well, I have to take this incredible pain and make
myself stronger, and go on."
</P>
<P>
	   With his patrician presence and rich voice, Estes has carved a niche for
himself as one of the world's finest performers of Verdi and Wagner, singing
alongside stars like Placido Domingo and Leontyne Price. And his new
autobiography is filled with photos of Estes in the company of world leaders -
Nelson Mandela, Pope John Paul II, former President Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   But the glossy tome begins with a simple boy growing up in Iowa amid fierce
segregation.
</P>
<P>
	   "When I was a kid, we couldn't go into the swimming pool with white people,"
Estes remembers. "They'd disinfect the pool, and then they'd let the white kids
come in. You know, those 'black' germs were in the water."
</P>
<P>
	   This kid had a splendid voice. He ended up at New York's Juilliard School
and soon became the only black male opera singer of great celebrity.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, he says, "the world did not let me forget that I have a darker skin
color than you."
</P>
<P>
	   For his 1965 debut at the Deutsche Oper in Berlin, he was subjected to
makeup that made him look "white as a ghost," he says.
</P>
<P>
	   And in the 1970s, "I remember singing in one of those Southern cities, and
the director of the opera house came up to me and said, 'Simon, I want to work
with you, but I can't because some of the people who are giving us money said if
I engaged you, they're going to take away the funds. And we need the money."'
</P>
<P>
	   Things have changed. In his hometown of Centerville, Iowa, the local high
school auditorium was named after him several years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   "That was a way of saying, 'Simon, we're sorry,"' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He has given concerts around Iowa, and the state has given him the Iowan
Award, it's highest honor. This was the first time it went to a black person.
</P>
<P>
	   But his racially charged journey has left its mark.
</P>
<P>
	   When he teaches classes at Iowa State University, he speaks not only about
music but about human values, telling students: "Don't ever compromise your
principles to try to get a job, or a position or relationship, or whatever."
</P>
<P>
	   And despite his success, he's still waging an age-old battle to bring more
talented black male singers into classical music. There are plenty of black
female stars, he says, but only a handful of men.
</P>
<P>
	   "Find me a group of people where one gender can sing, and the other gender
cannot sing!" he says. "It's one of the last big hurdles that we still have to
overcome."
</P>
<P>
	   Estes tempers such frustrations by thinking of Nelson Mandela, for whom he
has sung.
</P>
<P>
	   "Here was a man who was unjustly incarcerated for 27 years. He came out and
not one time did he speak of revenge or hatred or bitterness," Estes says. "In
order not to have hatred when you have been so unjustly treated requires an
inner strength that I personally think has to come from a higher source."
</P>
<P>
	   Before each performance, he prays.
</P>
<P>
	   "I pray that the gift God has given me touches somebody's heart out there,"
says Estes, his face illuminated by a winter sun as he sits on the glassed-in
porch of his New Jersey home.
</P>
<P>
	   He glances at his watch to make sure it's not too late to call Switzerland,
where his three daughters live with their mother.
</P>
<P>
	   He has just finished vacuuming the white carpet; again he's a bachelor who
does his own cooking, laundry and ironing. He doesn't need to do housework,
given his six-figure income from work at the Met, the Vienna State Opera and the
Washington Opera.
</P>
<P>
	   But this man has a different definition of success.
</P>
<P>
	   "The more I sing, the more, in quotes, 'success' I have - whatever that may
be - the more humble and grateful I'd like to become, instead of feeling that
everybody has to cater to me and I have to have the presidential suite and a
limousine that's 40 feet long," Estes said.
</P>
<P>
	   To him, success means "being at peace with yourself."
</P>
<P>
	   There's at least one sore spot: The divorce he granted his wife more than a
year ago. Leaving her and their three daughters, ages 12, 14 and 16, "was the
most difficult thing in my life."
</P>
<P>
	   And it made performing tough, especially the lead role in Wagner's "Flying
Dutchman," for which Estes is famed. He pointed out that his character says at
one point, "Oh, I'm without a wife and I'm without a child," and said that's
when the lump arose in his throat.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've always been a very strong person in my life. But this broke me, it
really broke me," he says. "I flew around the world, and I was in hotel rooms
crying like a baby."
</P>
<P>
	   He survived through friends and prayer, and the shows went on. And now, his
piano accompanist tells him, he's singing at his best again.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm almost cured," Estes says. "And I think about trying to improve my
life, to be a better person."
</P>
<P>
	   He sponsors an educational foundation that gives scholarships to talented
students. Two years ago, he founded the Simon Estes High School near Cape Town,
South Africa, with almost 200 students who are focused on music. Last year, 40
of them attended school in Iowa for the academic year.
</P>
<P>
	   The baritone has perhaps another dozen years of performing ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
	   In March, he'll appear at Carnegie Hall in Ponchielli's "La Gioconda,"
followed by Verdi's "Aida" in Los Angeles with Domingo, appearances in Tokyo and
opera dates all over Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   And he says he'll stop performing "while I can still sing. ... I want to try
to be like Michael Jordan."
</P>
<P>
	   His final, dream concert in Washington is already planned, except for the
date. The program will include "Nobody Knows the Trouble I've Seen," as well as
a rendition of the 27th Psalm, "The Lord is my light."
</P>
<P>
	   And Estes will offer a beloved song by Gustav Mahler, "Ich bin der Welt
Abhanden Gekommen," meaning "I am lost to the world."
</P>
<P>
	   It ends with the words: "I live alone in my heaven, in my love and in my
song ... ."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-07-00 0208 </TRAILER>
