<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Fighting Back Against Gore  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GLOVER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hoping to counter early campaign setbacks, Bill Bradley's
Democratic presidential campaign has largely abandoned its above-the-fray
attitude and is aggressively confronting rival Al Gore on a series of fronts.
</P>
<P>
	   He has also opened a competition for backing of key party constituencies
where the vice president has held sway and where Bradley must make inroads if he
hopes to make the race competitive.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley began that effort by toughening his assault on Gore's fund-raising
troubles, coupled with a high-profile pitch for black voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's campaign week opened Sunday with a pitch for racial harmony at New
York's largest black church, Allen AME Church, and that theme was continuing.
The former New Jersey senator was heading for Florida today to tout his
commitment to affirmative action, then visit South Carolina to wade into the
fight over flying the Confederate battle flag at the state capitol.
</P>
<P>
	   The appearances were aimed at the significant black vote in such states as
New York and California, where the next round of Democratic primaries is planned
March 7.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley found a receptive audience in New York, where activist Al Sharpton
proposed that Gore and Bradley debate before New York's black community.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have been courted by both sides,'' said Sharpton. ``I come out of the
traditional family where people who want to marry you, court you. The black vote
is not monolithic. We need to hear the candidates.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley agreed, and Gore aides said they would present the debate idea to
the vice president. Spokesman Chris Lehane said the Gore campaign was in
discussions with Bradley's camp about debates, and ``I assume this (proposal)
will be part of those discussions.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am not taking the African-American vote for granted,'' said Bradley. ``I
have a lot of friends in New York.''
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, Bradley sharpened his criticism of Gore, a gambit that is
not risk-free because one of his core appeals is as a nontraditional politician
who doesn't use campaign attacks. But aides have concluded there is little
choice.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley renewed his attack on Gore's fund-raising practices in the last
campaign, criticizing the vice president's 1996 appearance at a Buddhist temple
near Los Angeles. ``I think he has to explain more thoroughly what was happening
at the Buddhist temple, said Bradley. ``If he didn't know it was a fund-raiser
then he was spectacularly naive.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley again warned that Republicans will hammer Gore on the issue in the
fall. ``There is no doubt in my mind that is going to happen,'' Bradley said.
``This is a real risk in the fall. The Democratic Party is taking a risk.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley also has challenged Gore on health care and his record on abortion
and says voters want a ``fresh start,'' a thinly veiled reference to President
Clinton's troubles.
</P>
<P>
	   ``America is about competition, political campaigns are about competition,''
Bradley said in explaining his new aggressiveness. ``If your positions are
misrepresented, you can only take it so long. That's the way I'll continue for
the next four or five weeks.''
</P>
<P>
	   By then, the battle for the Democratic presidential nomination could well be
decided, with the high-stakes showdown in California, New York and other states.
``I have to take off on March 7,'' Bradley acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
	   One place to begin is within his own party. Much of the Democratic
establishment is behind Gore and one of Bradley's most urgent tasks is winning
back key constituencies like blacks and women that surveys show overwhelmingly
support the vice president.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think I have to communicate better with the Democratic base,'' said
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley and Gore opened their weeks in New York, and both were setting aside
ample time for delegate-rich California.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have to win California,'' Bradley said. ``I know I have some ground to
make up.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore has focused heavily on California and has the backing of key state
leaders like Gov. Gray Davis along with organized labor.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides said Gore will continue the kind of grassroots, retail campaign that
led to success in the opening contests in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Al Gore is a national candidate,'' said spokesman Lehane. ``We'll be
campaigning in virtually every state where they have a primary. There's only one
candidate in this race who is undefeated, and that's Al Gore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
