<HEADLINE> Forbes Campaigns in Delaware  </HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER THORNE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DOVER, Del. (AP) -- For Steve Forbes, it comes down to Delaware. Again.
</P>
<P>
	   He's a Republican in need of a victory, campaigning for one against Gov.
George W. Bush, with Sen. John McCain an absentee name on the ballot in
Delaware's presidential primary Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes won in Delaware four years ago, gaining 33 percent of the vote to
beat Bob Dole, then the front-runner and the eventual nominee. But Forbes was
the only GOP candidate to campaign in Delaware that year, with the others
staying away in deference to New Hampshire's insistence on being the first and
only contest in the opening week of primary competition.
</P>
<P>
	   To avoid a replay in 2000, Delaware Republicans opted out of the state
primary last Saturday to hold a party-run election Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush was battling in Delaware to take some of the sting out of his landslide
loss to McCain in the New Hampshire primary. He campaigned here Friday, and was
due back today.
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes is spending four days on a bus tour of the state. He held town
meetings in Smyrna and Newark on Sunday, and planned two others today.
</P>
<P>
	   He said in an interview that even if he doesn't win, he will not quit the
race. Forbes said he'd be happy to come in second in Delaware -- but not behind
Bush. That's based on the idea that McCain might win, even though he hasn't set
foot in the state.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Nobody's ever had the united establishment, political-elite support that
George Bush has had,'' Forbes said. ``If George Bush is third, then you have a
two-man race.''
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes' problem is that it's already a two-man contest, and he isn't one of
them. He lost Iowa to Bush, and ran a distant third, with 13 percent of the
vote, in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   The self-financed candidate won two primaries in 1996, Delaware and Arizona.
This time, he has an active Bush to contend with in Delaware, and not only Bush
but home-state Sen. McCain in Arizona on Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes still trumpets his familiar flat tax proposal, the single issue
centerpiece in his first campaign. But he has tried to broaden the fare this
time, asking -- and after New Hampshire, pleading -- for conservative support,
campaigning as an ardent foe of abortion rights, an issue he did not stress in
1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Before a conservative crowd in rural Bridgeville, he got two standing
ovations when he denounced abortion. Jesse Flynn, taking a rare day off from his
auto repair shop there, said he was impressed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Abortion was a question mark. I had reservations in '96,'' Flynn said.
``But he's come out much more conservative, clearly, on the issue this time.''
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes said his positions have not changed but that he is better now at
delivering the message.
</P>
<P>
	   Polling by the Forbes campaign shows Delaware Republicans split almost
evenly between Bush and Forbes, said Wayne Smith, GOP majority leader of the
state House of Representatives and a Forbes supporter. He would not provide
details.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a key state,'' Forbes said. ``We've got a good basis for support
here, so I'm optimistic. If we win, we'll gain credibility here.''
</P>
<P>
	   In 1996, winning twice wasn't enough. Forbes quit that contest in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If Steve Forbes wins here, it'll be a serious setback for Bush, no
question. Bush has worked very hard in Delaware,'' said Chuck Welch, Republican
whip in the state House.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I like Forbes,'' Welch said. ``But he's spreading an ideological divide at
a time when the GOP is really trying to pull things together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 0225 </TRAILER>
