<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bombing Compounds NIreland Tensions  </HEADLINE>
   By SHAWN POGATCHNIK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- A bombing at a rural hotel by an IRA
splinter group has aggravated tensions as Northern Ireland faces the prospect of
losing its Protestant-Catholic government.
</P>
<P>
	   The Continuity IRA, which is opposed to the province's 1998 peace accord,
planted a bomb at the family-run Mahon's Hotel in Irvinestown, 90 miles west of
Belfast. The area was evacuated following telephoned warnings, and nobody was
injured when the bomb detonated beneath an oil tank at the back of the hotel.
</P>
<P>
	   But Sunday night's blast -- the first carried out by Irish Republican Army
dissidents since 1998, when a car bomb killed 29 people in the nearby town of
Omagh -- sent out shockwaves amid a crisis over the IRA's refusal to disarm.
</P>
<P>
	   Gerry Adams, leader of the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party, condemned the attack
and called for the dissidents to disband. But he said the blast should serve as
``an incentive'' to politicians to keep the province's four-party Cabinet
running.
</P>
<P>
	   Urging the British government to drop its plans to suspend the Cabinet's
powers this Friday if the IRA doesn't pledge to disarm, Adams said: ``The vacuum
which is opening up needs to be closed and closed quickly.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Good Friday peace accord proposed that a Catholic-Protestant Cabinet
should be strengthened by the gradual disarmament of the IRA and outlawed
pro-British groups. But it didn't explicitly tie the two goals together.
</P>
<P>
	   So for more than a year the major Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists,
refused to form a Cabinet alongside Sinn Fein unless the IRA first promised to
disarm. The American mediator, former Sen. George Mitchell, appeared to bridge
this divide in November with a deal that got the Cabinet formed in expectation
that IRA disarmament would soon begin.
</P>
<P>
	   But the IRA has refused. The group never accepted the accord's expectation
that the outlawed group should completely disarm by this May -- if ever.
</P>
<P>
	   In response, the Ulster Unionists threatened to resign from the Cabinet,
forcing its collapse, unless the British resumed ``direct rule'' from London,
the quasi-colonial system of government imposed here in 1972.
</P>
<P>
	   By rendering the four-party coalition powerless, the British government says
it is decreasing the risk that the Cabinet would collapse, an outcome that could
make it make its resurrection unlikely.
</P>
<P>
	   IRA dissidents oppose the accord completely because it doesn't come close to
achieving the IRA's traditional goal -- the abolition of Northern Ireland as a
Protestant-majority state linked with Britain. Voters in both parts of Ireland
backed the peace accord in referendums.
</P>
<P>
	   The IRA, which started its violent campaign in 1970, called a cease-fire in
1997 after killing 1,800 people.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain's secretary of state for Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson, said
Sunday's attack was ``not just wrong. It is against the democratically expressed
wishes of the people. What can it possibly achieve?''
</P>
<P>
	   Northern Ireland's major Catholic-supported party, the moderate Social
Democratic and Labor Party, said the bomb was timed to build Protestant
suspicions of Sinn Fein at a critical moment.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is madness,'' said the SDLP's Sean Farren, minister of higher education
in the threatened Cabinet. ``It has no purpose but to drive people apart. Given
the looming crisis, the attack was clearly calculated to exploit the
situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 0245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
