<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Proposed 2001 Budget  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Highlights of the 2001 budget that President Clinton sent to Congress today:
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   SPENDING
</P>
<P>
	   --The president's $1.84 trillion proposal would be 2.5 percent more than the
$1.79 trillion to be spent this year.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   TAXES
</P>
<P>
	   --Clinton would cut taxes by $351 billion over 10 years, largely for low-
and middle-income Americans. It includes establishment of government-subsidized
retirement savings accounts; alleviation of the ``marriage penalty'' that forces
many married couples to pay higher taxes; expanding the earned-income tax credit
for the working poor; a deduction for up to $10,000 in college expenses; and a
$3,000 tax credit for long-term health care. To defray the cost, he would raise
other levies by $100 billion, including a 25-cent-a-pack boost in cigarette
taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   SURPLUS
</P>
<P>
	   --Clinton's package projects a $746 billion federal surplus over the next
decade. Social Security would run surpluses of its own totaling $2.17 trillion
over 10 years, bringing the total estimated surplus to $2.92 trillion.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   NATIONAL DEBT
</P>
<P>
	   --Clinton seeks to eliminate the publicly held $3.7 trillion portion of the
$5.7 trillion national debt by 2013. The remaining $2 trillion debt is money the
government owes its own Social Security and other trust funds.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   HEALTH CARE
</P>
<P>
	   --The president's budget proposes to spend $168 billion over 10 years to
create a prescription drug benefit for Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
	   --A proposed $277.5 billion Pentagon budget would give a high priority to
the modernization of weapons and better pay and benefits for men and women in
the armed services.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   AGRICULTURE
</P>
<P>
	   --The budget would provide $65 billion in the new year to pay for a range of
programs including farm subsidies, food stamps and food inspection. The
president is proposing a 20 percent increase in food-safety programs.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
	   --Clinton's budget would give a high priority to wiring schools for the
Internet, hiring more teachers, fixing crumbling schoolhouses and making college
more affordable.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   HEALTH INSURANCE
</P>
<P>
	   --The president expands insurance coverage to 5 million more Americans,
primarily by covering low-income parents whose children already are in the
program.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   GUN CONTROL
</P>
<P>
	   --``The largest gun enforcement initiative ever,'' providing funds to begin
hiring 500 new agents at the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and 1,000
new state and local gun prosecutors and for research into new ``smart-gun''
technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 0951 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Would Hike Taxes on Smoking  </HEADLINE>
   By CURT ANDERSON AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today proposed $181 billion in tax
increases over the next decade similar to those rejected by the Republican-led
Congress last year, including a 25-cent-a-pack cigarette tax increase and
attempts to curb abusive corporate tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
	   The revenue increase helps the president offset $351 billion in tax relief
already outlined by the White House, including $45 billion in relief from the
``marriage penalty,'' $54 billion for new retirement savings accounts, $32.7
billion in relief for the middle class from the alternative minimum tax, and
credits or deductions for child care, long-term health care, charitable giving,
college costs, school construction and inner-city development.
</P>
<P>
	   The tax increases mean Clinton would use less of the projected budget
surplus for tax cuts than either Republicans in Congress or the leading GOP
candidates for president. Clinton's net tax relief would be about $170 billion,
far less than the $483 billion over five years advocated by Texas Gov. George W.
Bush or the $237 billion proposed by Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans on Capitol Hill, meanwhile, are advancing pieces of the $792
billion tax cut vetoed last year by Clinton, starting this week with a House
plan to cut taxes for all married couples -- including those who now pay more
than if they were single -- that would cost $182 billion over 10 years. GOP
lawmakers are cool to any tax increases for an offset, arguing that taxpayers
deserve a return of a bigger chunk of the burgeoning surplus.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I guarantee that Republicans in Congress will strongly oppose the
president's $181 billion tax hike,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of
the House Ways and Means Committee. ``It is amazing to me that after all these
years, President Clinton still cannot resist his urge to raise taxes on the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
	   The proposed cigarette tax increase, which would raise nearly $66 billion
over 10 years, is less than half the 55-cent tax advocated by Clinton last year
and ignored by Congress. The total also includes proposed fines on tobacco
manufacturers of $3,000 for each teen-age smoker beginning in 2004 if the
national youth smoking rate isn't cut in half.
</P>
<P>
	   The president would raise nearly $23 billion by limiting many corporate tax
shelters, a thriving industry that costs the federal government billions of
dollars a year. Promoters of abusive shelters could be penalized with a 25
percent tax and the current penalty for corporate underreporting of income would
rise from 20 percent to 40 percent under Clinton's plan.
</P>
<P>
	   The budget also would impose new restrictions on corporations with dealings
in ``identified tax havens,'' usually foreign countries with a friendly or
nonexistent tax law, including new penalties on companies that fail to report
their business in those places.
</P>
<P>
	   Other revenue increases in the proposed budget include reinstatement of a
5-cent-a-barrel oil tax to help pay for spill cleanups, making trade
associations' investment income over $10,000 taxable and making now-exempt bingo
and keno winnings over $10,000 taxable at a 28 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
	   Major elements of the president's tax cuts include establishment of
government-subsidized retirement savings accounts and his own plan to alleviate
the marriage penalty. Others include expansion of the earned income tax credit
for the working poor, tax deductions for up to $10,000 in college expenses and a
$3,000 tax credit to help cover the cost of long-term care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 0958 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0055 </DOCNO>
