<HEADLINE> Dow Down 64.22; Nasdaq Up 0.63  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly lower at the start of trading today,
although technology stocks once again held up better than the broad market.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 64.22 at 10.899.58.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were narrowly mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 4.76 at 1,419.61, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 0.63 at
4,244.77.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow's weakness came from J.P. Morgan, down 1 7/16 at 117 11/16, and 3M,
down 1 13/16 at 87 1/4.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet there was little news to give the market direction today. Concerns that
interest rates will rise sharply this year continue to weigh on investors'
minds, but very little data on the economy's strength is due for release this
week.
</P>
<P>
	   Drug stocks were mostly higher after Pfizer and Warner-Lambert Co. resolved
their bruising three-month takeover battle. Pfizer will pay $90 billion in stock
to acquire Warner-Lambert, creating the world's second largest pharmaceutical
company.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer rose  3/4 to 36 1/2 and Warner-Lambert gained 2 7/16 to 97. American
Home Products, which had also conducted merger talks with Warner-Lambert, rose 2
11/16 to 48 3/16. The company will be paid $1.8 billion -- the largest breakup
fee in history -- to sever its contract with Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 135.93 million shares, well behind Friday's
early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was up 0.84 at 526.36.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.0 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.4 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down
0.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1028 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
