<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Slips 98; Nasdaq Gains 32  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell today, while technology shares pushed
modestly higher, helping the Nasdaq composite index extend its record high.
</P>
<P>
	   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was down
98.66 at 10.865.14.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were narrowly mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 5.80 at 1,418.57, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 32.13 at
4,276.27, edging past the record of 4,244.14 set Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a very fragmented market, and you can understand why," said Larry
Wachtel, market analyst at Prudential Securities. "The cyclicals have run out of
gas and tech remains all the rage."
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow's weakness came from General Electric, down 3 at 138 3/4, and 3M,
down 2 3/16 at 86 7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet there was little news to give the market direction today. Concerns that
interest rates will rise sharply this year continue to weigh on investors'
minds, but very little data on the economy's strength is due for release this
week.
</P>
<P>
	   The lingering nervousness sent investors toward the technology stocks that
have performed well so far this year, proving immune to concerns that rising
interest rates are especially damaging to high-growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   "When there's a dearth of news, investors are deciding to play what works,"
Wachtel said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cisco Systems rose 3 to 124 1/8, Applied Materials rose 2 7/16 to 147 13/16
and Apple Computer gained 2 1/8 to 110 1/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Drug stocks were mostly higher after Pfizer and Warner-Lambert Co. resolved
their bruising three-month takeover battle. Pfizer will pay $90 billion in stock
to acquire Warner-Lambert, creating the world's second largest pharmaceutical
company.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer rose  3/4 to 36 1/2 and Warner-Lambert gained 1 15/16 to 96 1/2.
American Home Products, which had also conducted merger talks with
Warner-Lambert, rose 2 1/16 to 47 9/16. The company will be paid $1.8 billion --
the largest breakup fee in history -- to sever its contract with Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 294.42 million shares, well behind Friday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was up 4.02 at 529.54.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
