<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mainly higher against other major
currencies in European trading today. Gold rose.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro was quoted at 97.78 cents in late European trading, up from 97.60
cents Friday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro traded at 97.80
cents.
</P>
<P>
	   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday, included 108.62
Japanese yen, up from 107.54; 1.6420 Swiss francs, up from 1.6066; 1.4446
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4106.
</P>
<P>
	   The British pound was quoted at $1.5922, up from $1.5899.
</P>
<P>
	   In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 108.80 yen, and the pound
was worth $1.5950.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro rates, the dollar is
worth 1.9998 German marks, down from 2.0031; 6.7071 French francs, down from
6.7174; 2.2533 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2567; 1,979.83 Italian lire, down
from 1,982.87.
</P>
<P>
	   Gold closed in London at $313.00 bid per troy ounce, up from $294.20 on
Friday. In Zurich the bid price was $312.70, up from $293.50. Hong Kong markets
were closed Monday for Chinese New Year.
</P>
<P>
	   Silver closed in London at $5.42 bid per troy ounce, up from $5.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
