<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Airways Reports Loss  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- British Airways reported Monday that its third-quarter pretax
loss narrowed to 60 million pounds ($97 million) from 75 million pounds ($121
million) a year earlier as the airline continued to be hurt by a glut of
low-cost fares in the market. The results were in line with expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   The company lost 2 million pounds ($3.2 million) in the quarter ended Dec.
31, compared to an operating profit of 92 million pounds ($148.7 million) a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   BA reported a loss per share of 6.6 pence, the same loss per share reported
in the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   Operating results continued to be hurt by excess seats in the industry,
which produced an abundance of low fares, the airline said. BA said it responded
by increasing the number of higher-paying premium passengers.
</P>
<P>
	   Premium traffic grew 6.8 percent and non-premium traffic fell by 2.8 percent
in the quarter. Thanks to the higher proportion of premium traffic, yields --
the average fare received for carrying a passenger one kilometer -- rose 3.2
percent compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
	   BA said increased demand by summer travelers should help fill seats in its
principal markets.
</P>
<P>
	   The airline is implementing various cost-cutting measures and innovations,
including the launch of a fourth class, to stem losses.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Europe's largest airline fell 13 pence to 296 pence ($4.76) in
trading Monday on the London Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1327 </TRAILER>
