<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Mainly Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- Most European bourses moved lower Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology shares were the exception, continuing to gain amid
Internet-related merger and acquisition news and speculation.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in countries that
joined the single currency, fell 5.25 points, or 1.2 percent, to 428.06. The Dow
Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 78.7 points, or 1.5 percent, to 5,041.1.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell 3.12 points,
or 0.8 percent, to 374.25, while the Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Index fell 44.5 points,
or 0.9 percent, to 4730.8.
</P>
<P>
	   In domestic markets, London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 1.1 percent to
6,118.6. Some investors blamed the losses on fears over the Bank of England's
expected quarter percentage point interest rate hike Thursday and caution about
the longer-term rate outlook.
</P>
<P>
	   Although a quarter-point hike is priced into the market, caution about the
longer-term rate outlook and concerns about the impact of a rising pound on
exporters is playing on investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
	   The pound's upward trend hit some major exporters. Construction firm Hanson
fell 27.5 pence, or 6.2 percent and steel maker Corus Group lost 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index fell 2.0 percent to 7,296.32, with Deutsche
Telekom down 5.6 percent. In Paris, the CAC-40 Index ended down 1.2 percent to
6,203.58, led by tobacco group Altadis and telecom giant Alcatel.
</P>
<P>
	   In Amsterdam, the AEX Index ended down 1.3 percent to 652.42 led by
heavyweight KPN, which for much of the day had been one of the shares keeping
the AEX in the black. KPN's shares closed down 1.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
