<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BB&AMP;T Buys Big West Virginia Bank  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- One Valley Bancorp, West Virginia's biggest bank
holding company, is being acquired by BB&AMP;T Corp. of North Carolina for $1.2
billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the deal announced Monday, One Valley with assets of $6.6 billion will
become part of BB&AMP;T which has $45.5 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
	   West Virginia's largest bank chain was founded in 1867 as Kanawha Valley
Bank by Col. William Dickinson, Jr. It now has nine affiliate banks and 124
branches, 76 of which are in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   One Valley chairman J. Holmes Morrison will continue as chairman of BB&AMP;T's
West Virginia operations and join the BB&AMP;T board.
</P>
<P>
	   BB&AMP;T, based in Winston-Salem, N.C., has been expanding rapidly, acquiring 40
banks and thrifts, 32 insurance agencies and 12 small finance companies in the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
	   It has more than 650 branch banks in North and South Carolina, Virginia,
Kentucky, Georgia, the District of Columbia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   BB&AMP;T said it will create a $10 million trust fund for charitable
contributions and economic development in the areas served by One Valley, more
than doubling a similar $4 million fund the West Virginia bank operates.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal, which is expected to be completed in the third quarter, has been
approved by both banks' boards but still must be approved by One Valley
shareholders and regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1435 </TRAILER>
