<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Dept. Spokesman Leaving Post  </HEADLINE>
   By BARRY SCHWEID AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- James P. Rubin, the voice of the State Department and a
trusted adviser to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, will leave April 1 and
be replaced by Richard Boucher, a spokesman for three of Albright's
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement Monday, Rubin gave no explanation why he was leaving his
State Department post or where he was going. Rubin, 39, is known worldwide
through television broadcast of daily department briefings and for being at
Albright's side during international trips.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin spoke with rare authority, having been close to Albright while she was
U.S. ambassador to the United Nations and then in her more than three years at
the State Department.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright said she asked Boucher to take over, citing ``a superb record of
government service.''
</P>
<P>
	   Boucher served as spokesman for former Secretaries James P. Baker III,
Lawrence Eagleburger and, briefly, Warren Christopher. He is a career foreign
service officer who was U.S. ambassador to Cyprus, consul general in Hong Kong
and, currently, coordinator for the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Department spokesman's job was relatively low key before the
popularity of cable television and instant communication. The spokesman would
hold daily briefings that were largely informal and provided reporters with such
basic information as the secretary's travel schedule.
</P>
<P>
	   The Iran hostage crisis, which began in 1979, changed that. Television
cameras were brought into the department briefing room, give-and-take with
reporters became more formal, and spokesmen became celebrities.
</P>
<P>
	   Last June, for instance, when Albright and her entourage toured a camp in
Macedonia for ethnic Albanians who fled Kosovo, hundreds of refugees pushed
against ropes and chanted, ``Rubin, Rubin.''
</P>
<P>
	   The spokesman drew far more attention, and touched off more commotion, than
Albright herself.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin's dark good looks and Armani suits contributed to his fame. So did his
marriage to Christiane Amanpour, a London-based reporter for CNN. They are
expecting their first child in a few months.
</P>
<P>
	   He previously worked at the private Arms Control Association, and for Sen.
Joseph R. Biden, Jr., D-Del., before joining Albright in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1508 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, Feb. 7, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer To Acquire Warner-Lambert
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer Inc. is buying Warner-Lambert Co. for $90
billion in stock after a three-month takeover battle. American Home
Products, which also wanted Warner-Lambert, will be paid $1.8
billion -- the largest breakup fee in history -- to sever its
contract with Warner-Lambert. American Home Products decided not to
wage a lengthy and expensive court battle to stop Pfizer, according
to a person involved in the deal. William C. Steere Jr., chairman
and chief executive of Pfizer, will retain those titles at the
combined company. Warner-Lambert's chairman and CEO Lodewijk J.R.
de Vink will leave the company after the deal closes, it was
announced. He stands to receive millions of dollars in
compensation. Pfizer is expected to cut hundreds of jobs, most of
them at Warner-Lambert. Warner-Lambert stock was up 2 3/16 at 96 3/4
in afternoon trading. Pfizer was up 15/16 at 36 11/16, and American
Home Products was up 1 15/16 at 47 7/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Dow Down 96.10; Nasdaq Up 20.48
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell today, while technology
shares pushed modestly higher, helping the Nasdaq composite index
extend its record high. Just before 3 p.m. EST, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 96.10 at 10,867.70. Broader stock
indicators were narrowly mixed, with the Nasdaq composite index up
20.48 at 4,264.62, edging past the record of 4,244.14 set Friday.
``It's a very fragmented market, and you can understand why,'' said
Larry Wachtel, market analyst at Prudential Securities. ``The
cyclicals have run out of gas and tech remains all the rage.''
</P>
