<HEADLINE> Historian: Smoke Risk Dangers Known  </HEADLINE>
    By CATHERINE WILSON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Smokers were exposed to significant news coverage about the
dangers of cigarettes and very little on the tobacco industry's view that those
risks were small, a historian testified Monday in a landmark smokers' trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Thomas DiBacco, a retired American University history professor from Palm
Beach, was the industry's opening witness.
</P>
<P>
	   He testified about his review of newspapers and magazines commonly read
since the 1950s by three smokers who filed the class-action lawsuit on behalf of
about 500,000 Florida smokers.
</P>
<P>
	   Focusing on throat cancer victim Frank Amodeo's preferred newspaper during
his early years, the Detroit Free Press, DiBacco said 94 percent of 556
smoking-related news stories focused on health risks.
</P>
<P>
	   Only 2 percent of the articles from 1950 to 1963 focused on the industry
playing down the risks of smoking, he said. DiBacco did not count cigarette
advertising during the period.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial is proceeding before the same jury that in July found the nation's
five largest cigarette makers produced a product that causes emphysema, lung
cancer and other illnesses. In this phase, the jury is hearing evidence to
determine damages.
</P>
<P>
	   The industry has warned that the jury might award a crippling verdict of
$300 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   DiBacco's testimony was intended to show jurors that smokers shouldn't be
compensated because they kept smoking in the face of bad medical news.
</P>
<P>
	   Stanley Rosenblatt, an attorney for smokers, tried to keep DiBacco off the
stand entirely, calling him "a totally created witness" with no expertise in
smoking, health or addiction.
</P>
<P>
	   But Philip Morris attorney Dan Webb said DiBacco is a necessary witness
because smokers have made an issue of whether the industry drowned out
anti-smoking messages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
