<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chemical Companies Announce Venture  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) -- Phillips Petroleum Co. and Chevron Corp. have
agreed to a 50/50 joint venture of their chemical businesses, creating a company
with assets of more than $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The as-yet-unamed petrochemicals company, which will be based in Houston,
will employ up to 6,000 people. As a result of the combination, 600 jobs cuts
will be made.
</P>
<P>
	   "Phillips and Chevron are strong companies with excellent chemicals assets
and a shared vision of growth for their chemicals businesses," said Jim Mulva,
chairman, president and chief executive officer of Phillips. "This joint venture
creates one of the world's leading chemicals producers, with a global market
presence, excellent growth prospects and a strong financial position."
</P>
<P>
	   San Francisco-based Chevron is the second-largest U.S. oil firm in terms of
revenue, while Phillips, based in Bartlesville, is the nation's eighth-largest
oil company.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim Gallogly, Phillips' vice president of chemicals, has been named
president and chief executive officer of the new company. Kent Potter, vice
president of finance for Chevron Overseas Petroleum Inc., will be chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
	   The new company will be one of the world's top five producers of olefins and
polyolefins, which are used in the manufacture of basic chemicals and plastics.
It also includes the companies' aromatics and styrene businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement does not include Chevron's Oronite additives business, which
develops, manufactures and markets fuel and lubricant additives.
</P>
<P>
	   Under terms of the agreement, the joint-venture company will arrange $1.6
billion of debt financing and will make one-time cash distributions of $800
million to each parent company.
</P>
<P>
	   The transaction is expected to close by midyear and is subject to final
approval by the companies' boards of directors and regulators.
</P>
<P>
	   Chevron employs 31,000 people worldwide and has about $40 billion in assets.
Chevron Chemical Co. produces commodity petrochemicals, plastics and additives
in nine U.S. states and in Brazil, France, Japan, Mexico, Saudi Arabia and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips had 15,900 employees and $15 billion of assets at the end of 1999.
Last month, Phillips announced a gas processing and marketing joint venture with
Duke Energy.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Chevron were unchanged at $78.56 1/4 in afternoon trading on the
New York Stock Exchange, while shares of Phillips were up $1 to $40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
