<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis of Clinton's Budget  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   An AP News Analysis
By DAVID ESPO Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- By contemporary historical standards, the first sentence
of President Clinton's final budget message is the most striking: The $1.84
trillion tax and spending plan ``is the fourth balanced budget of my
administration.''
</P>
<P>
	   That's more than all other presidents in the last half century combined
could claim, and it comes against a backdrop of divided government and
near-constant political bickering.
</P>
<P>
	   It also underscores how the budget debate has shifted in the last
half-decade.
</P>
<P>
	   In the days of government red ink -- five years ago -- any proposed tax cut
or spending increase would have meant a rise in the deficit.
</P>
<P>
	   But, as Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., pointed out Monday: ``We have come a long
way since 1992, when the deficit was $290 billion and headed up.''
</P>
<P>
	   On the key big issues this election year, the two parties are in rough
agreement on what is needed to sustain the current economic expansion. They
pledge jointly to keep the budget balanced and to set aside the entire Social
Security surplus to reduce the debt, with a goal of retiring it by the middle of
the next decade, and are likely to spend much of the year jockeying for the
political credit.
</P>
<P>
	   The rest of the debate revolves around allocation of the general government
surplus, the money that does not come from payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   On that, the argument is as strong as ever. Republicans favor bigger tax
cuts; the White House wants more spending.
</P>
<P>
	   ``How can we address the issue of tax fairness, when his budget does not
substantially ease the marriage penalty?'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``How can the `era of big government' be over, when his budget would create
close to $350 billion in new government programs?'' The quotation harks back to
Clinton's 1996 State of the Union promise to shrink the government.
</P>
<P>
	   Said Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., chairman of the Senate Budget Committee,
``The president is proposing the era of big government come back with a
vengeance. This is a document designed to help Al Gore win election.''
</P>
<P>
	   As usual, Clinton's proposal is well-stocked with politically potent
spending increases: a prescription drug benefit for the elderly, health
insurance for 5 million who now lack coverage, more money for Head Start and
money to help local school districts hire additional teachers. He wants to set
aside a portion of the surplus to lengthen Medicare's solvency.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton provides for tax cuts totaling $351 billion over 10 years, but that
is substantially offset by tax increases of $181 billion. The biggest single
item is a tax on cigarettes of 25 cents a pack.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let me be very clear,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey said in rapid
rebuttal: ``This Congress will not raise taxes.''
</P>
<P>
	   Nor will it agree to all the new spending the president wants.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House would like to be very clear, as well.
</P>
<P>
	   It won't accept a tax cut being readied for a vote by the House GOP
leadership that would ease the so-called marriage penalty by $182 billion over
10 years.
</P>
<P>
	   And at a weekend retreat in western Pennsylvania, there was general
agreement among the House GOP rank and file to hold spending on domestic
programs at current year's level, in the aggregate. It's not quite clear what
they mean by that, but it will certainly involve less spending than Clinton
favors.
</P>
<P>
	   By the time Congress adjourns for the elections this fall, a compromise will
be reached on spending and, given the swelling surplus, quite possibly on a tax
cut as well.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans intend to pass some sort of prescription drug benefit for the
elderly, although they prefer that it apply only to the less well-off.
</P>
<P>
	   The likelihood is the budget will be balanced, the Social Security surplus
left untouched and the nation's debt reduced by default as a result.
</P>
<P>
	   An entirely different situation than on the occasion of Clinton's first
budget eight years ago, when he said ``We can't keep on going the way we're
going.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- David Espo is AP's chief congressional correspondent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1513 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
