<DOCNO> APW20000207.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Impact on Americans  </HEADLINE>
   By DEB RIECHMANN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the sweetest economic time of his presidency, the
budget that President Clinton proposed Monday is like a 10 1/2 pound box of
candy filled with bite-sized goodies for young and old.
</P>
<P>
	   For children, there's more money to expand Head Start, renovate schools and
recruit more teachers. For parents, there's a tax deduction of up to $10,000 to
help pay college expenses. For grandparents, prescription drug benefits under
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
	   There are benefits for Americans without health insurance and tax breaks for
low-income and middle-class citizens. But there's also something bitter for
smokers to stomach -- a 25-cent increase in the federal tax charged on each
pack.
</P>
<P>
	   For fiscal 2001, Clinton proposed a $1.84 trillion budget -- 2.5 percent
higher than the budget currently running the nation. He wants to increase
spending on dozens of government programs, provide some tax relief and use
surpluses to pay off the publicly held national debt by 2013.
</P>
<P>
	   It's the rest of the surplus that Republicans and Democrats will be fighting
over on Capitol Hill. With voters to woo in the upcoming presidential and
congressional election, the surplus is like a pile of bonbons. And Republicans
have their own idea of who should savor them.
</P>
<P>
	   House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich, R-Ohio, criticized the
president's budget, saying it promises something for interest groups, large and
small. ``It's flavor of the day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Clinton said the nation is prosperous and can afford his budget
proposals.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is time to make the most of this moment of promise to extend prosperity
to all corners of our nation,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   For farmers, he plans $11 billion to enhance farm income when crop prices
are low. For members of the armed services, a 3.7 percent pay raise and more in
housing subsidies to cut out-of-pocket costs for those who live off the base. A
$3,000 tax credit is extended to help families that care for a disabled or
elderly relative. For couples, there's relief from the ``marriage penalty'' that
forces them to pay higher taxes than they would have if they remained single.
</P>
<P>
	   Many proposals are aimed at children and families.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton proposes expanding Head Start funding by $1 billion to add 70,000
more toddlers to the program, bringing the total to about 950,000. His budget
requests $1.3 billion to give loans and grants to school districts the need to
make essential repairs like fixing leaking roofs and plumbing, $75 million in
grants to recruit skilled teachers to high-poverty school districts and $1
billion for summer and after-school programs. To make college more affordable,
Clinton wants to expand tax credits for higher education and increase Pell
grants and other college aid.
</P>
<P>
	   For households struggling to make ends meet, there's an expanded earned
income tax credit to provide tax relief for 6.8 million working families.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton also wants to widen a health insurance program that serves 2 million
children. He wants to extend this coverage to more children and to pull their
parents and other low-income working adults into the program. And he wants to
let hundreds of thousands of Americans, aged 55 to 65, buy Medicare coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   In the budget's fine print, there's a $10 credit for people who file their
tax returns electronically. Holocaust reparations would be tax-exempt. Hollywood
movie shots of the Grand Canyon would cost more if Congress approves the
administration's plan to increase fees for making films, TV shows, sound tracks
and other productions on national lands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1513 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Satisfied With IMF Relations  </HEADLINE>
    By JOHN IAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia should not beg for international aid but it won't cut
off relations with foreign lenders, acting President Vladimir Putin said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Putin was speaking after Russia's main lender, the International Monetary
Fund, announced that it won't resume a $4.5 billion loan package to Russia until
it sees more progress on structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
	   "It would be wrong to sever our relations with international financial
organizations, but it would be wrong to beg. We are a big and self-sustaining
country," he said on Russia's ORT television.
</P>
<P>
	   Putin also said Russia needs to strengthen its economy to ensure that
prosperity isn't limited to a privileged few. But it was unclear how he would go
about doing so if elected president in March elections that he is widely
expected to win.
</P>
<P>
	   Russia's spurts of growth since the 1991 Soviet collapse mainly benefited
tycoons with close ties to the Kremlin, while millions of Russians sank into
poverty. Russian media say some of those tycoons may help fund Putin's
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Monday, Finance Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said his ministry must borrow
from the central bank to pay off foreign debts in March. Russia had hoped to use
the IMF loan to help pay off previous debt.
</P>
<P>
	   Russia is due to make about $3 billion in foreign debt payments in the first
quarter. Kasyanov said the Finance Ministry will borrow from the central bank
for its March debt payments, but wouldn't say how much.
</P>
<P>
	   Russia has been forced to borrow from the central bank for debt payments
before, though the practice reduces crucial hard currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
	   The amount to be borrowed from the central bank was agreed upon with IMF
experts who left Friday after spending two weeks in Moscow, Kasyanov said,
according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
	   "The exact amount will be determined closer to March," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kasyanov said Russia was satisfied with its relationship with the IMF
despite the frozen loan deal.
</P>
<P>
	   "The belief that our relations with the IMF are limited to squeezing money
from this organization wrongly reflects the goals of our cooperation," Kasyanov
said in a Russian television interview Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   The IMF froze disbursements of its loan for Russia last year, saying that
Russia's reform moves were insufficient.
</P>
<P>
	   No quick resumption of lending has been expected, and the fund reiterated in
a statement from its Moscow office this weekend that it's waiting for Russia to
fulfill key reforms.
</P>
<P>
	   Kasyanov met with Putin on Monday, and was instructed to work harder and
faster to put the country's banking system in order, Interfax said. Many banks
froze or collapsed after Russia's August 1998 financial meltdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1515 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mergers Benefit German Execs Little  </HEADLINE>
    By HANS GREIMEL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Mannesmann AG chief executive Klaus Esser managed
to seal a spectacular purchase price for his company, forcing Vodafone Airtouch
PLC to double its original offer to a record $180 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   But despite all the work Esser did in conducting the grueling negotiations
over the past several weeks, he will be leaving with what likely will be a very
modest severance package, underscoring just how little German executives have to
gain when merger offers come knocking at the door.
</P>
<P>
	   In contrast to the American model, where executives bail from their
companies with a golden parachute of stock options and cash bonuses, German
executives are hemmed in by a corporate culture that typically scoffs at stock
options and values the prestige of a top position more than the paycheck.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's the curse of being a German manager," said Rolf Gerner, an
acquisition analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin and Jenrette in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
	   "A person in Mr. Esser's position is clearly driven by motivations of
wanting to be independent and being seen as a smart manager, but not as someone
taking home 200,000 Deutsch marks ($100,000) or more," he said. "It's less
money-oriented than the Anglo-Saxon world."
</P>
<P>
	   The breakthrough deal was history's largest corporate merger and created the
world's fourth-most valuable company in terms of market value. By holding out
for nearly three months, Esser not only squeezed twice as much money out of
Vodafone as it initially offered, he managed to guarantee Mannesmann
shareholders a 49.5 percent stake in the merged company -- a sweetened offer up
from the original 47.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   "I hope the Mannesmann board looks after him because he has done a wonderful
job for shareholders," Vodafone chief executive Chris Gent said Friday after
clinching the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   In the freewheeling world of American-style capitalism, looking after
management often means loading them with stock options -- an offer to buy shares
at a fixed price.
</P>
<P>
	   If the company's stock rises, they can buy the shares and then sell them,
netting a quick profit.
</P>
<P>
	   When Vodafone bought out U.S.-based AirTouch Communications last year,
AirTouch chief Sam Ginn stepped out of the picture with roughly $150 million in
stock options, according to Vodafone spokesman Mike Caldwell. And even Vodafone
head Chris Gent has roughly 2.5 million stock options in Vodafone he can cash in
for a soft landing worth up to $2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the merger of American pharmaceutical companies Pfizer Inc. and
Warner-Lambert Co., announced Monday, Warner-Lambert chief executive, Lodewijk
J.R. de Vink, will leave the company with three years' salary and bonus, plus
stock options currently worth about $245 million.
</P>
<P>
	   But Esser won't be getting anything like that when he departs in five
months. Esser does not have any options, and Mannesmann would not comment on
whether he owned any shares. An earlier appeal by the CEO to link executive
bonuses to stock price was turned down, and whatever options might be worked
into his contract are thought by analysts to be meager.
</P>
<P>
	   In Germany, stock options are relatively unheard of -- and even discouraged
for fear they would tempt managers to sell out the company's long-term health
for short-term payoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a philosophical debate over whether it entices managers to hold on and
try to build the company, or cut a deal and sell out," Gerner said. "At least in
the American model, if they lose their job, they get something in return."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
