<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Slates $227.5 for Defense  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BRISCOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's last defense budget would provide
$277.5 billion to run the world's most powerful military, replacing outdated
weapons, developing a national missile defense and boosting military pay and
benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   While the total budget outlays for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1 would
match those expected for this year, the budget sports some big increases. Most
come in the purchase of military hardware including $4 billion for an aircraft
carrier. Some older systems get cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress is more likely to increase than cut the proposed budget. With
expected additions and military-related spending in other department's budgets,
total defense spending authority is projected at $305.4 billion for the year.
When inflation is discounted, real growth in defense budget authority is
expected to exceed 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pentagon said its spending plan protects Clinton's commitment to
preserve ``America's military excellence.''
</P>
<P>
	   Defense Secretary William Cohen, in a prepared statement, said the budget
lays out key building blocks to transform U.S. defense policy to meet modern
needs, ``but more hard work and tough choices are needed.'' These include
possible future rounds of base closures to further streamline the military,
Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Assuming presidential approval of a national missile defense system, the
budget proposes $1.9 billion for the plan being designed to defend all 50 states
against limited ballistic missile attack. An additional $2.6 billion is sought
for other missile programs.
</P>
<P>
	   The budget includes $4.8 billion that was added from previous planning for
operations in Bosnia and Kosovo and for expected higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
	   It proposes $60 billion for procurement, fulfilling a major military
planning goal to update its planes, ships and other equipment. Included are the
most current new systems like the V-22 tilt-rotor plane and the F-22 fighter as
well as upgrades to other planes, helicopters, ships and land vehicles.
</P>
<P>
	   For the Navy, it would build three Arleigh Burke class destroyers and a new
attack submarine in addition to the last of 10 Nimitz-class aircraft carriers.
</P>
<P>
	   It plans for a 3.7 percent military pay raise, increased health benefits and
$5 billion in additional housing subsidies for military men and women living off
base. Those personnel now pay 19 percent of housing costs, to be reduced to 15
percent next year and eliminated by 2005 under the administration plan. Earlier
proposals to increase health care benefits for military retirees were not
included in the budget, however.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
