<HEADLINE> Consumer Borrowing Up 9.7 Percent  </HEADLINE>
    By JEANNINE AVERSA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' borrowing leaped ahead in December led by
strong demand for loans for everything from autos and boats to education and
vacations.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumers' credit outstanding, excluding mortgage debt, advanced at a 9.7
percent annual rate in December to a seasonally adjusted $1.39 trillion, the
Federal Reserve said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   All told, consumers borrowed $11.2 billion more in December then during the
month before -- much more than the $7 billion gain many analysts were
forecasting.
</P>
<P>
	   In November, consumer debt rose at a 13.8 percent annual rate, slightly
stronger than the government previously estimated. Consumers borrowed $15.8
billion that month than in October, ringing up the largest monthly increase in
debt since 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   Demand for non-revolving loans, including loans for autos, mobile homes,
boats, trailers, education and vacations, in December rose at a 10.6 percent
annual rate, following a whopping 17.3 percent rate the month before.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumers also used their credits cards freely in December. Revolving credit
-- primarily credit cards revolving loans -- grew by a 8.4 percent annual rate,
down from a 9 percent rate in November.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Reserve bumped up interest rates by a quarter of a percentage
point last week, the fourth increase since June. The action made borrowing more
expensive for consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the three prior rate increases, the U.S. economy -- supported by
hardy consumer and business spending -- continues to barrel ahead. The economy
grew by a breakneck 5.8 percent annual rate in the last three months of 1999 and
by 4 percent for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
	   All that spending helped give the nation's retailers their strongest holiday
shopping season since 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   Americans continued their spending spree after Christmas, boosting retail
sales to surprisingly strong levels in January, the nation's retailers reported
last week. That helped stores finish their fiscal year with the biggest gains
since 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1533 </TRAILER>
