<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Mixed in T-Bill Sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury securities were
mixed in Monday's auction.
</P>
<P>
	   The Treasury Department sold $9 billion in three-month bills at a discount
rate of 5.545 percent, down from 5.560 percent last week. An additional $8
billion was sold in six-month bills at a rate of 5.770 percent, up from 5.705
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The three-month rate was the lowest since Jan. 24 when the bills sold for
5.385 percent. The six-month rate was the highest since May 1, 1995, when the
rate was 5.840.
</P>
<P>
	   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors -- 5.719
percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,859.80 and
6.042 percent for a six-month bill selling for $9,708.30.
</P>
<P>
	   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making changes in
adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 6.24 percent last week from 6.17 percent the
previous week.
</P>
</TEXT>
