<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumers See Some Telecom Changes  </HEADLINE>
   By KALPANA SRINIVASAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The revolution envisioned by a landmark
telecommunications law that held the promise of more choices and lower prices
for consumers remains a work in progress, with some Americans not yet enjoying
the fruits of greater competition and falling costs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My cable bill is outrageous! The rate has steadily increased with no
changes in service or quality,'' wrote Debbie Williams of Aloha, Oregon this
summer to a consumer group in Washington. Bob Palinchak of Cordova, Tenn.,
griped that an array of monthly charges has caused his phone bill to increase
even when he makes few calls.
</P>
<P>
	   Since the passage of the 1996 Telecommunications Act, cable rates have risen
three times faster than inflation and the regional Bell companies still claim 96
percent of local phone revenue.
</P>
<P>
	   But there are some signs of change: The number of Internet users has tripled
and wireless prices have plummeted in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The big picture is that the whole telecommunications and information
sectors of our economy are just booming,'' Federal Communications Commission
Chairman William Kennard said in an interview with The Associated Press. ``We've
really never seen anything like this in the history of communications in the
world where you have so much investment so quickly, a myriad of new services
being provided to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
	   The law, signed by President Clinton four years ago Tuesday, freed cable and
local and long-distance phone companies to enter each others' businesses. House
Commerce Committee Chairman Thomas Bliley, R-Va., one of the bill's co-authors,
said consumers are beginning to see choices in markets once controlled by
monopolies.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I would have liked to have seen it go quicker,'' Bliley said. But ``it's
coming.''
</P>
<P>
	   Fledgling businesses have spent billions of dollars to offer local phone and
data services to compete with the Baby Bells. AT&AMP;T has invested heavily in its
ambitious plan to use cable lines to deliver local phone service, while MCI
WorldCom and Sprint say their combined merger could enable then to reach local
customers through fixed wireless systems.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Bell companies and GTE still have the lion's share of the local
market.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is hardly full-fledged realistic competition,'' said Adam Thierer a
fellow in economic policy at Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank.
</P>
<P>
	   Regulators point to the success of wireless service in giving consumers more
options. Almost all Americans now have a choice of three or more wireless
providers, according to the FCC, and prices have steadily declined.
</P>
<P>
	   A plethora of new long-distance plans -- boasting rates as low as 5-cents a
minute -- have helped drop the price of state-to-state calls more than 2 percent
between the time before the act was passed and December 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   But consumer groups, in a scathing letter to President Clinton, said most
Americans are not benefitting from falling rates because of an extra $4 billion
a year in assorted charges now tagged on to their monthly phone bills. They also
warned that an unprecedented wave of communications mega-mergers set off by the
law has reduced consumer options.
</P>
<P>
	   New competition could come as the Bell companies aggressively seek
permission to offer long-distance in their territory. In one of the biggest
milestones since the act's passage, Bell Atlantic received FCC approval in
December to provide its local customers in New York with long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States Telecom Association, which represents local phone
companies, says the time is ripe for the FCC to remove regulatory hurdles
keeping its members out of voice and data long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All customers suffer as a result,'' said Roy Neel, president of the group
</P>
<P>
	   And consumers are still waiting to see lower cable TV rates. Lawmakers and
others hope that legislation passed last year allowing direct broadcast
satellite companies to beam local channels to their customers will help bolster
competition.
</P>
<P>
	   That could help drive down cable TV prices -- which have increased nearly 27
percent between the time right before the law was enacted until December 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Cable TV is one of the biggest black eyes for the 1996 act,'' said Gene
Kimmelman, co-director of the Washington office of Consumers Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1551 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Said Tilted Toward Gore  </HEADLINE>
   By SONYA ROSS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The budget that went to Congress on Monday is President
Clinton's, but Vice President Al Gore hopes to administer the plan that contains
at least a dozen of his own proposals. One Republican chairman grumbled that it
was designed ``to get Al Gore elected.''
</P>
<P>
	   In some instances, Clinton not only incorporated Gore's ideas, he left it to
the vice president to announce them over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House says Gore's extensive involvement in crafting the budget is
not unusual; he's done it for seven years. But this year Gore's role is far more
evident.
</P>
<P>
	   Even the title presents the budget as a ``Clinton-Gore administration''
document.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a document designed to help Al Gore win election,'' said Senate
Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M. His House counterpart, Rep. John
Kasich, R-Ohio, said the White House framed the budget to offer ``all things for
everyone they feel they will need to get Al Gore elected.''
</P>
<P>
	   The White House denied that Clinton tried to load the budget to Gore's
advantage, even while picturing him as a prominent player in putting it
together.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of the major proposals Clinton put forth are mirror images of Gore's
positions. For example, like Gore, the president is calling for health insurance
coverage for all children under 18 and offering some coverage to poor, working
parents. Clinton's plan to tighten gun laws includes large sections of Gore's
anticrime proposal, although he shied away from Gore's suggestion that photo
licenses be mandatory for handgun buyers. Clinton would make it optional.
</P>
<P>
	   James Thurber, political science professor at American University, said such
close mirroring in policies reflects not only Clinton's desire to see Gore
elected, but also the close relationship they enjoy.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As a result of that relationship, the president is going out of his way to
help the vice president,'' said Thurber, who is writing a book on Congress and
the presidency. ``It's a relationship that is of equal importance on both sides.
The president probably has suggestions for (Gore's) campaign, the vice president
is probably asking the president for help in certain areas.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore has advocated funding for social programs that run the gamut from AIDS
research to nursing homes to wetlands. He called for funds to preserve the house
where Martin Luther King Jr. was born, and proposed $1.3 billion to help farmers
with water conservation.
</P>
<P>
	   Outside of those proposals, Gore also manifested himself in a number of
small proposals, such as $30 million for training preschool teachers, $247
million for school safety, $211 million for transit systems in 12 urban areas;
and $4.8 million for preserving the camps where Japanese-Americans were interned
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
	   It's a different reality from when Ronald Reagan was the popular two-termer
in the White House and Vice President George Bush was the candidate, Thurber
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He wanted his vice president to be president, but he wasn't doing what
Clinton is doing in terms of all these budgetary items,'' Thurber said of
Reagan. ``It was very much a lame duck period for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1552 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
