<HEADLINE> Dry Weather Boosts Grains, Soybeans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures settled higher Monday on the
Chicago Board of Trade, buoyed by dry weather in key growing regions of both
North and South America.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybeans set the tone, rising early in the session after weekend rains in
Brazil were less than expected. Forecasts for more dryness the rest of this week
also helped prices, as did rumors of U.S. soybean sales to China.
</P>
<P>
	   Dryness in the U.S. winter wheat belt pushed wheat prices higher, as funds
jumped in to buy.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn settled higher amid generally bullish sentiments for that commodity.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery rose 1 3/4 cent to $2.58 3/4 a bushel; March corn
rose 1 3/4 cent to $2.21 1/2 a bushel; March oats rose  1/2 cent to $1.11 a
bushel; March soybeans rose 1 cent to $5.06 1/2 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef and pork futures finished mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   April live cattle rose .33 cent to 72.75 cents a pound; March feeder cattle
fell .03 cent to 84.82 cents a pound; April lean hogs rose .22 cent to 61.37
cents a pound; March pork bellies fell 1.45 cent to 90.12 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
