<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Seeks $150M To Fight Fraud  </HEADLINE>
    By MARCY GORDON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Securities and Exchange Commission, in an uphill
fight against burgeoning fraud over the Internet, is seeking $150 million for
enforcement work and investor education and another $15 million to pay its
attorneys and other professionals above government rates.
</P>
<P>
	   The market watchdog agency has lost 25 percent of its attorneys, accountants
and examiners in the past two years to lucrative jobs in private practice. For
lawyers, many of those jobs now have become even more seductive as big law firms
have offered huge pay raises to compete with high-tech companies providing
bigger salaries and juicy stock options.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposals sent to Congress on Monday are part of the SEC's $422.8
million budget request for fiscal 2001, up 12 percent from the current spending
level of $377 million for the 3,200-person agency.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC "has made great progress in fighting fraud on the Internet," said
Richard Walker, the agency's enforcement director. "Additional funds from
Congress will enable us to detect violations better and bring even more cases."
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC and state regulators are battling a new form of investment fraud
that has been proliferating in Internet junk mail, online newsletters,
electronic "chat rooms" and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
	   Because the Internet is everywhere, unscrupulous stock promoters anywhere in
the world can cloak themselves in anonymity and lure investors across the
country, who have lost millions in such schemes in recent years.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month, the SEC sued a man who calls himself Tokyo Joe -- a flamboyant,
self-proclaimed stock expert with a Web site and an investment club -- for
allegedly defrauding investors by failing to tell them he was selling the same
stocks he was advising them to buy.
</P>
<P>
	   Tokyo Joe's attorney has said he will contest the allegations in court.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the SEC's first enforcement action against a well-known Internet
guru, but it followed several nationwide "sweeps" by the agency against online
investment fraud involving relatively minor companies and individuals.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC is seeking new funds to add 15 people to its "Cyberforce" team, now
some 240 strong, which prowls the Internet on the lookout for investment scams
and other securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
	   While SEC fraud-fighters do conduct Internet surveillance, they don't have
the legal authority to go undercover online. Unlike the Justice Department, the
SEC cannot put anyone in jail; it can only file civil lawsuits against suspected
violators.
</P>
<P>
	   The SEC said Monday it also will continue to go after financial accounting
fraud by publicly traded companies. It has recently accused some corporations of
manipulating their earnings to meet Wall Street analysts' projections.
</P>
<P>
	   In September, the SEC accused 68 people and companies -- including Hall of
Fame quarterback and Atlanta businessman Fran Tarkenton -- of accounting fraud
in the first nationwide "sweep" against inflating earnings and other alleged
reporting misconduct.
</P>
<P>
	   The $15 million in "special pay" the SEC is seeking for attorneys,
accountants and examiners, a premium of about 10 percent over government rates,
would put the SEC employees closer to their counterparts at the federal bank
regulatory agencies.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress shot down in 1998 a proposal by SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt to pay
$7 million in bonuses, representing as much as 20 percent of salaries, to get
people to stay.
</P>
<P>
	   The steady drain of talent in recent years has included several high-level
SEC officials, including Richard Lindsey, the former director of market
regulation; former enforcement director William McLucas and his deputy, Colleen
Mahoney; ex-chief accountant Michael Sutton; Barry Barbash, formerly the top
official overseeing the mutual fund industry; and Brian Lane, former director of
the corporation finance division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1554 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
