<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phillips, Chevron Announce Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) -- Phillips Petroleum Co. and Chevron Corp. have
agreed to a 50/50 joint venture of their chemical businesses, creating a company
with assets of more than $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The yet-to-be-named petrochemicals company, which will be based in Houston,
will employ up to 6,000 people. As a result of the combination, 600 jobs will be
cut.
</P>
<P>
	   "Phillips and Chevron are strong companies with excellent chemicals assets
and a shared vision of growth for their chemicals businesses," said Jim Mulva,
chairman, president and chief executive officer of Phillips. "This joint venture
creates one of the world's leading chemicals producers, with a global market
presence, excellent growth prospects and a strong financial position."
</P>
<P>
	   San Francisco-based Chevron is the second-largest U.S. oil firm in terms of
revenue, while Phillips, based in Bartlesville, is the nation's eighth-largest
oil company.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim Gallogly, Phillips' vice president of chemicals, has been named
president and chief executive officer of the new company. Kent Potter, vice
president of finance for Chevron Overseas Petroleum Inc., will be chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
	   The new company will be one of the world's top five producers of olefins and
polyolefins, which are used in the manufacture of basic chemicals and plastics.
It also includes the companies' aromatics and styrene businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement does not include Chevron's Oronite additives business, which
develops, manufactures and markets fuel and lubricant additives.
</P>
<P>
	   Under terms of the agreement, the joint-venture company will arrange $1.6
billion of debt financing and will make one-time cash distributions of $800
million to each parent company.
</P>
<P>
	   The transaction is expected to close by midyear and is subject to final
approval by the companies' boards of directors and regulators.
</P>
<P>
	   Chevron employs 31,000 people worldwide and has about $40 billion in assets.
Chevron Chemical Co. produces commodity petrochemicals, plastics and additives
in nine U.S. states and in Brazil, France, Japan, Mexico, Saudi Arabia and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips had 15,900 employees and $15 billion of assets at the end of 1999.
Last month, Phillips announced a gas processing and marketing joint venture with
Duke Energy.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Chevron were up 50 cents at $79.06 1/4 in late afternoon trading
on the New York Stock Exchange, while shares of Phillips were up $1 at $40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1612 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Off 58.01; New Nasdaq High  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks diverged in familiar fashion today, with technology
shares leading the Nasdaq composite index higher for a sixth straight session
while blue-chip industrials slumped.
</P>
<P>
	   According to preliminary calculations, the Nasdaq rose 76.40 to 4,320.54,
coasting past its previous record of 4,244.14, set Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 58.01 to 10,905.79. Broader stock
indicators were narrowly mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq, dominated by technology stocks, has risen more than 5 percent so
far this year, while the blue-chip Dow industrial average has fallen more than 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a very fragmented market, and you can understand why," said Larry
Wachtel, market analyst at Prudential Securities. "The cyclicals have run out of
gas and tech remains all the rage."
</P>
<P>
	   General Electric and 3M contributed most to the Dow's decline. An overall
weakness in the Dow's industrial and financial components held the blue-chip
index lower despite a big gain by Hewlett-Packard, which rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
	   Gary Campbell, chief investment officer at The Commerce Funds in St. Louis,
said fears that interest rates will rise sharply this year are weighing heavily
on investors' minds, pressuring the vast majority of stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's going to be a much tougher year for the equity markets," he said.
"Many stocks have reached very, very high valuations, and rising interest rates
are going to make many investors wonder if they're worth their high prices."
</P>
<P>
	   Rising interest rates are generally bad for stocks because they cut into
corporate profits by making it more expensive to borrow money. Traditionally,
companies that place a high premium on growth are most vulnerable to higher
rates.
</P>
<P>
	   But so far this year, investors have determined that a handful of leading
technology companies are growing quickly enough to outrun interest rates. Cisco
Systems, Applied Materials and Apple Computer, strong performers in recent
weeks, all rose on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "When there's a dearth of news, investors are deciding to play what works,"
Wachtel said.
</P>
<P>
	   Drug stocks were mostly higher after Pfizer and Warner-Lambert Co. resolved
their bruising, three-month takeover battle. Pfizer will pay $90 billion in
stock to acquire Warner-Lambert, creating the world's second largest
pharmaceutical company.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer and Warner-Lambert both rose. American Home Products, which had also
conducted merger talks with Warner-Lambert, also advanced. The company will be
paid $1.8 billion -- the largest breakup fee in history -- to sever its contract
with Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
	   While shares of high-tech companies dominated buying on Wall Street,
investors received several reminders of the fragility of technology. Brokerage
Charles Schwab Corp. said clients experienced intermittent problems using the
company's Web site today.
</P>
<P>
	   Search engine provider Yahoo! said its Web site also experienced service
problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, technical problems related to a software upgrade forced the
Chicago Board Options Exchange to halt trading for about two and a half hours.
The Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange were unaffected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1626 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Dept. Spokesman Leaving Post  </HEADLINE>
   By BARRY SCHWEID AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- James P. Rubin, the voice of the State Department and a
trusted adviser to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, will leave in April
and be replaced by Richard Boucher, a spokesman for three of Albright's
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement Monday, Rubin gave no explanation why he was giving up the
spot that made him world famous, or what he would do next. But Albright
suggested that wife Christiane Amanpour's pregnancy may have something to do
with it.
</P>
<P>
	   Amanpour, a London-based reporter for CNN, is due to give birth in March.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I've just become a grandmother, and I can just tell you it's a lot easier
to be a grandmother than to become a father,'' Albright said. ``He has to get
ready for those duties.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Obviously, Mr. Rubin has been very important in everything that we've
done,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said that after a ``great run in government'' for seven years, and
four years on the staff of Sen. Joseph Biden, Jr., D-Del., he needed time to
decompress.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't know what I am going to do next except that I am going to help
Christiane take care of our baby in London,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At this stage in life, I am doing three stressful things -- going to a new
country where I only partly speak the language, leave my career and have a
baby,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin, 39, is known worldwide through television broadcasts of daily
department briefings and for being at Albright's side during international
trips.
</P>
<P>
	   He spoke with rare authority, having been close to Albright while she was
U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, where he was her spokesman, and then in
her more than three years at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright said she asked Boucher to take over, citing ``a superb record of
government service.''
</P>
<P>
	   Boucher served as spokesman for former Secretaries James P. Baker III,
Lawrence Eagleburger and, briefly, Warren Christopher. He is a career foreign
service officer who was U.S. ambassador to Cyprus, consul general in Hong Kong
and, currently, coordinator for the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Department spokesman's job was relatively low key before the
popularity of cable television and instant communication. The spokesman would
hold daily briefings that were largely informal and provided reporters with such
basic information as the secretary's travel schedule.
</P>
<P>
	   The Iran hostage crisis, which began in 1979, changed that. Television
cameras were brought into the department briefing room, give-and-take with
reporters became more formal, and spokesmen became celebrities.
</P>
<P>
	   Last June, for instance, when Albright and her entourage toured a camp in
Macedonia for ethnic Albanians who fled Kosovo, hundreds of refugees pushed
against ropes and chanted, ``Rubin, Rubin.''
</P>
<P>
	   The spokesman drew far more attention, and touched off more commotion, than
Albright herself.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin's dark good looks and Armani suits contributed to his fame. So did his
marriage to Amanpour.
</P>
<P>
	   He worked at the private Arms Control Association, and for Biden before
joining Albright in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1633 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
