<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Penn St. Keeps Investments a Secret  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Student activists who want to peek at Penn
State's investment portfolio have gotten a message: It's none of your business.
</P>
<P>
	   School administrators say outside advisers manage the school's $800 million
portfolio. Releasing any more information would mislead or confuse students,
they say.
</P>
<P>
	   "In the morning, we could have money in a stock or company that somebody
doesn't like, and then the investment manager could sell that stock by
afternoon," said Daniel Sieminski, assistant vice president for finance and
business.
</P>
<P>
	   Some students are not satisfied with this, however.
</P>
<P>
	   "We want to know where the money's going," said Garrett Fitzgerald,
undergraduate student government president. "We want a full disclosure."
</P>
<P>
	   The student Senate voted 12-4 last week to ask university administrators to
open the books. The campus chapters of the American Civil Liberties Union,
Amnesty International and Eco-Action, an environmental defense group, back the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   "Penn State has an obligation to teach its students -- teach them in a lot
more ways than just inside the classroom," said Fitzgerald. "And if you invest
your money in ways that aren't positive and life-affirming, you're teaching that
it's OK, it doesn't matter if there is environmental pollution or human rights
abuses."
</P>
<P>
	   The student drive at Penn State is part of a nationwide effort to get
schools to invest their money in socially responsible ways. In the 1980s,
students opposed to apartheid in South Africa protested to stop their schools
from investing in companies that did business there.
</P>
<P>
	   Penn State, a quasi-public institution, opens its books to explain the use
of tuition money and state funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1646 </TRAILER>
