<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pfizer To Buy Warner-Lambert  </HEADLINE>
    By PHIL GALEWITZ and NOELLE KNOX AP Business Writers
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- After three bruising months of courtship, the world's two
fastest-growing large drug companies, Pfizer and Warner-Lambert, agreed to marry
Monday in a $92.3 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
	   The daunting challenge for executives of both companies is to put aside
their nasty accusations and lawsuits and unite their research, sales and
manufacturing efforts to make the Pfizer takeover work.
</P>
<P>
	   The combined company, to be called Pfizer, will be the world's
second-largest drugmaker. But if the merger succeeds as analysts expect, it is
expected to vault to No. 1 within two years.
</P>
<P>
	   For consumers, the gargantuan merger will have little short-term impact. The
new Pfizer will control less than 7 percent of the world market for prescription
drugs. But the companies contend that by combining they will be able to more
effectively develop new medicines and help hold down business expenses.
</P>
<P>
	   "We predict the integration will go very smoothly," said William C. Steere
Jr., Pfizer's chairman and chief executive, who will lead the business with
annual sales of $28 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   One reason for that rosy outlook is that Warner-Lambert Chairman and CEO
Lodewijk J.R. de Vink is stepping aside once the merger is completed this
summer.
</P>
<P>
	   "The fact that de Vink will not be staying will be sufficient to clear the
air,"said Dr. Joseph Zammit-Lucia, president of London-based Cambridge Pharma
Consultancy.
</P>
<P>
	   De Vink last November agreed to a takeover by American Home Products, saying
AHP's pipeline of new products was more impressive than Pfizer's. De Vink was to
be the top executive of the combined American Home-Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
	   No sooner had the deal with AHP been announced than Pfizer launched its own
hostile offer and Steere accused Warner-Lambert of failing to give Pfizer a
chance to bid.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner-Lambert responded by seeking to terminate Pfizer's rights to
co-market and share profits from the blockbuster cholesterol-lowering drug
Lipitor.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's all behind us," Steere said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Added de Vink, "In any negotiation of this magnitude, you are going to have
tensions, and the most important thing is you look forward."
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer won by upping the ante, offering 2.75 shares of its stock for each
Warner-Lambert share, a deal valuing Warner-Lambert at $100.89 a share.
</P>
<P>
	   In trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Warner-Lambert rose $2.56
1/4 to $97.12 1/2, Pfizer rose 93 3/4 cents to $36.68 3/4 and American Home
gained $2.50 to $48.
</P>
<P>
	   Before moving forward, Warner-Lambert will pay American Home $1.8 billion --
the largest breakup fee in history. American Home will use the money and cash
from selling its struggling agriculture business to pay the legal bills from
health claims from consumers who used its former diet drugs, and make itself
more attractive for another suitor.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer's first step with Warner-Lambert will be to identify $1.6 billion in
cost cuts to be taken by 2002. A big chunk of that is expected to come from
layoffs as the companies move to combine administrative and manufacturing
forces.
</P>
<P>
	   "Obviously, there is going to be a certain amount of discomfort when there
is change like this," de Vink said. Referring to the 4 percent unemployment rate
that is the lowest in 30 years, he added, that "it's a good market for finding
other jobs."
</P>
<P>
	   Wall Street analysts say the new company will be the fastest-growing large
drug company for at least the next several years.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer, fueled by strong sales of its blood pressure medicine Norvasc and
impotence-treatment pill Viagra, had been among the best-performing drug
companies in the last few years. But analysts said Pfizer had too few
blockbuster drugs in its pipeline to keep its growth rate going.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner-Lambert's fast growth has been spurred by Lipitor, which had $5
billion in sales last year. But even though Lipitor will soon be the world's
top-selling drug, analysts worried that Warner-Lambert was growing too dependent
on it.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer's earnings were expected to grow at about 20 percent this year, but
with the acquisition of Warner-Lambert it expects to accelerate to average 25
percent growth over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
	   In comparison, analysts expect annual earnings to growth around 15 percent
for top U.S. drugmakers Merck &AMP; Co and Bristol-Myers-Squibb.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer, which had been the world's fourth-largest drugmaker, will now be
second behind Glaxo SmithKline, which is being formed by the proposed merger of
British firms Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline Beecham.
</P>
<P>
	   Because Pfizer is growing considerably faster than Glaxo, analysts expect
Pfizer to take over the No. 1 spot by 2002.
</P>
<P>
	   "The combined firms can grow much faster together than on their own," said
Bob Kirby, an analyst with Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
	   In co-marketing Lipitor, the two companies showed Wall Street they can get
along, and that should help smooth over wrinkles left from the fierce takeover
battle.
</P>
<P>
	   "Given that it's a hostile takeover, it should go as smoothly as one can
expect, given the relationship the companies have had for three years in terms
of Lipitor." Leonard Yaffe, Banc of America Securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
