<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Head Eyes Wiranto Pardon  </HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANT BRAND Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid said Monday
that he would pardon Gen. Wiranto if the former army chief is found guilty of
war crimes in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I will pardon him,'' Wahid said while in Brussels as part of a European
tour. ``For the past several years we have been good friends, despite whatever
he has done in the past.''
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid also rejected rumors that Wiranto and other generals in Jakarta are
plotting a coup.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He protected me when I was persecuted by the last government,'' Wahid
said. ``I know him. I know he would not do such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, Wahid called for Wiranto to step down from his current Cabinet
post and threatened to fire him in response to a government investigation that
held Wiranto responsible for the tragedy in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
	   The territory was torched and looted and some residents were killed after it
voted for independence from Indonesia last year. Wiranto, who is now the
nation's security minister, was the army chief at the time.
</P>
<P>
	   The United Nations last week said in a report that the Indonesian army was
responsible for the crackdown and called for an international tribunal to look
into war crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid reiterated Monday that it would be better for Wiranto to step down
from his Cabinet post until he is cleared of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, he appeared to be softening his stance toward the general. Even
before Monday's comments, he had offered qualified praise for Wiranto's
character and had said Wiranto saved him from an army assassination plot in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is better for him to resign now,'' he said Monday. ``I respect him and
will continue to communicate with him whether he resigns or not.''
</P>
<P>
	   Despite Wahid's comments, it appeared tension between him and the Indonesian
military would continue in the wake of his allegations about an assassination
plot.
</P>
<P>
	   In a stopover in Rome this weekend, Wahid said Wiranto tipped him off about
the mid-1990s plot aimed at him and Megawati Sukarnoputri, who is now his vice
president. Wahid recounted how Wiranto told him that the army had been ordered
``eliminate'' him and Megawati. At the time, both were high-profile critics of
Suharto, Indonesia's former authoritarian leader.
</P>
<P>
	   Wiranto told him the order to kill had been conveyed by then-armed forces
commander Feisal Tanjung, Wahid stated.
</P>
<P>
	   Tanjung denied the story, describing Wahid's accusations as ``abnormal and
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
	   Monday was the last day of Wahid's 16-day European tour. While in Brussels,
he met with European Union Commission President Romano Prodi to discuss future
cooperation and a possible EU aid package for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
	   Wahid stressed to officials that a new political system was being set up in
Indonesia. He said he would open a ``new dialogue'' between the Muslim and
Christian communities in his country to try and create a secular society.
</P>
<P>
	   Several parts of Indonesia have been marred in recent years by sectarian
violence that has claimed thousands of lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
