<DOCNO> APW20000207.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police: Gifted artist, musician and wrestler also a murderer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Thomas G. Nelford left southern California for faraway
Columbia University a wrestling star, a gifted musician and artist. But the
23-year-old's life began a downward spiral at the Ivy League school that may
have led to the murder of his girlfriend and his suicide beneath a subway train.
<P>
	   Nelford dropped out of Columbia in 1998 and freeloaded at a fraternity house
before his drug use got him kicked out. No one on Monday seemed to know why
Nelford turned to drugs and left school. Or why he may have slain his
19-year-old girlfriend, lacrosse star Kathleen Roskot from Bayshore, Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
	   Police are investigating whether Nelford's motive may have been anger
because Roskot wanted to break up with him.
</P>
<P>
	   Roskot's throat was slashed, and she was found naked Saturday afternoon on
the floor of her bedroom, a literary journal with a picture of the beatnik
author Jack Kerouac covering her face.
</P>
<P>
	   The placement of the journal may not have been a coincidence. Stark
similarities existed in Nelford's life and that of Kerouac, author of the 1950s
classic "On the Road."
</P>
<P>
	   Kerouac, who coined the term "Beat Generation" for himself and his starving
fellow writers Allen Ginsberg and William Burroughs, was a high school football
star and won a scholarship to Columbia. But things at the Ivy League school
began to go wrong after Kerouac got into a fight with his coach, who refused to
let him play, according to biographies of the writer.
</P>
<P>
	   At about the same time, Kerouac's father lost his business and began
drinking heavily. A disillusioned Kerouac dropped out of Columbia. He began
hanging around New York with a crowd his parents disapproved of: Ginsberg and
company.
</P>
<P>
	   There are other similarities, as well. Kerouac, who died in 1969, also spent
time in California, where he turned to Buddhism and drank himself into oblivion.
According to one biography, "he was cracking up," an experience he recounted in
his last successful novel, "Big Sur."
</P>
<P>
	   And there's more: Kerouac's parents lived on Long Island as did Roskot's,
and through his first 40 years, he had failed to sustain a long-term romantic
relationship, although he often fell in love.
</P>
<P>
	   Friends in Oxnard, Calif., and at Columbia said they were stunned by the
news of Nelford's actions.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Columbia student Betty Lai said Nelford would often walk her and
other women home at night, so they would be safe.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was the sweetest boy," Lai said. "But I guess he was also a murderer."
</P>
<P>
	   "I trusted him around my family, my children," Todd Stoke, Nelford's
wrestling coach at Rio Mesa High School, said in several newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
	   Stoke did not return telephone calls for comment Monday. A woman who
answered the Nelfords' telephone Monday said the family did not wish to comment.
The New York Times quoted Nelford's mother, Carolyn, as saying reports her son
was a drug user were "very cruel."
</P>
<P>
	   But several students at the Beta Theta Pi fraternity house, where Nelford
once lived, said his drug use was frequent. Fraternity president Rich Luthmann
said Nelford often did drugs out in the open, prompting the other members to
throw him out.
</P>
<P>
	   Other students said Nelford acted strangely and knew local homeless people
by name.
</P>
<P>
	   "We called him 'Weird Tom,"' said Corey Barnes, who lives next door to the
Beta Theta Pi fraternity house. "He seemed like a weird, crazy guy."
</P>
<P>
	   Hours after he allegedly killed Roskot, Nelford committed suicide by jumping
in front of a No. 1 train on West 181st Street. Investigators said he was
carrying Roskot's wallet when found.
</P>
<P>
	   The medical examiner confirmed Monday that Roskot's death was a homicide and
Nelford's a suicide. Nelford's violent end was very much in contrast to the
young man people knew in Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was the kind of guy you thought would do something good for himself,"
Andrew Ferrari, 23, told the Daily News of Los Angeles. Ferrari was on the
wrestling team with Nelford for three years.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's a good friend, a great wrestler and had a real promising outlook,"
Ferrari said. "Ever since I've known him, he's been a real nice guy. I never
expected anything like this."
</P>
<P>
	   At the end of last summer, Nelford was back in Oxnard, living in a van as he
wrote songs and dreamed of a music career, Luciano Basua Jr., 26, told the Daily
News.
</P>
<P>
	   "He told me he was writing a lot of songs and that a record producer had
taken an interest in his music," Basua said.
</P>
<P>
	   Nelford was also a gifted artist and had drawn a mural for the high school.
But he was best known for his wrestling prowess. In a 1994 article, the Los
Angeles Times described him as "arguably the best wrestler in Ventura County."
And Nelford was named "athlete of the year" in 1995 by his school. That same
year, he came in fourth in the 152-pound category in the state wrestling
tournament.
</P>
<P>
	   It's those memories that Stoke, Nelford's wrestling coach, still holds dear.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not trying to say Tommy's an angel who dropped directly from heaven,
but this was a good, very popular, well-liked young man who, around here, people
thought the world of," Stoke said. "I love Tommy."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
