<HEADLINE> Congress Staffer on Game Show  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Turns out congressional staffers want to be millionaires,
too.
</P>
<P>
	   Press secretary Matt Phillips was a contestant Sunday on the quiz show ``Who
Wants to be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
	   One question that almost tripped him up was naming the national park where
Old Faithful is located. His boss, Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif., serves on the
Government Reform Committee rather than Resources. But the audience helped
Phillips correctly pick Yellowstone over Yosemite.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't get to go to too many national parks,'' Phillips, 26, of
Washington, said in an interview from his office Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Another question rewarded his reading, by listing four governors in order
from east to west based on their states. The answer was George Pataki of New
York, George Ryan of Illinois, Jesse Ventura of Minnesota and Gary Locke of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I couldn't believe my luck, working in Congress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips is again on the show Tuesday, when he'll try to build on the $2,000
he won on his first episode. But he isn't telling what happens on the show,
which was taped Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Perhaps a clue was that he was still at work Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
