<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP: Clinton Budget 'DOA'  </HEADLINE>
   By JANELLE CARTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- So much for an acrimony-free final year. Congressional
Republicans on Monday greeted President Clinton's $1.84 trillion farewell budget
proposal with open scorn, declaring it a ``lame duck spending spree'' that was
headed for a quick burial.
</P>
<P>
	   Top Republicans ripped into Clinton's budget, saying it was an election-year
return to the era of ``big government'' the president had supposedly disavowed.
Even though Republicans too no longer abide by spending caps put in place in
1997, many complained about Clinton's ignoring spending limits.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The President didn't just blow the caps -- he blew all commitment to
fiscal restraint and sanity,'' said House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill
Young, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans were of one voice in concluding that the budget proposal went
way too far in devising new ways to spend federal money, didn't go nearly far
enough in providing tax relief and was headed for a dead end in suggesting ways
to increase tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
	   House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas called the plan ``a spending
smorgasbord full of special interest handouts.''
</P>
<P>
	   And Rep. George Radanovich, R-Calif., called Clinton's proposal a ``lame
duck spending spree by Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
	   House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich, R-Ohio, was even blunter. ``His
budget will be dead on arrival. Instead of looking for ways to create new
government programs we should focus on ways to make them work better by rooting
out growing waste, fraud and abuse.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's budget proposal for fiscal 2001 is 2.5 percent more than this
year's $1.79 trillion budget.
</P>
<P>
	   The president has proposed $351 billion in targeted tax cuts to help low-
and moderate-income taxpayers pay for college, care for sick relatives and save
for retirement -- far less than what Republicans envision. Clinton aims to
defray those tax cuts with $181 billion in tax increases, including a proposed
25-cent-per- pack boost in cigarette taxes and $96 billion in corporate loophole
closers that Congress has rejected in the past.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let me be very clear -- this Congress will not raise taxes,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
	   House Speaker Dennis Hastert said the budget was a ``paradox.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``How can we pay down the debt with a budget that substantially expands the
size and scope of the federal government?'' he asked. ``How can the era of big
government be over when his budget would create close to $350 billion in new
government programs?''
</P>
<P>
	   At least one Republican saw the possibility for compromise. ``There's no
question that common ground exists between us,'' said Senate Finance Committee
Chairman William V. Roth, R-Del. ``I hope this year we can build on this common
ground and not miss the opportunities before us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
