<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Proposes Health Investments  </HEADLINE>
   By ALICE ANN LOVE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Proposing the biggest increase in government spending on
health care since the 1960s, President Clinton asked Congress on Monday for $195
billion over the next decade for new Medicare prescription benefits. For younger
Americans without health insurance, he wants another $110 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton cited rising government surplus projections in boosting by $77
billion the administration's previous request for cash to improve prescription
coverage for the elderly, even though congressional Republicans rejected last
year's more modest version as too expensive.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the new money, $35 billion would go to create a reserve account for sick
retirees whose very high drug bills would barely be dented by the limited
Medicare coverage the administration previously proposed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Some seniors have absolutely enormous bills that they have no way of
paying,'' Clinton said. He offered no details about how the catastrophic
coverage would work, saying he would try to work it out with Congress'
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
	   GOP leaders continued Monday to question the wisdom of adding a new benefit
to Medicare, which is financially unprepared for the baby boomers' retirement.
But they held out the possibility of compromise.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In this case, the president deserves credit for including Medicare and
prescription drugs on his canvas, but his picture needs revision,'' said Sen.
Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa, chairman of the Senate Committee on Aging.
</P>
<P>
	   Many Republicans would prefer to target help to low-income senior citizens
through tax credits or state block grants or to increase opportunities for
Medicare beneficiaries to enroll in HMOs that cover drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's plan would create an optional Medicare drug benefit in 2002,
covering half of retirees' prescription costs up to a $1,000 cap. Those
participating would pay a $26-a-month premium.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, for younger Americans, Clinton wants to make health insurance
more accessible through new spending on existing state and federal programs, as
well as tax credits to defray the cost of private coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   Together, his initiatives for the young and old would require the biggest
government commitment to health-care spending since Medicare -- now a
$220-billion-a-year program -- was created in 1965.
</P>
<P>
	   Some Republican lawmakers said Clinton seemed to be laying out a Democratic
campaign platform for the fall elections rather than a realistic budget with a
chance of passing Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, chairman of the House Republican Conference,
said progress is possible only ``if President Clinton and House Democrats put
aside election-year politics.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton was in part responsible for the death of some health care proposals
similar to his when he vetoed a broader Republican tax-cut package last year.
</P>
<P>
	   To help the nation's 44 million uninsured, Republicans and some moderate
Democrats support a $70 billion plan for a standard health insurance tax credit
for individuals and families not covered by employers or public assistance
programs -- about 27 million people.
</P>
<P>
	   Among Clinton's competing proposals is $76 billion over 10 years to extend
coverage to 4 million parents of children eligible for state-run Medicaid and
Child Health Insurance Programs, known as CHIPs. He is also asking for an
additional $13.6 billion to get more children enrolled in CHIPs.
</P>
<P>
	   The president wants to give states authority and money to expand Medicaid
coverage for pregnant women and children who are legal immigrants as well as
people who leave welfare rolls for jobs without benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   He would give tax credits to Americans who want to buy insurance from a
previous employer under existing COBRA laws and those caring for an elderly or
disabled relative at home.
</P>
<P>
	   And for the third year running, Clinton will ask Congress to let people aged
55 to 64 who lack health insurance buy into Medicare, now limited to those 65
and older.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1728 </TRAILER>
