<P>
	   Pfizer To Acquire Warner-Lambert
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Pfizer, Warner-Lmbert and American Home Products
stocks all were higher today after Pfizer won a battle to get
Warner-Lambert. American Home Products will benefit to the tune of
$1.8 billion -- the largest breakup fee in history -- for severing
its contract with Warner-Lambert. Pfizer stock was up 15/16 at 36
11/16; Warner-Lambert was up 2 9/17 at 97 1/8, and American Home
Products gained 2 1/2 to 48. The combined company, to be called
Pfizer, will be the world's second-largest drugmaker. But if the
merger succeeds as analysts expect, the firm is expected to vault
to No. 1 within two years. For consumers, the gargantuan merger
will have little short-term impact. The new Pfizer will control
less than 7 percent of the world market for prescription drugs. But
the companies contend that by combining they will be able to more
effectively develop new medicines and help hold down business
expenses.
</P>
<P>
	   Yahoo! Suffers Breakdown
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc., which runs the most popular site
on the Internet, suffered technical problems today and its flagship
Web directory was inaccessible for much of the day. The company
said, ``We're working as quickly as possible to identify and
correct the situation.'' Yahoo said the problems began about 1:45
p.m. EST. The problem also apparently prevented customers from
accessing free e-mail accounts through the Web site, but it didn't
affect customers' home pages on Geocities, owned by Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
	   Lucent Acquires Ortel
</P>
<P>
	   MURRAY HILL, N.J. (AP) -- Lucent Technologies Inc. is paying
nearly $3 billion in stock to acquire Ortel Corp., a leading
developer of optical components used to upgrade cable TV networks
for Internet and telephone service. The deal announced today will
help Lucent, a leading developer of optical technology for
telephone networks, to meet demand for equipment that enables
high-volume, two-way communications over cable systems, which were
originally designed to broadcast TV programming in only one
direction. Shares of Lucent were at 56, down 1.
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips, Chevron Announce Deal
</P>
<P>
	   BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) -- Phillips Petroleum Co. and Chevron
Corp. have agreed to a 50/50 joint venture of their chemical
businesses, creating a company with assets of more than $6 billion.
The yet-to-be-named petrochemicals company, which will be based in
Houston, will employ up to 6,000 people. As a result of the
combination, 600 jobs will be cut. San Francisco-based Chevron is
the second-largest U.S. oil firm in terms of revenue, while
Phillips, based in Bartlesville, is the nation's eighth-largest oil
company.
</P>
<P>
	   British Airways Reports Loss
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- British Airways reported today that its
third-quarter pretax loss narrowed to 60 million pounds, or $95.5
million at current exchange rates, from 75 million pounds a year
earlier as the airline continued to be hurt by a glut of low-cost
fares in the market. The results were in line with expectations. On
the basis of operations, the company lost 2 million pounds ($3.2
million) in the quarter ended Dec. 31, compared to an operating
profit of 92 million pounds a year earlier. BA reported a loss per
share of 6.6 pence, the same loss per share reported a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   UPS Forms Subsidiary for E-Commerce
</P>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- United Parcel Service Inc. is creating a
subsidiary, UPS e-Ventures, to seek out new Internet-related
business opportunities. UPS e-Ventures will identify and bring to
market companies that will serve the needs of businesses that
operate on the Internet, UPS said today. Some will be UPS
subsidiaries, but others may be spun off as independent companies.
The first company to be developed by UPS e-Ventures will be UPS
e-Logistics, which will offer a package of services -- from
warehousing to customer service -- for small- and medium-size
companies that sell their products on the Web. UPS already offers
such services to its larger customers.
</P>
<P>
	   BB&AMP;T Buys Big West Virginia Bank
</P>
<P>
	   CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- One Valley Bancorp, West Virginia's
biggest bank holding company, is being acquired by BB&AMP;T Corp. of
North Carolina for $1.2 billion in stock. Under the deal announced
today, One Valley with assets of $6.6 billion will become part of
BB&AMP;T which has $45.5 billion in assets. West Virginia's largest
bank chain was founded in 1867 as Kanawha Valley Bank by Col.
William Dickinson, Jr. It now has nine affiliate banks and 124
branches, 76 of which are in West Virginia.
</P>
