<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez, Fellow Coup Leaders Feud  </HEADLINE>
   By BART JONES Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Three former officers who helped President Hugo
Chavez stage his famous 1992 coup attempt are lashing out at the president and
his inner circle, threatening to carve a division in Venezuela's leftist
governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
	   The ex-coup leaders last week used the eighth anniversary of their revolt to
publicly warn Chavez that his year-old government may be betraying the
revolutionary goals that prompted them to take up arms.
</P>
<P>
	   They offered details. But on Monday, retired Lt. Col. Francisco Arias
Cardenas, considered the intellectual author of the 1992 coup, said Chavez's
Fifth Republic Movement political party is in crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   ``An organization that doesn't allow contrary opinions, that doesn't debate,
that doesn't discuss, in my opinion doesn't exist,'' Arias, who is now governor
of oil-rich Zulia state, told the Globovision TV network.
</P>
<P>
	   Another former coup leader, retired Lt. Col. Jesus Urdaneta, called on
Chavez to fire two cabinet ministers and the head of the legislature. He claimed
they are leftovers from the corrupt oligarchy the former soldiers want to
destroy.
</P>
<P>
	   Government officials have shot back, fiercely criticizing the former coup
leaders and stirring the first major feud among Chavez forces. The spat has led
some to speculate that true opposition to Chavez may finally be emerging in the
South American nation.
</P>
<P>
	   Political analyst Anibal Romero said the conflict is partly about power,
since the three former coup leaders may feel sidelined in the Chavez
administration. Arias was passed over recently for vice president, and Urdaneta
was fired as head of the political police after he clashed with the foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
	   The feud could cause deep rifts in Chavez's governing coalition, especially
if the discontent spreads to the military. Yet Chavez also enjoys near-fanatical
support among millions of poor people and is the most famous of the former coup
leaders. Some say it's Chavez's personality, not his governing coalition, that
really matters in Venezuelan politics.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez hasn't commented directly on the feud, though on Friday he announced
he was retaking control of the Fifth Republic Movement after ``letting them do
what they want'' for the last year.
</P>
<P>
	   In an apparent attempt to ease tensions, Fifth Republic leaders announced
Monday that the third former coup leader, retired Lt. Col. Joel Acosta Chirinos,
was resigning as head of the organization but will be the party's candidate for
governor in Falcon state in western Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez spent two years in prison after the coup attempt and was swept to the
presidency in December 1998 on a wave of public anger over mass poverty and some
of the world's worst corruption. Since then, he has overhauled Venezuela's
government -- winning approval for a new constitution, increasing the power of
the presidency and ousting the old Congress and Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics say Chavez has concentrated power in his own hands and moved
Venezuela dangerously close to dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez's hodgepodge coalition is made up of former coup participants, the
military and leftist political parties with backing from Venezuela's poor
majority. The two traditional political parties that ruled the country during
four decades of democracy have all but disappeared, and some analysts had
predicted a viable political opposition would emerge from disenchanted Chavez
supporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1732 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis of Clinton's Budget  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   An AP News Analysis
By DAVID ESPO Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- By contemporary historical standards, the first sentence
of President Clinton's final budget message is the most striking: The $1.84
trillion tax and spending plan ``is the fourth balanced budget of my
administration.''
</P>
<P>
	   That's more than all other presidents in the last half century combined
could claim, and it comes against a backdrop of divided government and
near-constant political bickering.
</P>
<P>
	   It also underscores how the budget debate has shifted in the last
half-decade.
</P>
<P>
	   In the days of government red ink -- five years ago -- any proposed tax cut
or spending increase would have meant a rise in the deficit.
</P>
<P>
	   But, as Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., pointed out Monday: ``We have come a long
way since 1992, when the deficit was $290 billion and headed up.''
</P>
<P>
	   On the key big issues this election year, the two parties are in rough
agreement on what is needed to sustain the current economic expansion. They
pledge jointly to keep the budget balanced and to set aside the entire Social
Security surplus to reduce the debt, with a goal of retiring it by the middle of
the next decade, and are likely to spend much of the year jockeying for the
political credit.
</P>
<P>
	   The rest of the debate revolves around allocation of the general government
surplus, the money that does not come from payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   On that, the argument is as strong as ever. Republicans favor bigger tax
cuts; the White House wants more spending.
</P>
<P>
	   ``How can we address the issue of tax fairness, when his budget does not
substantially ease the marriage penalty?'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``How can the `era of big government' be over, when his budget would create
close to $350 billion in new government programs?'' The quotation harks back to
Clinton's 1996 State of the Union promise to shrink the government.
</P>
<P>
	   Said Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., chairman of the Senate Budget Committee,
``The president is proposing the era of big government come back with a
vengeance. This is a document designed to help Al Gore win election.''
</P>
<P>
	   As usual, Clinton's proposal is well-stocked with politically potent
spending increases: a prescription drug benefit for the elderly, health
insurance for 5 million who now lack coverage, more money for Head Start and
money to help local school districts hire additional teachers. He wants to set
aside a portion of the surplus to lengthen Medicare's solvency.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton provides for tax cuts totaling $351 billion over 10 years, but that
is substantially offset by tax increases of $181 billion. The biggest single
item is a tax on cigarettes of 25 cents a pack.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let me be very clear,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas said in
rapid rebuttal: ``This Congress will not raise taxes.''
</P>
<P>
	   Nor will it agree to all the new spending the president wants.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House would like to be very clear, as well.
</P>
<P>
	   It won't accept a tax cut being readied for a vote by the House GOP
leadership that would ease the so-called marriage penalty by $182 billion over
10 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Nor will House Democrats, mounting a strong effort to gain a majority in the
fall elections.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Republicans' mantra is massive tax cuts and not a penny for Social
Security and Medicare,'' charged House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt of
Missouri. ``As a result, they threaten the surplus before we can use it
responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
	   And at a weekend retreat in western Pennsylvania, there was general
agreement among the House GOP rank and file to hold spending on domestic
programs at current year's level, in the aggregate. It's not quite clear what
they mean by that, but it will certainly involve less spending than Clinton
favors.
</P>
<P>
	   By the time Congress adjourns for the elections this fall, a compromise will
be reached on spending and, given the swelling surplus, quite possibly on a tax
cut as well.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans intend to pass some sort of prescription drug benefit for the
elderly, although they prefer that it apply only to the less well-off.
</P>
<P>
	   The likelihood is the budget will be balanced, the Social Security surplus
left untouched and the nation's debt reduced by default as a result.
</P>
<P>
	   An entirely different situation than on the occasion of Clinton's first
budget eight years ago, when he said ``We can't keep on going the way we're
going.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- David Espo is AP's chief congressional correspondent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1733 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
