<HEADLINE> One dead, one wounded in Westchester Community College shooting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   VALHALLA, N.Y. (AP) - A man in the midst of a breakup with his
18-year-old girlfriend accosted her in a college hallway Monday, shot her in the
head as she tried to get away, then shot and killed himself as he ran off across
the snow-covered campus.
<P>
	   "His hand went up, then his head went back. He was still running, then he
fell," said Rayvon Miller of Greenburgh, a student who witnessed the suicide at
Westchester Community College.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting was the first in the 54-year history of the college, said
Julius Ford, vice president of student services.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not really what you expect when you go to school," said Louis Ramirez,
a student from the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
	   The woman, who lives in Mount Vernon but whose name was not made public, was
listed in critical condition at the Westchester Medical Center. Detective
William Rehm of the Westchester County police said, however, that her gunshot
wound - from a bullet that glanced off her temple - did not appear to be
life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
	   Rehm said the woman was in a first-floor hallway of the Academic Arts
building at about 12:15 p.m. when the man, identified only as a Yonkers man in
his 20s who was not a student, confronted her.
</P>
<P>
	   "There was on ongoing prior relationship," Rehm said. "We have reason to
believe that that relationship may have been terminated by one party or the
other."
</P>
<P>
	   They argued and she tried to leave, Rehm said, but he followed and "she
obviously felt threatened. ... She went for the first open door she came to."
</P>
<P>
	   Just as she was going through the door, the man grabbed her from behind and
fired one shot from a handgun. She fell into the room, where a staff member and
a student had been meeting, and they shut the door behind her. The bullet that
glanced off her head was found embedded in the door, Rehm said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Closing the door was good thinking on their part," the detective said. "It
ended the assault and forced the perpetrator to leave."
</P>
<P>
	   The attacker ran off along campus pathways and was near the school's
Classroom Building when he shot himself. Blood marked the snow where he fell,
the gun still in his hand.
</P>
<P>
	   Don Gregory, a journalism teacher who walked by the body soon after the
suicide, called the experience "surrealistic."
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a numbing sensation to see someone lying there. ... You feel despair
at not knowing what to do."
</P>
<P>
	   Ford said classes were not interrupted for the 20,500 students, but campus
exits were sealed for half an hour until police concluded that the dead man was
the only attacker.
</P>
<P>
	   The school offered a telephone hotline for worried parents and counseling
for any students troubled by the shootings.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford said the building where the first shooting occurred is patrolled by one
unarmed guard. The school will eventually review security, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
