<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Rally Fizzles; Cocoa Rises  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   A brief but explosive rally in gold fizzled out Monday when a major Canadian
mining company signaled caution about prices after they had reached a second
consecutive four-month high.
</P>
<P>
	   In other markets, heating oil and other energy futures sank as temperatures
in the Northeast rose, and cocoa bounced higher after hitting 27-year lows last
week.
</P>
<P>
	   Gold prices rocketed 8 percent higher Friday on a combination of factors,
including evidence of an overheating U.S. economy and the optimism shown by a
top producer in suspending its program for hedging, or betting on lower prices.
</P>
<P>
	   The furious rally continued early Monday on the Comex division of the New
York Mercantile Exchange, barreling upward another 4 percent to $326.90 an
ounce, the highest price since Oct. 7. The two-year high for gold, $339 last
Oct. 5, was in sight.
</P>
<P>
	   But investors' enthusiasm for the metal began waning at that lofty level,
and they went on a selling spree when the world's No. 4 gold producer announced
it was revising but not halting its gold sales and hedging program.
Toronto-based Barrick Gold Corp. had been widely expected to follow the lead set
last week by fellow Canadian producer Placer Dome Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   Gold for April delivery settled down $8.50 at $304.50 an ounce -- a 3
percent decline.
</P>
<P>
	   That's still 5 percent higher than it was before the flurry began last
Friday, and analysts are uncertain whether the higher level will hold.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think you'll see pullbacks to the mid-$290s," said Dave Meger, senior
metals analyst for Alaron Trading Corp. in Chicago. "But you can now see prices
averaging $300 an ounce without any problem. I think we'll settle between $300
and $310."
</P>
<P>
	   George Gero, first vice president for Prudential Securities, said the sharp
fallback Monday was disappointing but "at least it's off those doldrum lows" of
recent months.
</P>
<P>
	   "The jury's out on whether this was a turnaround in the market or once again
a short-term event," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Silver, following gold's lead, also came down sharply after an earlier
rally, with the March contract settling 30 cents lower at $5.28 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
	   Heating oil's hot winter run may be nearing an end after prices slid 4
percent on the New York Merc. Temperatures were above freezing Monday in much of
the U.S. Northeast, the world's top heating oil market, and are forecast to rise
higher in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   March heating oil fell 2.97 cents to 75.81 cents a gallon. March crude oil
dipped 1.3 percent, settling 37 cents lower at $28.45 a barrel, while March
unleaded gasoline fell 1.21 cent to 78.62 cents a gallon and March natural gas
plummeted 18 cents to $2.562 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
	   In London, March Brent crude from the North Sea fell 19 cents to $26.88 on
the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   Cocoa traders said prices for that commodity may finally have hit bottom.
West African crops are still coming in huge, but a U.S. forecast lowered the
estimate for production in Indonesia, the world's No. 3 producer.
</P>
<P>
	   May cocoa settled up $16 at $814 a ton on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa
Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1756 </TRAILER>
