<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman disavows Michael Francis despite his acquittal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The former chairman of the New Jersey Sports and
Exposition Authority may be exonerated of any crimes, but his former boss, Gov.
Christie Whitman, said Monday she is nonetheless glad to be rid of him.
<P>
	   Michael Francis was acquitted of charges last month that he had concealed
ties to a reputed mobster and tried to use those ties to win a contract for his
cleaning company from a mall in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman said Francis' nefarious ties may not have been enough to plant him
in jail "but those associations, that kind of business association, is just not
acceptable in government, as far as I'm concerned."
</P>
<P>
	   "The reasons, the ethical concerns that I had that led me to request his
stepping down as chairman of the Sports Authority were never in contention (in
his trial). Those exist," the governor said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Francis was a former Essex County GOP chairman, fund-raiser for the
governor's 1993 campaign, head of her inaugural party and her first Sports
Authority chairman.
</P>
<P>
	   Then in 1996 Whitman demanded his resignation, and in 1997 Francis was
indicted on charges that he concealed ties to Anthony Rizzo, a reputed leader in
the Genovese crime family who was convicted of criminal conspiracies in the
trash industry over the course of 15 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Evidently the trail got hot when investigators wiretapping Rizzo heard him
bragging about his friendship with Francis.
</P>
<P>
	   Various counts in Francis' indictment had to be redone because of defects,
other counts were thrown out along the way and finally on Jan. 20 a Superior
Court judge ended Francis' trial and dismissed the remaining charges because
prosecutors had failed to provide "a scintilla of evidence for the jury to
consider."
</P>
<P>
	   Francis said it "ends what has been a devastating and painful period in my
life."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman has repeatedly declined to comment on the Francis case because two
minor charges were still pending against him. Attorney General John Farmer
dropped those two weeks ago, so on Monday Whitman broke her silence.
</P>
<P>
	   "Let me just say that it was a very difficult time for me when I was first
made aware of his business associates, and I would say that I felt betrayed at
that time. If I had known about that prior to the appointment (to the Sports
Authority), I never would have offered him that position.
</P>
<P>
	   "And for me, that was difficult, because he did lay himself out for me (in
the 1993 campaign), he did a lot of fund raising, and I felt a great deal of
loyalty to him because of that," the governor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman said his ties to organized crime created an insurmountable ethical
smear, and she would never have accepted his help as a candidate had she any
inkling about them.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor said it was inappropriate for her to discuss prosecution
matters.
</P>
<P>
	   "The criminal procedure is the criminal procedure. Those charges were
brought, and the judge dismissed them. That's the way that goes," Whitman said.
"There are those who would argue there were things the jury was not allowed to
hear about some of the other issues, but I can't go into that."
</P>
<P>
	   But she also said the dismissals had no bearing on the ethical concerns,
which she said "were never in dispute" for an official "in a position where you
carry the trust in the name of the state of New Jersey with you as you do
business."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
