<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs Yen on Japan Outlook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar jumped against the yen Monday after a Japanese
official issued a gloomy assessment of that country's economic situation.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was quoted at 108.78 yen in late New York trading, well above its
level of 107.35 yen late Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the latest gain for the dollar against the yen as currency markets
reacted to continued signs of strength in the U.S. economy, higher short-term
interest rates and the absence of inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, the yen took a blow from statements by a senior Japanese
official in a television interview Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Taichi Sakaiya, the country's chief economic planner, said he expects to see
a "considerably large negative figure" when gross domestic product for the
October-December quarter is announced next month.
</P>
<P>
	   If the Japanese economy did shrink during the latest quarter, it would mark
the second consecutive quarter of contraction, meeting the textbook definition
of an economy in recession.
</P>
<P>
	   A separate survey showing a decline in Japanese business sentiment added to
the concerns about Japan's economy, which has been struggling to emerge from a
prolonged slowdown.
</P>
<P>
	   The survey by Japan's Economic Planning Agency found that business sentiment
worsened slightly in the October-December quarter on concern over Y2K computer
glitches.
</P>
<P>
	   In other trading, the euro was quoted at 98.00 cents, down from 98.29 cents
late Friday. The dollar also was quoted at 1.6387 Swiss francs, up from 1.6345,
and 1.4458 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4416. The British pound rose to $1.5964
from $1.5908.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. Based on Monday's
euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9952 German marks, up from 1.9899; 6.6917
French francs, up from 6.6737; and 1,975.28 Italian lire, up from 1,969.96.
</P>
</TEXT>
