<HEADLINE> Czech, U.S. Brewers Share Bud Name  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- The legal wrangling between Czech and U.S. brewers to use the
Budweiser brand name fizzled out Monday when the Court of Appeal announced its
ruling: This Bud's for both of you.
</P>
<P>
	   The court battle originated back in 1911 when the Czech brewery sought to
expand sales into the United States using the Bud name.
</P>
<P>
	   The fight resumed in the 1970s when both companies began marketing their
products in Britain. Another round of litigation was triggered later in the
decade when the Czech firm successfully applied to register Bud as a trademark.
</P>
<P>
	   But despite the "danger of confusion" facing the beer-drinking public, three
Court of Appeal judges ruled that the names Budweiser and Bud belonged to both
breweries.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bud name originally came from a town in Bohemia, which was part of the
Austro-Hungarian empire, called Budwis. Budejovicky Budvar is the successor of a
brewing firm established there in 1895.
</P>
<P>
	   St. Louis-based Anheuser-Busch Inc. set up its business in the United States
in the 19th century and began calling its beer Budweiser in 1875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
