<HEADLINE> GM Taps Cadillac Boss for Parts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. said Monday the head of the Cadillac
division has been tapped to run the company's parts operation.
</P>
<P>
	   John F. Smith will replace Bill Lovejoy, who was named to run GM's North
American Vehicle Sales, Service and Marketing division. Lovejoy is replacing Roy
Roberts, who will retire April 1.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith, no relation to GM Chairman Jack Smith, has been in charge of Cadillac
since 1997. He has been trying to turn around the luxury division, which lost
the crown of best-selling U.S. luxury brand in 1998 and 1999. Under Smith,
Cadillac developed its "art and science" design theme that should show up on
vehicles in 2002.
</P>
<P>
	   GM's parts operation employs about 12,000 people, and sells auto parts and
services under GM, ACDelco and Goodwrench brands.
</P>
<P>
	   GM did not say who would succeed Smith at Cadillac.
</P>
