<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, Russia OK Nuke Protection Plan  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration has agreed to give Russia an
additional $100 million to safeguard nuclear materials and conduct research in
return for Russia's promise to stop making plutonium from civilian reactor fuel.
</P>
<P>
	   Arms control advocates praised the agreement as a significant step toward
reducing the threat of nuclear proliferation and the first attempt to deal with
the huge volume of used fuel, and tons of weapons-grade plutonium, from Russia's
civilian reactors.
</P>
<P>
	   Some details of the agreement in principle remain to be worked out, and some
of the money for nuclear research is linked to Russia's ending its transfers of
nuclear technology to Iran, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson called the tentative agreement ``a very
exciting new initiative'' that will reduce the amount of Russian plutonium
exposed to potential theft or diversion.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress must approve the additional money, which was included in President
Clinton's fiscal year 2001 budget announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. officials estimate that Russia produces about 2 tons of plutonium a
year out of spent fuel from its 29 civilian reactors. It already has stockpiled
an estimated 30 tons of plutonium from the reactors.
</P>
<P>
	   While Russia has not promised to end reprocessing permanently, U.S.
officials said they hoped the moratorium would remain in effect for several
decades, giving time to develop a system to produce waste more difficult to
convert for weapons-making.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a good development. It doesn't solve the problem, but it's an
important step in the right direction,'' said Thomas Graham Jr., president of
the Lawyers Alliance for World Security, an arms control advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
	   Ernest Moniz, the undersecretary of energy who discussed the agreement with
Russian officials last week in Moscow, said, ``There is an agreement in
principle. We still have some work to do with regard to scope and scheduling''
and halt to reprocessing the civilian reactor waste.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the agreement, according to U.S. officials, the United States would
provide $45 million for more secure safeguarding of spent reactor fuel at Mayak,
a nuclear complex in the southern Urals, and $38 million to build a new dry-cask
storage facility for spent reactor fuel.
</P>
<P>
	   Another part of the accord calls for $25 million in long-term nuclear
research on a safer reactor and fuel cycle process. This money would be
contingent on an end to the Russian shipments to Iran.
</P>
<P>
	   Paul Leventhal, president of the Nuclear Control Institute, a private
advocacy group, called the agreement ``a major achievement for U.S.
negotiators.'' But he said Russia still appears intent on stockpiling civilian
plutonium as well as some of its surplus military plutonium for eventual use in
civilian reactors.
</P>
<P>
	   Russia is believed to have as much as 150 tons of plutonium and nearly 1,000
tons of highly enriched uranium in warheads and stockpiled as surplus at dozens
of sites around the country, according to various U.S. estimates.
</P>
<P>
	   Under a previous agreement the United States and Russia agreed to reduce
both their stockpiles of plutonium by 50 tons.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Russia is not believe to have given up on the use of plutonium as a
fuel in the future.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Russians believe that plutonium is a national treasure,'' Graham said
in an interview. ``They believe that plutonium can be used to produce power
safely, and they want to see it used for that purpose.''
</P>
<P>
	   While highly enriched uranium from weapons can easily be blended down for
use in commercial reactors, Russia's surplus plutonium ``poses far more
difficult obstacles,'' concludes a recent study on proliferation problems posed
by Russia's nuclear materials.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It will inevitably be many years before all of (Russia's) excess plutonium
has been transformed into forms that are no longer directly usable in nuclear
weapons,'' the study by the Center for Strategic and International Studies
concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1814 </TRAILER>
