<HEADLINE> Porsche Asks EU To Block BMW Aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- Porsche AG has asked the European Commission to
block a multimillion-dollar rescue package worked out last year between German
rival BMW AG and the British government to save the money-losing Rover operation
in Britain, a Porsche spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Board chairman Wendelin Wiedeking sent a letter to the commission last
summer after the deal involving $227 million in government subsidies was
announced, spokesman Manfred Ayasse said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It doesn't make sense when one company gets subsidies and another doesn't,"
Ayasse said, noting that Porsche has never asked for or accepted state aid.
</P>
<P>
	   A BMW spokesman in Munich said the automaker expected the European Union
Commission to approve the deal. A decision on whether it is compatible with EU
competition rules is expected this summer.
</P>
<P>
	   Including the state aid, BMW plans to invest $1.13 billion in Rover's
Longbridge plant in Birmingham, Britain's biggest car factory.
</P>
<P>
	   If the European Commission does not pass judgment by summer, BMW said it
would have to reassess its plans and possibly invest in an alternative plant in
Hungary, a country outside the European Union.
</P>
<P>
	   According to EU competition laws, Britain must prove that without its
subsidies, BMW will take its money outside the 15 countries comprising the
union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
