<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks Smoking Tax Hike  </HEADLINE>
   By CURT ANDERSON AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Smokers, corporate America and promoters of abusive tax
shelters would see $181 billion in tax increases over 10 years under the budget
outlined Monday by President Clinton. The plan also envisions $351 billion in
tax cuts targeted at the middle class.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress has previously rejected many of the tax increases, but they would
allow Clinton to use less of the projected surplus for tax cuts than measures
proposed by Republicans on Capitol Hill or the leading GOP presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's economic advisers say using too much of the surplus for tax cuts
jeopardizes other priorities including Medicare and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have to make tough choices,'' said Jack Lew, director of the White
House Office of Management and Budget. ``If the tax cut grows, it's going to
push something else out.''
</P>
<P>
	   GOP lawmakers contend taxpayers should get back a bigger chunk of the
surplus. The House this week plans to begin considering a 10-year, $182 billion
plan to cut taxes for married couples, including those who pay more than they
would if they were single.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I guarantee that Republicans in Congress will strongly oppose the
president's $181 billion tax hike,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of
the House Ways and Means Committee. ``It is amazing to me that after all these
years, President Clinton still cannot resist his urge to raise taxes on the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, Clinton left the plan open to GOP political attack by phasing in
the tax relief slowly, leading to net tax increases in fiscal 2001 of $9 billion
and fiscal 2002 of $1 billion, according to budget documents.
</P>
<P>
	   Among Clinton's proposed tax increases, which total $181 billion over 10
years:
</P>
<P>
	   --A 25-cents-a-pack increase in the federal cigarette tax, raising $66
billion over 10 years. It is less than half the 55-cent tax Clinton advocated
last year, which Congress ignored. The $66 billion total also includes proposed
fines on tobacco manufacturers of $3,000 for each teen-age smoker if teen
smoking isn't cut in half by 2004.
</P>
<P>
	   --New limits and penalties on corporate tax shelters, raising $23 billion
over 10 years. Firms that market tax shelters could be penalized with a 25
percent tax and the current penalty for corporate underreporting of income would
rise from 20 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   --New restrictions on corporations that deal in ``identified tax havens,''
usually foreign countries with a friendly or nonexistent tax law, including new
penalties on companies that fail to report their business in those places.
</P>
<P>
	   --Dozens of tax increases on businesses and various corporate transactions
that would raise more than $80 billion over 10 years, including a $14 billion
increase on insurance companies, a 5-cent-a-barrel oil tax to pay for spill
cleanups, taxes on trade associations' investment income over $10,000 and
reinstatement of a tax on oil and chemical companies to pay for Superfund
cleanups.
</P>
<P>
	   Major elements of the president's 10-year tax cut plan were released earlier
this year, including $45 billion in relief from the ``marriage penalty,'' $54
billion from new retirement savings accounts, and $32.7 billion in relief for
the middle class from the alternative minimum tax.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's plan also includes numerous middle-class tax credits or deductions
for child care, long-term health care, charitable giving, college costs, school
construction and inner-city development.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are targeted at the income ranges, the activities, that are engaged
in by the vast majority of American families,'' said Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers.
</P>
<P>
	   Counting all the tax increases, Clinton's net tax relief amounts to about
$170 billion over 10 years. That is far less than the $483 billion over five
years advocated by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, or the $237 billion over five
years proposed by Arizona Sen. John McCain, both seeking the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration put its net tax relief number at $254 billion over 10
years, arguing that revenue raisers are ``user fees'' for specific industries
and that the tobacco tax hike's intent is to curb smoking, not raise money. Seen
in that light, Clinton's revenue offsets would total $96 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress, meanwhile, is contemplating a variety of tax cuts that total more
than Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton also asked Congress to increase the Internal Revenue Service budget
by 9 percent to $8.8 billion. About $400 million would be used to hire 1,600
employees to improve customer service and reverse a sharp decline in enforcement
actions and audits, and to replenish an account for the IRS computer system
overhaul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1828 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deutch Clearances Face Review  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BRISCOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon is examining whether to end all security
clearances for former CIA director John Deutch, Defense Secretary William Cohen
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen acknowledged for the first time that Deutch has maintained access to
``some top-secret information in terms of a narrow area of technology,'' even
though the CIA revoked his clearances at the agency last summer because he had
kept classified documents on a home computer.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pentagon's inspector general has now asked the CIA for its evidence on
Deutch's security breaches, Cohen said at a news conference. ``I think it should
have been done sooner, but it was not,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the CIA apparently had offered no information about Deutch
previously, so his industrial security clearance at the Pentagon was not
reviewed. Limited industrial clearances are normally given to defense
contractors.
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen said the Pentagon revoked Deutch's broad security clearances last
August, including access to the Defense Intelligence Agency, the nation's main
military intelligence service. But as a defense industry consultant, Deutch
retained limited clearances, Cohen said. He said taking them away would require
a legal determination.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There must be a compelling level of evidence that would support removing
him from income-producing activities,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense Department lawyers will have to decide whether the evidence against
him is ``sufficient that we can, with due-process, terminate the relationship,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Before becoming CIA director, Deutch had served as deputy secretary of
defense from 1994 to 1995. He now acts as a consultant for several organizations
with defense contracts.
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen said he has no evidence Deutch had compromised any Pentagon
intelligence or operations in his activities. He described Deutch as ``fairly
aggressive in his work habits in working long hours, and I assume that had
something to do with'' his taking work home. But he said the Pentagon had not
determined whether he had done that with defense documents.
</P>
<P>
	   After news reports Saturday that Deutch retained industrial security
clearances at the Pentagon, the Defense Department inspector general contacted
the CIA to provide evidence to help determine whether all Deutch's clearances
can be dropped, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
	   The industrial clearance allows Deutch, a professor at Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, to serve as a paid consultant on defense contracts with
the MIT, SAIC Corp. and Raytheon Corp., Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, House Intelligence Committee Chairman Porter Goss, R-Fla.,
expressed surprise Monday that Deutch had kept his Pentagon security clearances
even after having his CIA ones revoked.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe that the removal of access to sensitive material should apply
universally,'' Goss said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
	   A former CIA intelligence officer himself, Goss said Deutch's ``admission
that he used bad judgment'' should result in a penalty that would apply equally
to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
	   He said his panel is continuing to review the matter and has not decided
whether to attempt to get testimony from Deutch.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate Intelligence Committee, meanwhile, was to meet privately Tuesday
with the CIA's inspector general, Britt Snider, and was waiting to hear whether
Deutch would agree to its request that he appear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1830 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon: Kosovo Taught Lessons  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BRISCOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Allied forces demonstrated ``unrivaled military prowess''
in the NATO action against Kosovo, a Pentagon report concluded Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   But the report says the conflict taught some lessons that may require
changes in doctrine, training, organization and technology.
</P>
<P>
	   In a detailed review of the 78-day air war that ended last June with Serb
forces driven out of the Yugoslav province, the Pentagon said the conflict
pointed to needed improvements in U.S. precision warfare capabilities. Some
portions of the report sent to Congress remained classified.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We forced Slobodan Milosevic to withdraw his forces from Kosovo, degraded
his ability to wage military operations and rescued over 1 million refugees,''
Defense Secretary William Cohen said in the report's introduction.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the NATO campaign ensured the stability of Eastern Europe, thwarted
ethnic cleansing and ensured NATO's credibility.
</P>
<P>
	   The report, which accompanied the department's 2001 fiscal budget proposals,
outlines enhancements already planned for precision strike, electronic warfare,
intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance capabilities.
</P>
<P>
	   The harshest self-criticism in the report is on one of the biggest U.S.
errors: bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, which killed three Chinese.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was a result of a failure in the process of identifying and validating
proposed targets,'' it said, adding that methods used were ``severely flawed.''
The report said immediate corrective actions were taken, however.
</P>
<P>
	   The report covers relations with Russia and considerations of a ground
option but offers no new details on the depth of concern over Russia's
opposition to the campaign or the debates within NATO over whether to use ground
forces.
</P>
<P>
	   It notes that the operation was conducted without a single combat fatality
among the 19 nations allied against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This achievement cannot be expected in every future conflict,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
	   The report contained no assessment of civilian or Serb casualties.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, Cohen said Monday he has no basis for judging the accuracy of a
Human Rights Watch report claiming 500 civilian casualties in the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Based on what I have seen, just a summary of that report, it seems to me
it does in fact expose Milosevic and his propaganda machine for the deceit that
they were perpetrating at that time, saying that there were 5,000 or more who
had been killed by this,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said every recommended target was reviewed to avoid unnecessary civilian
casualties. ``We don't want to see any innocent people harmed, and we took
extraordinary care to achieve those results,'' Cohen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
