<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Catholic Leader Hume Appeals To IRA  </HEADLINE>
   By SHAWN POGATCHNIK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland's most respected Catholic
politician appealed Monday for the Irish Republican Army to give up a cache of
its most powerful explosives, saying such a gesture was needed to prevent the
province's government from collapsing.
</P>
<P>
	   John Hume, the leader of the Social Democratic and Labor Party, sought to
resolve the crisis that is threatening Northern Ireland's Catholic-Protestant
administration after just two months in power.
</P>
<P>
	   Hume said the U.S.-brokered peace deal that got the administration formed
also created expectations the IRA would start to disarm. The outlawed group has
so far refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I now appeal to the IRA to show their deep respect for the will of the
Irish people,'' Hume said in remarks published by the Irish News, Northern
Ireland's main Catholic newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I ask them to demonstrate for all to see their patriotism and desire to
move the situation forward by strengthening the peace process through beginning,
voluntarily, the process of decommissioning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He called on the IRA to hand over some Semtex, the Czech-made plastic
explosive the group has particularly prized since receiving several tons of it
from Libya in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
	   But the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party rebuffed the message. Sinn Fein chairman
Mitchel McLaughlin said Hume normally demonstrated ``great sensitivity and
judgment'' -- but that it would be ``hard to imagine a more inappropriate moment
to make that particular suggestion.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hume's IRA appeal came hours after dissident IRA members bombed a rural
hotel in Irvinestown, 90 miles west of Belfast. No one was injured in Sunday's
blast, but the attack was bitter reminder of the days the province is struggling
to leave behind.
</P>
<P>
	   The Continuity IRA, a dissident splinter group that claimed responsibility
for the bombing, answered Hume by threatening further violence.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We intend to continue to progress our war effort regardless of how British
rule in the six occupied counties is remodeled,'' the group said in a statement
Monday, referring to Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
	   The province's major British Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, has
threatened to withdraw from Northern Ireland's Cabinet if the IRA does not begin
to surrender its weapons. It has scheduled a meeting for Saturday to debate the
issue.
</P>
<P>
	   That has left the British government with a choice -- to watch the Cabinet
collapse outright, or try to keep it intact by rendering it powerless.
</P>
<P>
	   In London, Prime Minister Tony Blair's government announced it intends to
push legislation through the House of Commons on Tuesday. That would enable
Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson to revoke the Cabinet's
authority and resume so-called ``direct rule'' from London on Friday, as he has
already said he intends to do.
</P>
<P>
	   Hume, who shared the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize with Ulster Unionist leader
David Trimble, is considered a prime architect of the peace process that
produced the Good Friday peace accord in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   That pact proposed that the power-sharing Cabinet be buoyed by gradual
paramilitary disarmament. But since it did not link the two goals explicitly,
the Ulster Unionists spent more than a year demanding a start to IRA disarmament
before they would share power with Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
	   The breakthrough brokered in November by American diplomat George Mitchell
required the Ulster Unionists to accept Sinn Fein before the IRA would open
negotiations with the disarmament commission. The commission issued its first
detailed report about that secret dialogue Jan. 31 -- and confirmed no concrete
progress had been made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1835 </TRAILER>
