<HEADLINE> Clinton's budget funds defense projects  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - President Clinton's budget request for fiscal year
2001 includes billions of dollars for submarines, aircraft and engines built in
Connecticut.
<P>
	   The $1.84 trillion plan for the year beginning Oct. 1, 2000 is "very good
news in terms of the military industrial base of our state," said Sen. Chris
Dodd.
</P>
<P>
	   Given the president's largesse both Dodd and fellow Democrat Sen. Joseph
Lieberman questioned why United Technologies Corp., the state's major military
contractor, is laying off workers.
</P>
<P>
	   Lieberman also stressed that inclusion in the president's budget indicates
the administration's support for programs but does not guarantee funding. The
federal budget is subject to Congress' approval.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's proposal includes $2 billion for the New Attack Submarine being
jointly produced by General Dynamics Corp.'s Electric Boat Division in Groton,
Conn., and Quonset Point, R.I., and Newport News Shipbuilding in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   Four of the submarines are slated to be built. Last year the Navy requested
a fifth but Congress did not approve it. This year Clinton is again asking for a
fifth submarine.
</P>
<P>
	   Another big ticket-defense item is $614 million for development of the
Comanche helicopter, a joint venture between United Technologies Corporation's
Sikorsky Aircraft, in Stratford, Conn. and Boeing Vertol of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
	   At least one member of Congress wants to cut the program.
</P>
<P>
	   "On the Comanche, our guard is up," said Lieberman, a member of the Senate
Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   East Hartford-based Pratt and Whitney would be one of the contractors on the
F-22, a project that Congress almost killed last session, Lieberman said. This
year Clinton is proposing nearly $4 billion to fund the program.
</P>
<P>
	   Pratt and Whitney would also get the contract to build the engine of 12 new
C-17 Airlift Aircraft. The frame would be built by Boeing. The total cost of
that proposed project is approximately $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Given the downturn in the world aerospace market, the budget proposals are
not enough to keep all workers on the job, said United Technologies spokesman
Peter Dalpe.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sales to the government is an important piece of our business, but only a
piece of our business," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Other defense spending proposals include:
</P>
<P>
	   - $270.7 million for CH-60S helicopters by Sikorsky.
</P>
<P>
	   - $116 million for the purchase of six Blackhawk helicopters built by
Sikorsky.
</P>
<P>
	   - $61.3 million for development of F-15A Eagle Multi-Mission fighter planes
with engines built by Pratt and Whitney.
</P>
<P>
	   - $149.2 million for the F-16 Falcon Multi-Mission fighter with engines
built by Pratt and Whitney.
</P>
<P>
	   Struggling Connecticut fishermen may also benefit from Clinton's proposed
$38 million fisheries package.
</P>
<P>
	   Programs to help fishing communities hit by depleted fish stocks include $10
million to buy back boats from those who decide to get out of the business and
$7 million from the U.S. Department of Labor to provide job counseling and
training for displaced fishermen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
