<HEADLINE> Explosion Hits Russian Apartments  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- An explosion ripped through a five-story apartment building
Russia's Far East on Monday night, killing two people and destroying 10
apartments, emergency officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The cause of the blast in Khabarovsk, 3,800 miles east of Moscow, was
unclear. The Interfax news agency quoted police as saying a gas leak was likely
to blame, though they did not rule out a terrorist attack. Gas explosions are
common in aging Russian apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
	   The explosion hit at about 5:40 a.m. Tuesday and ignited a fire that blazed
for three hours, a duty officer at the Emergency Situations Ministry said on
condition of anonymity. At least two people were killed and an unknown number of
others were injured. Residents were evacuated.
</P>
<P>
	   Russians are tense over a series of overnight bombings of apartment
buildings in Moscow and two other cities last year that killed about 300
sleeping people. The bombings were blamed on Chechen rebels, though no one
claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
	   Russian officials warned recently that Chechens were planning terrorist acts
in Russian cities because of federal troops' progress in the Chechnya war.
</P>
</TEXT>
