<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ rail line among goodies in Clinton budget  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - Where Democrats found much to like in President
Clinton's eighth and final budget, Republicans found too much spending and not
enough tax relief.
<P>
	   Clinton's proposed $1.84 trillion plan would expand access to health care,
shrink the national debt and cut taxes for the sick, elderly, poor and
college-bound, while spending more for the environment, schools and gun-law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey lawmakers were particularly heartened by continued funding for a
new rail line.
</P>
<P>
	   "Initiatives aimed at every citizen - tax cuts, investments in education and
health care - are proof of the nation's economic prosperity," said Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., called it "a responsible, visionary budget
that focuses on fiscal discipline and the future."
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans, who control both houses of Congress, were less impressed.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've always said we need to live within our means and the president has
chosen not to," said Rep. Frank LoBiondo, R-Vineland.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-Ridgewood, said Clinton should move faster to end the
"marriage penalty" for two-earner couples. "The president says he's for
eliminating the marriage tax penalty but he wants to take 10 years to do it and
even then he leaves out homeowners," Roukema said.
</P>
<P>
	   The budget faces months of congressional hearings and debate.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey lawmakers cheered a commitment of funding to continue work on a
20-mile light rail line in Hudson and Bergen counties, running north from
Bayonne to the New Jersey Turnpike's Vince Lombardi service area in Ridgefield.
</P>
<P>
	   The budget includes $121 million for the first phase of the project, running
from Bayonne to Hoboken via Liberty State Park and the Jersey City waterfront.
The Clinton administration also indicated it will commit the federal government
to providing $500 million through 2003 to fund the project's second phase.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey's office in Washington estimated that Clinton's renewed proposal
for school modernization would bring the state about $485 million in borrowing
authority to finance the building and renovation of public schools.
</P>
<P>
	   According to Lautenberg's office and the state office, the budget also
includes:
</P>
<P>
	   -$10 million for a nine-mile extension of Newark's existing rail line,
connecting the downtowns of Newark and Elizabeth with Newark International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
	   -$2.4 million for a recreation facility at Naval Weapons Station Earle in
Colts Neck. Rep. Rush Holt, D-Pennington, said Clinton's five-year defense plan
also includes $3.7 million for security at the yards where explosives are
unloaded from trucks.
</P>
<P>
	   -$9.8 million for a fitness center at McGuire Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
	   -$1 million to acquire land in Great Swamp National Wildlife Refuge in
Morris County; $2 million to acquire land in the Wallkill River National
Wildlife Refuge in Sussex County; and $1 million to acquire land in the Delaware
Water Gap National Recreation Area.
</P>
<P>
	   -$248 million for continued research into alternative energy sources, much
of which will go to the Princeton University Plasma Physics Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
	   -$53 million to deepen the Kill van Kull and Newark Bay Channel. At this
high level of funding, the project would be done by 2004.
</P>
<P>
	   -$12.4 million for shore protection projects, up from $11.6 million
requested last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Bill Pascrell, D-Paterson, cheered Clinton's proposal for a $25 million
pilot grant program to help communities obtain health and safety equipment for
their firefighters. Pascrell has been pushing to spend $5 billion over five
years to help fire departments hire more members, increase training and buy
high-tech safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Frank Pallone, D-Long Branch, said Clinton proposes continued funding
for the Sandy Hook-to-Barnegat Bay beach replenishment project and for flood
control projects in Middlesex and Monmouth counties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
