<HEADLINE> U.N. Force in Sierra Leone Expanded  </HEADLINE>
   By NICOLE WINFIELD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council voted Monday to nearly double
the size of its peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone and give the force broad
new responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
	   The resolution was approved by all 15 council members, including the United
States, which recently pledged to renew its support for peacekeeping in Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   The vote expands the U.N. force from its current 6,000 military personnel to
11,100, making it the largest U.N. force under active deployment.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The peace process in Sierra Leone remains fragile, and it is in all of our
interest to help ensure its success,'' deputy U.S. Ambassador Nancy Soderberg
told the council before casting the U.S. vote in favor of the expansion.
</P>
<P>
	   The Security Council first authorized a 6,000-member peacekeeping force in
October to monitor a cease-fire agreement reached by rebels and the government
in July and to oversee the disarming of fighters in the country's eight-year
civil war.
</P>
<P>
	   The West African regional intervention force known as ECOMOG helped end the
war and was responsible for maintaining security.
</P>
<P>
	   But Nigeria, which provided the bulk of ECOMOG's forces, announced in
December it was pulling out, compelling the United Nations to recommend an
expanded U.N. presence in the country to keep the cease-fire from crumbling.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, U.N. human rights experts said rebels had violated the cease-fire
by looting villages, burning houses, raping women and mutilating civilians in
the former rebel-held towns of Port Loko, northwest of Freetown, and Kabala in
the northwest highlands.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States previously cited continued cease-fire violations in
delaying approval for the force, but senior U.S. officials, Vice President Al
Gore, and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright came to the United Nations last
month to pledge U.S. support for peacekeeping in Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   With U.S. credibility on the line, U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke lobbied
to get congressional approval for the force, and is working to get similar
approval for the initial stages of a peacekeeping force for the Congo.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the resolution approved Monday, the expanded U.N. force for
Sierra Leone will now take on much of ECOMOG's responsibilities, providing
security at key government buildings, intersections and at Lungi airport outside
the capital of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
	   U.N. peacekeepers also are to help local law enforcement agencies maintain
order, guard weapons collections and help move humanitarian aid throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
	   The peacekeepers, whose mandate also was extended for another six months,
will have the power to use force to protect themselves and civilians threatened
with imminent violence.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Adoption of this resolution will cast another ray of hope across Sierra
Leone,'' the country's U.N. ambassador, Ibrahim Kamara, told the council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1918 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
