</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate takes action on DiFrancesco auto emissions plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Senate on Monday easily passed Senate
President Donald DiFrancesco's plan to cut lines at centralized auto inspection
centers, but Gov. Christie Whitman said she believes action she took last week
is already bringing relief to motorists.
<P>
	   The upper house, in a 37-1 vote, passed a bill that would suspend the
tougher emissions test at all 32 Division of Motor Vehicles inspection stations
and give motorists a $50 break at private garages until a private vendor can
solve problems that prompted long lines.
</P>
<P>
	   The lone dissenter was Sen. John Adler, D-Camden, who said he issued a
protest vote to show his fear that promised probes into the seven year, $400
million deal with Parsons Infrastructure and Technology will become a
"whitewash." The centralized lanes have faced problems since a new safety and
emissions inspections test was launched Dec. 13. The emissions upgrade is part
of the state's plan to conform with federal rules to clean the air.
</P>
<P>
	   DiFrancesco's bill, S-25, drew support from private garage owners and
senators who say it would do the most to buy time until Parsons can fix a wide
range of problems.
</P>
<P>
	   "We need to do something immediately, and this legislation offers a
practical solution," said DiFrancesco, R-Union.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman, however, says her approach - suspending the test and a more
involved computer system at 15 of the stations - is bearing fruit. Assembly
Speaker Jack Collins has said he is cool to the Senate President's idea. Both
Collins and DiFrancesco are eyeing a run for governor next year.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman last Monday suspended the tougher auto emissions test and a computer
system designed to monitor the process at the 15 centralized DMV stations that
had the longest waiting times. An old tailpipe test that essentially looks for
carbon monoxide is being used at these stations. Motorists whose cars pass the
old test will, until June 30, receive a sticker good for two years.
</P>
<P>
	   The new emissions test, which looks for asthma-causing smog compounds, is
still being administered at the 17 other centralized stations and at private
garages.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the governor's plan, the state is also paying up to $12 million to cut
the average $75 price tag for inspections at private garages by $25. She hopes
this will divert some drivers from centralized lanes, where there is no charge.
</P>
<P>
	   DiFrancesco, however, has a different approach: Cut out the tougher test at
all 32 centralized stations until June 30 and hand out one-year stickers to
motorists who take the less stringent tests at these stations. This is designed
to encourage motorists to take the tougher test at private garages, where they
get two-year stickers. The bill also calls for slicing the cost of inspections
at private garages by $50, with Parsons, not the state, providing the subsidy.
</P>
<P>
	   The Whitman administration is urging a delay of DiFrancesco's bill. Whitman
on Monday claimed her plan is working.
</P>
<P>
	   "The lines have gone down, the wait times have gone down at the central
lanes, and the number of people seeking to have their cars inspected by the
private inspection stations has actually gone up," Whitman said. "So the factors
that prompted that legislation being introduced now seem to be pretty well under
control."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman's office provided figures showing that the number of inspections at
private garages averaged 2,291 last week, after her plan was instituted. That's
about 150 more than the average for the week prior to the implementation,
according to the figures. One day from each week was excluded because of snowy
weather.
</P>
<P>
	   Garage owners, however, say Whitman's plan gives motorists no incentive to
use private garages. They maintain the numbers are down in the full week since
the plan went into effect.
</P>
<P>
	   "Over the last seven working days, we're experiencing an actual decrease in
the amount of inspections in private inspection facilities," said James Kenney,
vice president of the Repair Excellence Council of New Jersey, which represents
garage owners and mechanics. "Guys say since the enactment (of Whitman's plan),
they're doing three to four inspections a week, where they used to do three to
four inspections a day."
</P>
<P>
	   The federal Environmental Protection Agency prefers Whitman's approach,
according to spokeswoman Mary Mears. The EPA had threatened the loss of federal
highway funds if New Jersey didn't make good on its promise to toughen the
emissions test. Mears, however, said the EPA would "remain flexible" if
DiFrancesco's bill became law.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're going to wait and see what happens," Mears said. "We want the program
to work. We want New Jersey to get this clean air benefit."
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats, meanwhile, continued to call for an independent probe of how
Parsons got hired, and why a subcontractor's predictions of DMV disaster were
not heeded. Democrats charge that Parsons was hired by the state because the
company had hired people connected to the Whitman administration. Adler said he
voted no on DiFrancesco's bill to show his belief that an independent review is
needed.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman said she expects an attorney general's panel to be named soon to
look into implementation of the program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-07-00 1926 </TRAILER>
