<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diallo neighbor overhears remark following shooting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Moments after Amadou Diallo died in a hail of 41
police bullets, a man could be overheard making a remark suggesting a cover-up,
a next-door neighbor testified Monday.
<P>
	   "OK. OK. We're just going to say this," witness Ida Vincent quoted the man
as saying - testimony the defense had sought to keep out the trial of four
police officers. Vincent couldn't say if the remark was made by any of the
officers accused of murdering Diallo on his Bronx doorstep.
</P>
<P>
	   Vincent also became one of three prosecution "ear witnesses" so far to tell
jurors the barrage that killed the 22-year-old West African immigrant was
interrupted by a pause. Another neighbor, a police recruit named Thomas Bell,
testified the pause lasted up to five seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   Evidence of a pause could be used to argue the officers had a chance to stop
firing. The defense claims the shooting was uninterrupted and over within 10
seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   Kenneth Boss, 28, Sean Carroll, 36, Edward McMellon, 27, and Richard Murphy,
27, have pleaded innocent to the second-degree murder charges. If convicted,
they face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The slaying of the unarmed black man by the four white officers produced a
flood of pretrial publicity and protests alleging widespread abuse of minorities
by police. An appeals court responded by moving the case to Albany.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors allege the plainclothes officers, while searching for dangerous
criminals, made a "conscious decision" to fire 41 bullets at Diallo at 12:40
a.m. on Feb. 3, 1999, without warning; 19 bullets struck the victim. Defense
attorneys argue the shooting was a tragic mistake made after the victim ignored
orders to stop and pulled out a black wallet that appeared to be a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers have not been charged with trying to cover up their alleged
crime. Last week, a lieutenant who arrived on the scene moments after the
shooting testified that the officers were so stunned they couldn't speak.
</P>
<P>
	   Before Vincent took the stand, State Supreme Court Justice Joseph Teresi
barred prosecutors from asking about the fragment of conversation Vincent heard
out her front window because she couldn't identify the speaker. Defense attorney
John Patten had complained that the young housewife's account would leave the
false impression "that police were somehow concocting a story."
</P>
<P>
	   Later, when Vincent began to testify about it, the defense objected. But the
judge overruled, saying the defense itself had "opened the door" by
cross-examining Vincent about another part of the same conversation that
entailed someone cursing.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the other witnesses on Monday was a ballistics unit detective who
testified that four bullets fired by Carroll, two by McMellon and two by Boss
were recovered from Diallo's body. Other bullets found under Diallo's body were
shot by Boss and Murphy.
</P>
<P>
	   As the officers' pistols were introduced into evidence and passed around the
defense table, Boss and Carroll appeared to avoid touching them; Murphy and
McMellon simply passed them on. On cross-examination, the detective testified
that the semiautomatics could fire 16 rounds in as little as four seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   Bell, 28, told jurors on the morning of the shooting he was on the phone
with a cousin when gunfire erupted up the block from his apartment. The witness
said he heard four to five shots, followed by a three-to-five second pause, then
a longer, final volley from several guns - a sequence he tapped out on the
witness stand.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorneys attacked Bell's credibility, suggesting he lived too far
away from the scene to be reliable. But the witness stuck to his story.
</P>
<P>
	   "A pause is a pause, sir," he told an attorney at one point.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution is expected to conclude its case Tuesday by calling the
medical examiner who performed an autopsy on Diallo. The officers have said they
will testify in their own defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-07-00 1929 </TRAILER>
