<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bombs Damage Trucks in Virginia  </HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW BARAKAT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Bombs exploded in two pickup trucks Monday and a third
bomb detonated outside a nearby factory. One of the truck drivers was injured.
</P>
<P>
	   Two attempted capital murder warrants were issued for Luis Cristobal, a
47-year-old Cuban citizen who lives south of Richmond, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   Police refused to discuss a motive for the bombings, but Cristobal's former
employer, Dave Filippi, said he believes the attacks were related to a family
dispute.
</P>
<P>
	   Cristobal was the only suspect. A white van believed to have been used by
Cristobal was recovered at an Amtrak train station. It is not known if Cristobal
boarded a train, but police said he should be considered armed.
</P>
<P>
	   The first bomb went off about 6:30 a.m. as David B. Haston turned the
ignition on his truck in a subdivision south of Richmond. Haston was
hospitalized, although his injuries were not life-threatening, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   The second explosion happened about 7:50 a.m. in another subdivision as a
man put his pickup into gear. He was not injured.
</P>
<P>
	   Both trucks were damaged.
</P>
<P>
	   The third bomb detonated just before 8 a.m. outside the shop door of
Guttagard USA, a manufacturer of gutter protectors, in nearby Petersburg, state
police spokeswoman Corinne Geller said.
</P>
<P>
	   A secretary who was first to arrive at work noticed a strange smell. Then
Guttagard owner Dave Filippi discovered the bomb.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If it had gone off like it was supposed to, it would have blown the end of
the building off,'' Filippi said. ``We were lucky.''
</P>
<P>
	   The bomb, which caused only minimal damage, consisted in part of a 5-gallon
gas tank, a tank for compressed air, and an alarm clock, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said one of the pickup truck bombs apparently targeted Cristobal's
brother-in-law and the other an acquaintance of Cristobal's wife. Cristobal's
brother-in-law owns a business that shares space with Guttagard, Filippi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
