<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Assembly Democrats in spat over gubernatorial endorsement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - By backing a candidate for governor in the 2002
election, the majority leader of the state Assembly is forgetting that his
political "focus" should be on the 2000 elections, the Assembly speaker said
Monday.
<P>
	   Speaker Sheldon Silver said it is too early to worry about the governor's
race in 2002 with a president, congressional delegation and new state
Legislature to elect this November.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think there has to be an appropriate focus on the year 2000," Silver said
in reference to the activities of Assembly Majority Leader Michael Bragman.
</P>
<P>
	   Silver's comments served to confirm a report in Monday's New York Post of
tensions between Silver and Bragman over Bragman agreeing to be one of four
members of an advisory committee formed to promote state Comptroller H. Carl
McCall's candidacy for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
	   The Post, citing unidentified sources, reported that Silver was miffed
Bragman didn't clear his participation on the committee with Silver, and also
annoyed that Bragman wasn't worrying more about the 2000 elections at this point
than on the next gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
	   Bragman said Monday evening that he had not discussed the issue with Silver.
</P>
<P>
	   "However, no one should question my focus or my support for Assembly
campaigns, for the campaign of Hillary Clinton or any other statewide race,"
Bragman said. "If anyone should do that, then it's correct to say that there
should be a rift between that person and me."
</P>
<P>
	   Bragman said he has been a devoted follower and adviser to Clinton's
campaign and, when her announcement tour hits Syracuse Wednesday, he said he was
a chief organizer of a forum she will hold at Syracuse University and of a
fund-raiser later in the day.
</P>
<P>
	   McCall and Andrew Cuomo, the federal housing secretary and son of former
Gov. Mario Cuomo, are considered the top possible Democratic candidates for
governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
	   As majority leader, Bragman is the No. 2 figure in the Assembly behind
Silver. Bragman serves as traffic cop for legislation as it moves onto the floor
of the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   Though Bragman, of upstate Onondaga County, and Silver, of Manhattan, have
worked together in their current posts for seven years in the Assembly, they
have never been particularly close and relations between the two have at other
times been strained.
</P>
<P>
	   Bragman was not present at a news conference Silver called Monday to unveil
a series of managed care-related bills. Silver said he assumed Bragman was
attending to other Assembly business.
</P>
<P>
	   When asked whether a "rift" had developed between himself and Bragman,
Silver said the only rift he knew about was the much-publicized falling out that
Republican Gov. George Pataki and Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, also a
Republican, have been experiencing.
</P>
<P>
	   Silver appeared uncomfortable when pressed about his relations with Bragman
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think that is not a productive use of our time here," he told reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
