<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly panel OKs controversial $100 million HMO bailout  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - When a group of oncologists had no offices and no
medicine to treat 100 cancer patients, St. Peter's University Medical Center in
New Brunswick provided space and drugs.
<P>
	   The hospital took a chance. None of the patients had insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   They were among the members of a bankrupt HMO that left 165,000 people
without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, lawmakers are taking steps to make good on the state's promise to pay
hospitals and doctors that stepped in to treat these suddenly uninsured
patients.
</P>
<P>
	   The Assembly budget committee Monday passed a $100 million package to
reimburse hospitals and doctors for treating patients of two bankrupt HMOs - HIP
Healthcare of New Jersey and American Preferred Provider Plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Doctors and hospitals are owed $150 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The controversial package would pay them back with a combination of $50
million in state funds and $50 million from a new assessment on the state's
surviving HMOs. Doctors and hospitals have agreed to forgive $50 million of that
debt.
</P>
<P>
	   Powerful lobbyists lined up on both sides of the issue during a 3-hour
hearing on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Health insurance representatives called the plan a dangerous precedent that
forces surviving HMOs to bail out a competitor by paying their debts to
healthcare providers.
</P>
<P>
	   Randi Reichel, executive director of the American Association of Health
Plans, said no other state has taken this approach to mopping up after a failed
HMO. Typically, lawyers scrap together whatever assets they can find from the
failed business' estate, parent company and other revenue sources.
</P>
<P>
	   "The bill creates a tax or a penalty, which will be levied to the citizens
of New Jersey, and on the health plans that serve them, to benefit those
providers who entered into less than profitable business arrangements," Reichel
testified.
</P>
<P>
	   The insurers also asked lawmakers to require an independent audit of the
medical bills, saying they may be incorrect. But Insurance Commissioner Karen
Suter said the bills are already subject to court review. An audit, she said,
would only cost money and further delay payment.
</P>
<P>
	   About a dozen representatives from hospitals around the state also
testified, saying they stepped in when patients - and the state - needed help.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, they said, it's time to share the pain.
</P>
<P>
	   They called the measure a "compromise" that divvies up the financial burden.
</P>
<P>
	   "We don't have an extra dollar, never mind an extra couple of million," said
Ed Curley, director of managed care for the Bon Secours New Jersey Health System
in Jersey City. "And we are not in any way responsible for the failure of the
HMOs or for the failure of the state to prevent their collapse. Nevertheless, we
have agreed to absorb one third of the losses from the HMO failures."
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the unpaid bills are for patients of the former HIP Health Plan of
New Jersey, which was the state's fourth largest HMO. HIP began failing in 1998
and went bankrupt last spring. American Preferred Provider Plan, a smaller
company, was taken over by the state in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill prohibits HMOs from passing on the increase to their customers.
Suter said the assessment would only amount to 1 percent of premiums.
</P>
<P>
	   But Paul Langevin, president of the New Jersey Association of Health Plans,
said the state's HMOs lost about $26 million in 1998. The measure would tack
another $17 million annual hit onto those losses, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "If this is about preventing insolvency for health plans, then I'm missing
something," Langevin said.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill does allow HMOs to write off some of the increase.
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. Christie Whitman is pushing the plan, saying payment is essential to
reward hospitals and doctors that provided care to HIP members, even though they
ran the risk of not getting paid for their services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-07-00 1937 </TRAILER>
