<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Tumble for Second Session  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices tumbled for a second consecutive session on
Monday as market players sold securities in preparation for a U.S. auction of
$32 billion in new debt this week. Inflation concerns also pressured the market.
</P>
<P>
	   The bond price drop pulled the Treasury market further back from a powerful
rally last week, which was triggered by news the federal government intends to
cut circulation of long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year bond, which had plunged 1 27/32 points on Friday,
dropped another 29/32 point, or $9.06 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which
moves in the opposite direction of price, rose to 6.34 percent from 6.27 percent
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Preparations for an infusion of supply this week pressured prices. Large
Wall Street firms sold securities to try to push down market prices for the new
securities to levels seen as attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
	   The Treasury Department plans to sell $12 billion in new five-year notes
Tuesday, $10 billion in 10-year notes Wednesday and $10 billion in 30-year bonds
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The market's volatility reflects lingering uncertainty from the government's
announcement last week of plans to slash the national debt, meaning some
securities will be phased out altogether. A sharp supply cut would drive up the
value of bonds remaining in circulation.
</P>
<P>
	   Prices of short-term Treasury securities also fell Monday, dropping 3/32 to
3/16 point, while intermediate maturities fell 11/32 to 19/32 point, according
to the Bridge Telerate news service.
</P>
<P>
	   In other trading Monday, yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.58
percent, with the discount falling 0.07 percentage point to 5.42 percent.
Six-month yields were 6.02 percent as the discount rose 0.07 percentage point to
5.76 percent. One-year yields finished at 6.20 percent, with the discount rising
0.01 percentage point to 5.84 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, rose
to 5.75 percent from 5.63 percent late Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bond Buyer index of municipal bonds fell 5/32 point to 91 26/32. The
yield was 6.27 percent, up from 6.26 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
