<HEADLINE> Fall Fashion Week Opens in NYC  </HEADLINE>
   By FRANCINE PARNES
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Fashion Week is blimping out. This week's jampacked lineup
of designer previews is bursting at the seams with an unprecedented 110 shows,
and nobody's complaining it looks fat.
</P>
<P>
	   Fall Fashion Week, New York edition is snatching the international fashion
spotlight while cramming the catwalks. The semiannual openings feature an
expanded, nine-day marathon.
</P>
<P>
	   This season's round of shows kicked off Thursday with some twists --
menswear shows as well as a special program dedicated to newcomer designers. Add
to the bulky mix a smattering of Europeans, including Hugo Boss, Vivienne
Westwood, Nicole Farhi.
</P>
<P>
	   The timing couldn't be better -- at least for those opening in New York. For
the third season in a row, designers stateside have stepped to the front of the
line by scheduling their collections before Paris, Milan and London.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've fallen into the cadence of being first,'' says Stan Herman,
president of 7th on Sixth, which coordinates Fashion Week. But ``there is still
shuffling as to when the shows will be in the future. In the fashion business,
once your gait is equal, they tackle you at the knees.''
</P>
<P>
	   The tents at midtown's Bryant Park, home to Fashion Week for the past five
years, have grown from three to four, to accommodate a cosmopolitan caravan of
2,000 retailers, editors, photographers and others with a passion for fashion.
</P>
<P>
	   Carolina Herrera is known for dressing the social-page set, and Richard
Tyler dresses stars. At their previews Monday, the week of women's wear shows,
both designers showed something for everyone across America -- at least for the
rarefied social strata spanning Park Avenue drawing rooms to red-carpet galas of
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These clothes travel and have to look very well everywhere,'' says
Herrera, and by that she does not mean wash-and-wear. ``They have to be
international clothes. You can go to Paris, you can go to Rio, you can go to
India. And it's also very New York.''
</P>
<P>
	   Herrera pulled out all the rich-girl trappings, with sweeping, opulent
Russian sable coats; dresses lavishly embellished with embroideries inspired by
19th century Russian architecture; and dramatic details like single-shouldered
gowns and cascading ruffles.
</P>
<P>
	   As for color, Herrera's palette is an exercise in dozens of ways to wear
blazing red, fuchsia and orange, from monochromatic leather skirts and jackets
to strapless silk gowns.
</P>
<P>
	   Why the bright idea? ``There's not one woman who doesn't have a good time in
a flame-colored dress,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
	   Also on Monday, Tyler invited the fashion flock to his 150-year-old
townhouse-studio, where he previewed his top-of-the-line label, Richard Tyler
Couture, suitable for such Tinseltown clientele as Melanie Griffith, Sarah
Jessica Parker, Calista Flockhart, Heather Locklear and Meg Ryan.
</P>
<P>
	   While $6,000 for a blue-gray strapless gown might sound much, you'll get
more for the mileage: it's fashioned with three folds and tiers in back, from 40
yards of fabric.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I was inspired by architecture,'' says Tyler. ``Frank Lloyd Wright's
drawings of falling water seemed to fit in with the layers.''
</P>
<P>
	   But you'd better set out early for the Academy in one of these stunning
creations. Allow time for stop-and-go traffic of your own doing, thanks to
super-high heels, ballskirts with trains and the longest, leanest gowns not
built for speed.
</P>
<P>
	   One look that promises to show up throughout the week on the runways:
high-heeled, knee-high boots, which Tyler paired even with cocktail dresses.
</P>
<P>
	   What do you get when you put preppy plaid skirts on sexy, see-through
fabrics?
</P>
<P>
	   ``High-octane Ivy League,'' says Tommy Hilfiger, whose odd ode to
traditional tartans stems from a trip last summer to the Scottish countryside.
</P>
<P>
	   With a celebrity-studded audience of Billy Baldwin, Harry and Jill Connick,
Angie Harmon and Debbie Harry, Hilfiger rocked at Roseland, a dance club space
where he staged a coed show of plaid-gone-mad, unexpectedly pieced or paneled on
slim skirts, as well as on men's trousers with a different pattern on each leg.
Plaid also paved the linings of shrunken jean jackets in navy metallic leather
for men and in black calf hair for women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 1938 </TRAILER>
