<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diallo Neighbor Testifies on Remark  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM HAYS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Amadou Diallo's next-door neighbor testified Monday
that moments after Diallo died in a hail of 41 police bullets, she overheard a
man making a remark suggesting a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
	   ``OK. OK. We're going to say this,'' Ida Vincent, testifying at the murder
trial of four New York City policemen, quoted the man as saying.
</P>
<P>
	   Vincent said she couldn't say whether the fragment of conversation heard
outside her front window in the Bronx came from any of the officers.
</P>
<P>
	   Vincent also became one of three prosecution ``ear witnesses'' so far to
tell jurors the barrage that killed the 22-year-old West African immigrant was
interrupted by a pause. Another neighbor, a police recruit named Thomas Bell,
testified the pause lasted up to five seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   The pause -- which Vincent said was as long as a ``few seconds'' -- could be
used to argue the officers had a chance to stop firing. The defense claims the
shooting was continuous.
</P>
<P>
	   Bell, 28, told jurors that on the morning of the shooting he was on the
phone when gunfire erupted up the block from his apartment. The witness said he
heard four to five shots, followed by a three-to-five second pause, then a
longer, final volley from several guns -- a sequence he tapped out on the
witness stand.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorneys attacked Bell's credibility, suggesting he lived too far
away from the scene to be reliable. But Bell stuck to his story.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A pause is a pause, sir,'' he said at one point.
</P>
<P>
	   Diallo, an unarmed West African immigrant, was shot 19 times last February
by plainclothes officers searching for dangerous criminals. The defense contends
the shooting was a tragic mistake made after the victim ignored orders to stop
and pulled out a black wallet that looked like a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   Kenneth Boss, 28, Sean Carroll, 36, Edward McMellon, 27, and Richard Murphy,
27, could get 25 years to life in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
	   The slaying of the black man by four white officers produced a flood of
publicity and protests alleging widespread abuse of minorities by police. An
appeals court responded by moving the case to Albany.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors plan to call to the stand a medical examiner who will testify
that one of the bullets tunneled up Diallo's leg. That could help prove the
prosecution's claim that the officers kept shooting as Diallo was falling down
or on the ground.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense has argued Diallo remained standing throughout the barrage of
gunfire, making him appear still to be a threat.
</P>
<P>
	   Before Vincent took the stand, Justice Joseph Teresi had ruled that the
prosecution could not ask about the remark she claimed to have overheard.
</P>
<P>
	   When Vincent began to testify about it, the defense objected. But the judge
said the defense itself had opened the door by asking Vincent about other
remarks she claimed she overheard in the aftermath of the shooting, including a
man cursing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
