<HEADLINE> Federal budget contains New York goodies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - President Clinton's farewell budget proposal beefs up
spending on education and health care, critical issues in New York that his wife
has made cornerstones of her Senate campaign.
<P>
	   The president would increase spending by millions of dollars for Head Start,
after school programs and school construction.
</P>
<P>
	   All are initiatives embraced by Hillary Rodham Clinton, who officially threw
her hat into the U.S. Senate race the day before her husband unveiled his $1.84
trillion budget proposal. The president's plan would create more than 7,000 new
Head Start slots in New York and would increase education spending by millions
of dollars largely through a class-size reduction initiative.
</P>
<P>
	   The president's plan also contains a $10,000 college tuition tax credit at a
cost of $31 billion. The tuition tax break, popular with middle-class suburban
voters like those the first lady must woo in New York, was first put forward by
Sen. Charles Schumer, D-NY. The first lady has been pushing it lately on the
campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
	   On the health front, the president's plan would spend $168 billion over 10
years to create a prescription drug benefit for Medicare recipients.
Prescription coverage is another campaign theme of the first lady, who authored
the president's ill-fated health care reform plan.
</P>
<P>
	   But the president's spending plan isn't all good news for New York.
</P>
<P>
	   While Clinton in 1998 offered the federally-owned Governor's Island for sale
to New York State for $1, the asking price was upped to some $30 million in the
fiscal year 2001 plan the Clinton administration unveiled Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   But a letter from White House Budget Director Jack Lew to Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., indicated that the White House was willing to knock
that down to "nominal price" once a plan incorporating public use was finalized.
</P>
<P>
	   New York state and city have agreed on a plan to turn the for the 172-acre
island into a tourist center complete with a major hotel, a conference and
commercial center, an arts and cultural exhibit hall, a sports complex and open
space for public use. Located in the middle of New York Harbor, Governor's
Island has been occupied only by migratory birds and a small caretakers staff
since the U.S. Coast Guard left in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress has ordered it sold for "fair market value" of $500 million in
2002.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, an analysis of the president's budget plan conducted by Schumer
and Rep. Nita Lowey, D-Westchester County, determined that it would bring in
hundreds of millions more for New York City than the GOP-led Congress is
currently spending.
</P>
<P>
	   "This plan makes it clear that the priorities of New Yorkers are the
priorities of the administration and the Democrats in Congress," Lowey said.
</P>
<P>
	   But some Republicans groused that the president's heavy-spending plan seemed
designed to boost his wife's Senate campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's targeting his tax proposals where he believes they can do her the most
good," said Rep. John Sweeney, R-Saratoga County.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Thomas Reynolds, a Republican from the Buffalo area, agreed.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Clinton family is the most political family in America so if there is a
way they could benefit from the budget they would," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's perfecting his legacy as an indiscriminate big spender with this
budget," Reynolds added.
</P>
<P>
	   But Moynihan praised the president's discipline in paying down the debt.
</P>
<P>
	   "As I have said on numerous occasions our first priority should be to pay
down the national debt," New York's senior senator said. "The president proposes
to do just that. Under his budget, the debt held by the public is eliminated by
2013."
</P>
<P>
	   Among the New York projects funded in the president's budget plan for New
York:
</P>
<P>
	   -$20 million to convert the James A. Farley Post Office into the new Penn
Station.
</P>
<P>
	   -$10 million for the East Side Access Project to connect the Long Island
Railroad with the New York City subway's east side trains through Grand Central
Station.
</P>
<P>
	   -$10.3 million for Fort Drum Consolidated Soldier Support Center.
</P>
<P>
	   -$13.6 million for United States Military Academy at West Point for Cadet
Physical Development Center.
</P>
<P>
	   -$7 million to combat the Asian Longhorned Beetle that has infested
thousands of trees in New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
