<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diallo Trial City Is Pro-Police  </HEADLINE>
   By LYNN BREZOSKY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Albany County, New York. Middle-class, 90 percent
white, with a strong Irish Catholic heritage. A place where, tradition had it,
cops were there to guard your door and ignore your wager.
</P>
<P>
	   If there's a better place to defend a police officer, Albany defense
attorney Terence Kindlon says, he hasn't heard of it.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People here just like police,'' Kindlon says. ``They're inclined to trust
authority.''
</P>
<P>
	   New York Post columnist Bob McManus, who grew up here, readily agrees. He
says Albany has a strong ``Irish Catholic conservative civil service view of the
world.'' ``They like their cops,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
	   So it makes sense to both of them that the four white New York City
policemen charged with murder in the Bronx slaying of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed
West African immigrant killed in a barrage of 41 bullets, would have a better
chance with a jury in Albany than one in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial opened last week after a jury of eight whites and four blacks was
selected.
</P>
<P>
	   The case was moved to Albany, 150 miles north of New York City, after
defense attorneys argued, among other things, that the Bronx has a reputation
for being hostile to police.
</P>
<P>
	   In Bronx County, which is two-thirds black and Hispanic, the police have
become outsiders, McManus says.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The NYPD is second- and third-generation officers whose families' have
moved to Long Island and Rockland County to get away from the pressures of what
they were policing,'' he says. ``They're refugees going back to butt heads with
people.''
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the outcome of the Diallo case is far from certain.
</P>
<P>
	   While the defense will argue that the four police officers thought Diallo
was reaching for a gun and that it was all a tragic mistake, the 41 shots fired
could make a powerful impression on any jury.
</P>
<P>
	   And Kindlon and McManus believe that Albany is not as pro-police as it was,
say, a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past month, Albany juries have accepted arguments that a
well-respected detective forged a confession in the murder of an 82-year-old
former minister and that police were overzealous in arresting a man who helped
an alleged cop shooter escape.
</P>
<P>
	   In that latter case, police officers were caught on videotape roughing up a
store clerk following a marijuana arrest. The video led to internal disciplinary
action against four officers that once would have been unheard of.
</P>
<P>
	   Some criminal justice experts, such as Boston College law professor Robert
M. Bloom, say confidence in police around the country and in Albany is weakening
because of such things as the Rodney King beating in Los Angeles and the Abner
Louima case in New York City, in which the black defendant was sodomized with a
broomstick in a police station bathroom.
</P>
<P>
	   More recently, police officers on highways across America have been accused
of routinely pulling over blacks in what is known as racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Even in a place like Albany, conservative with an almost Midwestern feel,
there is a general feeling that you just can't take a police officer's word
anymore,'' says Albany Times Union columnist Fred LeBrun.
</P>
<P>
	   The convenience store rampage by police has black activists up in arms.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was very scary, to have police come out as though they were a gang.
They're supposed to be the ones protecting us. So who are we going to call?''
says Darryl Lahon, whose grocery store video camera caught police on tape.
</P>
<P>
	   It's the same frustration that is heard in the Bronx, says James Cohen, a
law professor at Fordham University there. ``The feeling is people in power --
the white people -- tend to treat people without power differently. They tend to
treat them worse,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
	   Recently there have been other cases in the Albany area that could give the
defense in the Diallo trial reason for both optimism and concern.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year in Albany, a black basketball player at the College of Saint Rose
claimed he was beaten by two white, off-duty police officers in a police garage
following a bar fight. The officers were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
	   In nearby Schenectady, a busload of partying off-duty police officers
cruised a crime-ridden area in 1997, throwing eggs out the bus windows.
Community leaders accused the officers of shouting racial slurs. Local news
agencies lost their battle to get the names of the officers released.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Frankly, you get enough of this stuff, it cracks through into people's
consciousness,'' Kindlon says. ``My sense is that every day it gets a little
easier to hear stories about bad cops all over the place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 2044 </TRAILER>
