<DOCNO> APW20000207.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State adopts new shore development rules, about six years late  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - After six years and several trips to court, the
state on Monday finally adopted rules designed to curb development in New
Jersey's sensitive coastal region.
<P>
	   But the new version of the Coastal Area Facility Review Act (CAFRA) won't
stop a long debate that has raged since lawmakers first ordered changes in 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmentalists on Monday continued to say the new rules will actually
prompt more development at the shore. And shore-area lawmakers once again
pledged to stop the rules, saying they hit their towns with more planning
restrictions than other parts of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   State officials say the new rules are designed to target development to
places planners say can handle it, and keep developers away from the most
environmentally sensitive areas.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's been a long road," said Raymond Cantor, assistant environmental
commissioner for land use management. "This is a big change. For the first time,
we're setting boundaries on where development should go. These rules will add a
significant mechanism to help prevent sprawl."
</P>
<P>
	   The rules were supposed to be adopted in 1994. However, the process was
stalled as developers and environmental groups tangled over what should be
allowed. Environmentalists in 1998 charged in court that the state was dragging
its feet while developers were carving up sensitive shore land. A state Superior
Court judge set a timetable for the state to act, and officials pledged to have
rules in place.
</P>
<P>
	   The rules force coastal towns to abide by the state master plan, which
details where development should and should not take place.
</P>
<P>
	   State officials say the rules make it easier for developers to build in
targeted areas that are already developed - and much more difficult for them to
build in undeveloped, environmentally sensitive areas.
</P>
<P>
	   The regulations would apply only to commercial buildings and residential
developments of more than 24 units. They affect much of the Atlantic coast east
of the Garden State Parkway, and the Delaware Bay shore north to the Delaware
Memorial Bridge.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmentalists, however, say the rules allow too much development in
environmentally sensitive areas. They say the old rules protected the shore
more.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's going to bring sprawl and overdevelopment and ruin an area of New
Jersey that the people cherish, our shore," said Jeff Tittel, director of the
Sierra Club's New Jersey chapter.
</P>
<P>
	   Tittel said that while the rules attempt to target development, they simply
allow too much in areas that should be protected.
</P>
<P>
	   "This could turn Cape May into another Edison," Tittel said.
</P>
<P>
	   DEP's Cantor responded that such worries are unfounded.
</P>
<P>
	   "They have taken worst-case scenarios of population growth and densities,
and they're ignoring the fact that there are limitations," Cantor said. "There
are now significant areas where significant development that would have been
allowed before is now limited. There are boundaries now."
</P>
<P>
	   Area lawmakers, however, say the rules are too restrictive.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Senate last year passed a bill saying the proposed rules did not
follow the Legislature's intent. The measure drew a sharp response from Gov.
Christie Whitman, who said it would block smart planning. It never reached the
Assembly, however, and died when the two-year session expired last month.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. William Gormley, R-Atlantic, said the effort to thwart the rules will
be revived. Gormley said the Department of Environmental Protection wants to
force coastal towns to follow the state plan while other towns can ignore it. He
said when it comes to development and planning, all towns should be treated the
same.
</P>
<P>
	   "For all other towns, the implementation of the state plan involves
negotiation (with local officials)," Gormley said. "That's not the case with
these other towns. These regulations don't stop sprawl."
</P>
<P>
	   Gormley said the disagreements are "not about environmental concerns.
They're about the planning process."
</P>
<P>
	   Cantor said the Legislature in 1993 mandated that "the coast should be
regulated differently than anywhere else, and therefore what we're doing is
regional coastal development in correlation with the state plan, as the
Legislature has directed us to do."
</P>
<P>
	   While enacting the plan, the DEP immediately proposed several changes that
were partly based on concerns from municipalities and environmentalists.
Previously, the state had delayed enactment of the rules to clear up such
concerns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
