<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't: Nev. Forest Workers Safe  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA CHEREB Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RENO, Nev. (AP) -- U.S. Forest Service employees in Nevada have been
intimidated and harassed by local residents but are not in danger, according to
an investigation by the agency released Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Disputes over Forest Service policies have created such hostility in some
areas that Gloria Flora, the supervisor of the Humboldt-Toiyabe National Forest,
cited concerns about her employees' safety when she resigned in November.
</P>
<P>
	   That led to the appointment of the fact-finding team that issued its report
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The report said the agency and local residents and officials all have a
strong desire to improve relations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The team did not find any reportable incidents of personal threats,
violence or abuse in the past several years that would cause the Forest Service
to seek criminal prosecution through the Department of Justice,'' said Joel
Holtrop, a Forest Service director who headed the investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Holtrop said a dispute in northeast Nevada's Elko County, where local
officials have locked horns with the Forest Service over a remote dirt road on
national forest land, is ``unusual and antagonistic.''
</P>
<P>
	   Residents want to rebuild a dirt road along the Jarbidge River, but the
Forest Service has fought their efforts, saying the erosion would harm the
river's bull trout population.
</P>
<P>
	   Many current and former Forest Service employees in Elko reported being
treated disrespectfully and feeling ``afraid for their well-being'' while doing
field work. The report said few employees wear their uniforms or drive marked
agency vehicles.
</P>
<P>
	   The spouses of two Forest Service employees said they were ostracized from
community groups and verbally abused and ridiculed in public. Another complained
of disparaging remarks against the agency made by a child's teacher.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Of the approximately 35 employees we met with in Elko, the majority said
that working and living in this setting affected their sense of well-being,''
the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   But the report concluded that while the experiences ``were beyond what is
typical in work environments for Forest Service employees in other places'' the
situation in Elko ``is not considered dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
