<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Says He's Reformer, Not McCain  </HEADLINE>
   By RON FOURNIER AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DOVER, Del. (AP) -- George W. Bush struck at the heart of John McCain's
candidacy Monday, accusing his presidential rival of ``saying one thing and
doing another'' on political reform. Bush said he, not McCain, was the
``reformer with results,'' changing the style and substance of his campaign to
counter his foe's momentum.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain reacted with a sarcastic dig: ``I guess Governor Bush is now a
reformer. If so, it's his first day on the job.'' And the Arizona senator's new
TV ad accuses Bush of breaking his promise to run a positive campaign and ends
with a zinger: ``Do we really want another politician in the White House America
can't trust?''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush is scrambling to regain his footing after McCain's rout in New
Hampshire shocked the GOP establishment and raised calls for a harder-hitting,
more freewheeling national front-runner.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush took the weekend off to retool his campaign, emerging with a format
that borrows from McCain's successful New Hampshire run. The Texan's stump
speech was cut in half and his question-and-answer sessions were two or three
times longer than normal.
</P>
<P>
	   And he tried to co-opt the Arizona senator's reform agenda.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to remind people that in this race there is one person who can
stand up and say, 'I'm a reformer with results,''' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Texas governor stood in front of a freshly minted sign that read
``Reformer with Results.'' He used the word ``reform'' a half-dozen times in a
10-minute speech, after rarely letting the term slip from his lips before New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said as governor he fought the status quo to improve schools, pass
lawsuit reform and cut taxes. By contrast, he said McCain champions campaign
finance reform while using his influence in the Senate to leverage political
donations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I hear him say, 'Let's have campaign finance reform' and on the other hand
he says, 'Let's pass the plate,''' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said he had pushed for a gift ban in Congress, line-item veto power
for the president and the closing of corporate tax loopholes. ``I have a long
record of reform and it's very well known,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   When wrongly attacked, McCain said, ``We are going to fire back and we are
going to fire doubly.'' Bush said the same: ``You can cut it any way you like
it. I'm going to take it to him.''
</P>
<P>
	   The back-and-forth overshadowed Tuesday's primary here. McCain has skipped
the contest, leaving Bush and conservative Steve Forbes to do battle while the
Arizonan focuses on the Feb. 19 showdown in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush aides are predicting a Delaware victory, and they need one to help
recover from the New Hampshire loss. Forbes hopes to finish close to the Texan,
but some supporters fear he'll finish behind McCain, who is still on the ballot,
and be forced out of the race.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The elites are not picking the nominee,'' Forbes said between Delaware
stops. ``That's why I feel optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush and McCain were looking ahead to South Carolina. A loss there would
damage Bush, but his fund-raising and organizational advantages would probably
keep him afloat. McCain, however, needs to keep his momentum moving.
</P>
<P>
	   Their rivalry intensified, Bush and McCain accused each other of going
negative and breaking a pledge not to do so. Both campaigns plan to feature the
same footage from a Michigan debate in which the two candidates shook hands and
promised to run positive campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   The mudslinging was not welcomed by voters. ``I don't like any of the
negative stuff, from either guy,'' said David Dixon, pulling up a chair at a
Bush luncheon.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush decided he had no other choice after New Hampshire. McCain's victory
there erased Bush's lead in polls in South Carolina and dramatically narrowed
his edge in California, Michigan and other key primary states.
</P>
<P>
	   The Texas governor said his mistake in New Hampshire was allowing McCain to
go unchallenged when he attacked Bush's tax policies and raised questions about
the governor's ability to serve as president.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The days of smiling and letting John McCain define me are over,'' Bush
said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, he told supporters, ``If you're tired of no results and simple,
empty rhetoric, if you're tired of people saying one thing and doing another,
come and join my team.''
</P>
<P>
	   Establishment Republicans welcomed the shift. ``He's going to get down in
the pits,'' said Priscilla Rakestraw, Republican National Committee member from
Delaware. ``I think he's learned a lesson from (Vice President Al) Gore, who was
playing the king for a while. He has to reply to attacks.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's new approach comes with some risk. He fielded dozens of questions in
the new format, most of them effortlessly. But he surprised one group of
veterans with his answer to a query about the anthrax vaccine administered to
U.S. troops to protect against biological warfare.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is the first I've heard of it,'' Bush said of the controversial
program launched in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush aides said the pointed remarks about McCain would continue. Testing
possible lines of attack, Bush pollsters were asking South Carolina residents
whether their opinion of McCain would change if they knew the Senate Ethics
Committee had said in 1991 he had ``exercised poor judgment'' in intervening
with regulators in the Keating Five banking matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 2055 </TRAILER>
