<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Down in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was sharply higher against the yen early Tuesday
amid deepening concern Japan's economic recovery may take longer than expected.
Tokyo stocks edged lower.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was trading at 108.94 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market
early Tuesday, jumping 1.12 yen from its level of 107.82 yen late Monday and
also gaining on its late New York level of 108.78 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 46.54 points, or 0.23
percent, to 19,898.89 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Monday, the average
closed up 111.86 points, or 0.92 percent, at 19,945.43.
</P>
<P>
	   The yen extended a retreat provoked by comments from Japan's chief economic
planner, Taichi Sakaiya, who warned in a television interview Sunday that the
economy will likely shrink during the October-December quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sakaiya's remark initiated the yen selloff abroad as two quarters of
contraction are regarded as a recession," said Takeo Suzuki, assistant manger of
foreign exchange at Nomura Trust and Banking.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas traders found little consolation in assurances by the economic
planner that the government still expects to hit its growth target of 0.6
percent for the fiscal year ending March 31.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was also supported by continued signs of strength in the U.S.
economy, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 107.08 yen, up from 105.99 yen
late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, the benchmark Nikkei edged lower as investors took
profits on high-flying technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   Some sellers took their cue from a retreat by stocks on Wall Street, where
the Dow Jones industrial average fell 0.4 percent to 10,905.79.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares in banks were hurt by news that the Tokyo metropolitan government
plans a new corporate tax on major lenders.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section fell 6.82 points, or 0.39 percent, to 1,747.96. On Monday the TOPIX
finished up 13.56 points, or 0.77 percent, at 1,754.78.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8950
percent from 1.8500 percent Monday. Its price fell 0.38 point to 98.34.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
