<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Take Guards in Peru Riot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- About 50 convicted Maoist rebels in a frigid Andean prison
were holding guards hostage Monday, after a riot that left at least two people
dead.
</P>
<P>
	   One guard and one rebel were killed in riots at Yanamayo prison that were
started Sunday by rebels loyal to Shining Path leader Oscar Ramirez Durand, who
was captured last year, said cable news station Canal N.
</P>
<P>
	   The Maoist inmates, armed with homemade knives, took an undetermined number
of guards hostage and demanded to be treated as prisoners of war instead of
terrorists, news stations reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The high-security prison holds some 450 rebel prisoners. Most belong to the
Shining Path, but members of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, a much
smaller rebel band, are also serving sentences there.
</P>
<P>
	   A statement from the National Penitentiary Institute said an unspecified
number of hostage were taken after the rebels refused to return to their cells,
prompting a violent confrontation.
</P>
<P>
	   The official version confirmed the inmate's death, but said he died at the
hands of other rebels. The statement did not confirm the guard's death and did
not specify how many guards were taken hostage. Officials refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
	   Television broadcast images of heavily armed police surrounding the prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Elias Aycacha, director of the Puno State Hospital told Peruvian radio
that three police guards had been injured, one critically.
</P>
<P>
	   A Justice Ministry spokesman in Lima said the rebels had been demanding
better prison conditions and more frequent family visits. President Alberto
Fujimori and Justice Minister Alberto Bustamante had visited the prison last
week to review conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   The Yanamayo prison is 12,700 feet above sea level in Puno, 525 miles
southeast of the capital Lima and near the Bolivian border.
</P>
<P>
	   New York native Lori Berenson was held there until being transferred in 1998
for health reasons. A military judge convicted Berenson, 30, of treason in 1996
for helping lead a thwarted assault on Congress by the Tupac Amaru.
</P>
<P>
	   Peru's war against leftist rebels has left 30,000 dead since 1980. Ramirez
Durand is serving a life sentence at a naval base in Lima -- where the group's
founder, Abimael Guzman, also is imprisoned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 2113 </TRAILER>
