<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Union Meet With Mediator  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SEATTLE (AP) -- Representatives of The Boeing Co. and its engineering and
technical workers' union met with a federal mediator on Monday to discuss an
impasse over contract issues.
</P>
<P>
	   The Society of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace voted down
Boeing's latest offer on Wednesday, but stopped short of calling a strike when
the mediator, C. Richard Barnes, agreed to intervene.
</P>
<P>
	   Barnes, head of the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service, met with
both sides for five minutes Monday to lay the ground rules for the talks, then
sent them to separate rooms and began shuttling between them. The talks
continued for at least three hours.
</P>
<P>
	   At Boeing facilities, workers reacted to a company memo asking for no
demonstrations or walkouts during the talks. At least 750 employees marched in
Everett, while another 250 marched around the Museum of Flight across from
Boeing's headquarters, said SPEEA spokesman Bill Dugovich.
</P>
<P>
	   Prior to the talks, neither side seemed particularly confident about a
friendly resolution. Boeing took away its previous offer, narrowly rejected
51-49 percent, and said it would no longer collect union dues until a new
contract was approved.
</P>
<P>
	   For its part, the union spoke with picket captains over the weekend about
strike procedures.
</P>
<P>
	   "They keep trying to use these bullying tactics," said SPEEA Executive
Director Charles Bofferding, regarding Boeing's decision on union dues. "I don't
think they've shown an inkling that they're willing to negotiate with us."
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said the dues move was perfectly legal since
there is no contract, and was done to help bring leverage to bear in the talks.
</P>
<P>
	   "The union can call for a strike, and we can refuse to collect dues, which
is a courtesy to the union on our part to begin with," Conte said. "These are
pressures that both sides are bringing."
</P>
<P>
	   Bofferding said the members of the union are ready to strike, despite the
slim margin of the previous vote. He said the union was willing to give
mediation a try, but would walk out and strike if Boeing proved intractable on
its positions regarding pay raises and benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
