<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ------
MPs Demand Stewart's Resignation
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- A chorus of opposition MPs called Monday for Human Resources
Minister Jane Stewart to take the fall for the bungled administration of federal
grants and resign.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the first day back for parliamentarians after a seven-week break and
the first time opposition parties could face off with the Liberal government
over the controversy.
</P>
<P>
	   Internal audits in Human Resources Development Canada found millions in
grants and contributions were paid out without standard paperwork to back them
up.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If the Human Resources minister had any respect for Canadian taxpayers and
respect for the principle of ministerial accountability, she would rise in her
place and resign from cabinet,'' said Reform Leader Preston Manning.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Will the minister do the honorable thing and resign?'' asked Bloquiste
Paul Crete.
</P>
<P>
	   Prime Minister Jean Chretien fielded the first volley of questions, while
Stewart sat red-faced in her seat. She later pointed out that she has a plan to
fix the problem and the money isn't missing.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Govt. Denies Overpayment, Fraud
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- The federal government has managed to fill in the gaps in its
paperwork for $11.7 million worth of job-creation, youth and training grants and
says there is no evidence of overpayment, fraud or other irregularities.
</P>
<P>
	   But another 34 projects, worth more than $20 million, remain under scrutiny
and thousands more will eventually be reviewed, officials from the Human
Resources Department acknowledged Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   David Good and Alan Winberg, two senior Human Resources officials who
briefed reporters, suggested the new information would help clarify the
controversy that has raged over department spending for the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Ex-Hockey Night Host Cornell Dies
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON, Ontario (AP) -- Ward Cornell, who served as the host of Hockey Night
in Canada for 13 years and then spent more than a decade as a top civil servant,
has died. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
	   Cornell died Saturday in hospital in Uxbridge, Ontario, about 60 kilometers
northeast of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
	   Cornell became the host of Hockey Night in Canada in 1959 and held the job
until 1972, when Dave Hodge replaced him.
</P>
<P>
	   Ward then represented the Ontario government as agent general in London
until 1978. He returned to Canada in 1980 and served as Ontario's deputy
minister for culture and recreation as well as deputy housing minister.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Quebecois Flag Plan Criticized
</P>
<P>
	   MONTREAL (AP) -- A Parti Quebecois resolution to ban Canadian flags from
public buildings in Quebec has some people snapping to attention.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's no way,'' said Pierre Roy, a retired veteran in Quebec City who
successfully lobbied to have the Maple Leaf returned to the flagpole outside the
provincial capital's city hall.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Canadian flag is the flag of our country,'' Roy said Monday from
Quebec City. ``There's no provincial government allowed to do such a thing.
We'll go to the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
	   The resolution to only fly Quebec's Fleur-de-lis flag on buildings under
provincial jurisdiction such as schools and hospitals was passed at a Parti
Quebecois meeting on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   The resolution is not binding on the government and Premier Lucien Bouchard
said flying only the Quebec flag would be studied but hedged when asked his
opinion on the matter.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Farmers Occupy Saskatchewan Legislature
</P>
<P>
	   REGINA (AP) -- Saskatchewan's farm crisis took a militant turn Monday as
about 150 angry farmers converged on the legislature and threatened to occupy
the building until they get provincial aid.
</P>
<P>
	   Years of frustration and anger down on the farm boiled over in the face of
politicians grappling with how to help grain farmers facing their worst year
since the Depression.
</P>
<P>
	   Premier Roy Romanow was heckled and cursed as he left a meeting with
representatives of the Saskatchewan Rally Group without agreeing to their
demands for almost $400 million from the province's coffers.
</P>
</TEXT>
