<HEADLINE> Columbine Threat Guilty Plea Likely  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A Florida teen-ager accused of threatening Columbine High
School over the Internet plans to plead guilty, the U.S. Attorney's Office said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Ian Campbell, 18, of Cape Coral, Fla., is accused of telling a
Columbine student he would ``finish what begun'' at the high school last April,
when two teen-age gunmen killed 12 students and a teacher before committing
suicide.
</P>
<P>
	   Campbell's attorneys notified a federal judge in Denver Monday ``that it's
their intention to plead guilty,'' said Jeff Dorschner, a spokesman for the U.S.
attorney.
</P>
<P>
	   Dorschner would not say whether prosecutors had agreed to reduce the charge
against Campbell, who pleaded innocent. He would not discuss the details of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   Campbell was charged with transmitting a threat against another person in
interstate commerce, a felony that carries a sentence of up to five years in
prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
	   Campbell's lead attorney, Ellis Rubin of Miami, could not be reached for
comment Monday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Campbell was scheduled to appear in court Wednesday, when details of the
agreement might be made public, Dorschner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
