<DOCNO> APW20000207.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, McCain in Close S.C. Race  </HEADLINE>
   By WILL LESTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain are locked in a very
close race in a poll of those most likely to vote in South Carolina's Republican
primary, and McCain is narrowing the gap nationally.
</P>
<P>
	   An ABC-Washington Post poll released Monday gave Bush, the Texas governor,
48 percent, and McCain 43 percent while Steve Forbes and Alan Keyes were in the
low single digits in the race to win South Carolina's Feb. 19 primary. The
difference between Bush and McCain was just outside the 4.5 percentage point
error margin for most likely voters.
</P>
<P>
	   The ABC-Post poll was designed to measure the sentiments of those very
likely to vote in a primary with relatively low turnout. Turnout in the last
three GOP primaries has been low, averaging below 10 percent of the state's
voting age population, ABC pollster Gary Langer noted. This poll allowed for
slightly higher voter participation in such a competitive primary, about 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   On 10 of 11 personal qualities, McCain scored higher than Bush in the
ABC-Post poll. South Carolina's potential voters saw him as more likely to say
what he really thinks, not a typical politician, someone who knows world affairs
and who has an inspiring personal story.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush performed better than McCain among core Republican groups in South
Carolina, leading among those who identify themselves as Republicans,
conservatives and members of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
	   More than four-out-of five said McCain would be a good commander in chief,
while two-thirds said that of Bush. McCain's overall performance was stronger
with the inclusion of more independents and Democrats, who can vote in the
state's primary.
</P>
<P>
	   In national polls of likely voters in the Democratic primaries, Vice
President Al Gore has a 30-point to 50-point lead over Bill Bradley, depending
on the poll.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has cut into Bush's lead in national polls since late January when
the Texas governor led by about 50 points, according to other surveys released
Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush led McCain, 56 percent to 34 percent, in a CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll
taken after McCain's win in the New Hampshire GOP primary, compared with a 65-16
lead for Bush in the days immediately after he won the Iowa caucuses on Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
	   A Zogby poll showed Bush leading McCain 48 percent to 30 percent among
likely voters in Republican primaries. The ABC-Post poll had Bush at 63 percent
and McCain at 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Many Bush supporters have said he is the best hope of victory in November
and the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll indicated that a majority, 57 percent, still
feels Bush gives Republicans the best chance of winning the White House, while
39 percent said that of McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has caught up with Bush in how the public views them personally, with
67 percent viewing the Arizona senator favorably, compared with 51 percent who
said that in late January in the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. Only 12 percent had
an unfavorable view of McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's favorable rating was at 63 percent, down slightly from the 71 percent
in October, while 31 percent viewed him unfavorably, up slightly from 21 percent
in October.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican race recently has focused on who is more of a Washington
insider and who is the outsider challenging the system. Interestingly, more
people saw Bush as a Washington insider, 35 percent, than saw McCain, a member
of Congress since 1983, as an insider, 27 percent, in the CNN-USA Today-Gallup
poll.
</P>
<P>
	   Six-out-of-10 people said McCain wants to be president because he has a
sincere desire to help the country, while people were about evenly split on
whether Bush wanted political power or wanted to help the country.
</P>
<P>
	   By a 2-to-1 margin, Republicans said they want a candidate who is not tied
to the party's leaders, in the CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. That's a description
that more closely fits McCain than Bush. A narrow majority of Democrats said
they wanted a nominee who was loyal, reflecting the advantage the vice president
has in that race.
</P>
<P>
	   The CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of 1,018 people and the Zogby poll of 1,024
were taken Friday through Sunday. They both had error margins of plus or minus 3
percentage points. The ABC-Post poll of 1,013 people nationwide and 490 of the
most likely voters in South Carolina was taken Thursday through Sunday. It has
an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points nationally and 4.5 percent
for the most likely voters in South Carolina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
