<HEADLINE> Politics 2000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Alan Keyes said Monday
he will not support rival John McCain if McCain won the party's nomination
because he is ``not pro-life.''
</P>
<P>
	   Keyes, speaking to a packed crowd at the National Press Club, said he could
not continue to support a GOP that nominates a candidate who favors abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It will leave me,'' Keyes said of the party. ``I will not leave it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Keyes criticized McCain for saying last month that any decision about ending
a pregnancy would be up to his teen-age daughter. He clarified that later,
saying it would be a ``family decision.''
</P>
<P>
	   Keyes has said the answer lacked the strong anti-abortion position he
considers crucial.
</P>
<P>
	   ``John McCain is not pro-life,'' said Keyes.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Democrat Bill Bradley's campaign for Ohio's March 7
primary will be chaired by two veteran officeholders and a college friend of the
former New Jersey senator, his campaign announced Monday on the eve of his first
visit to the state this year.
</P>
<P>
	   State Senate Minority Leader Ben Espy, former lawmaker and Cuyahoga County
Commissioner Mary Boyle and Cleveland lawyer Robert Rawson will run Bradley's
campaign in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement came the day before Bradley's first trip to the state since
Dec. 1. He planned a town meeting Tuesday night to discuss racial unity.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore, Bradley's rival for the Democratic presidential
nomination, is scheduled to attend a union dinner in Dayton on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Rawson was Bradley's classmate at Princeton in the early 1960s and a fellow
Rhodes Scholar.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley has told gay and lesbian leaders he will
continue to speak out against a California ballot initiative that would ban
state recognition of same-sex marriages legally performed in other states, the
National Gay and Lesbian Task Force said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democratic presidential candidate met with representatives of the
Washington-based group during a campaign stop Sunday at a Queens, N.Y., church.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's rival, Vice President Al Gore, also has denounced the initiative
appearing on the state's March 7 ballot. State law currently recognizes only
marriage between a man and a woman.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are gratified that Senator Bradley not only recognizes the inherent
unfairness of Proposition 22, but will continue to use his campaign as a bully
pulpit to organize and get his supporters out to vote against it,'' said Kerry
Lobel, the group's executive director.
</P>
<P>
	   A Bradley spokesman confirmed the meeting, but declined to go into details.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- GOP presidential candidate Steve Forbes, long a
favorite of Washington's social conservatives, got a lift Monday when the
Republicans' 1998 Senate nominee, Linda Smith, announced her endorsement.
</P>
<P>
	   The former state legislator and former congresswoman and longtime leader of
the state's politically powerful religious conservatives said she is sending an
endorsement letter to the 42,000 supporters on her mailing list.
</P>
<P>
	   In it, she declares Forbes to be her choice for the presidential nomination,
calling him ``a bold leader who stands on principle.'' Her nod is considered
significant, since she has built up a loyal following from previous campaigns,
her statewide initiatives and work on campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith's letter, released by Forbes' national campaign office, said, ``When I
compare today's presidential candidates to Ronald Reagan, I would have to say
the one that comes closest to him is Steve Forbes. Steve Forbes is the kind of
leader that we have wanted for many years.
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes' forces are hoping to do well in the state's precinct caucuses on
March 7.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith's is the first major endorsement for Forbes in the state. Most of the
state's GOP establishment, including Sen. Slade Gorton and Rep. Jennifer Dunn,
have signed on to George W. Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
