<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Administration Seeks Embassy Safety  </HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE GEDDA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two years after the bombing of two U.S. embassies, the
Clinton administration asked Congress on Monday for $1.05 billion to improve
embassy security for fiscal 2001 and an additional $3 billion over the three
ensuing years for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
	   Historically, Congress resists advance appropriations, but the
administration is hopeful lawmakers will make an exception for embassy security
given the vulnerability of overseas missions to terrorism.
</P>
<P>
	   There has been a sense of urgency on the diplomatic security issue since the
bombing of U.S. embassies in East Africa in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   An independent panel led by Adm. William Crowe, former chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, recommended a year ago an ambitious $14 billion program over 10
years to upgrade security at U.S. embassies and consulates and undertake new
construction where necessary.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress appropriated $567 million for fiscal 2000, more than $800 million
short of what Crowe and his Accountability Review Panel recommended.
</P>
<P>
	   Crowe said he was pleased with the $1.05 billion the administration
requested Monday even though the figure is still almost a third less than his
panel had recommended.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Whatever figure you turn in, you're always going to get a little less,''
Crowe said in a telephone interview. ``I'm going to keep agitating.'' He spoke
before the administration disclosed its intention to request an advance
appropriation.
</P>
<P>
	   Marshall Adair, president of the union that represents career diplomats,
said he was pleased that embassy security was given higher priority. But he
complained the administration is still about $1 billion behind where it should
be after two years, based on the recommendations of the Crowe panel.
</P>
<P>
	   He noted that an estimated 80 percent of U.S. embassies are considered
substandard in terms of security.
</P>
<P>
	   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright acknowledged that the $1.05 billion
contemplated for fiscal 2001, plus the advance appropriation request is not
sufficient.
</P>
<P>
	   She said she is ordering a review of current plans ``to ensure that
cooperation encountering threats to our security from whatever source is at the
highest level.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our goal is to ensure that as far as humanly possible and consistent with
their professional responsibilities, our people are fully protected, to make
certain that the classified information we handle is fully secure, and to drive
home the message that at the Department of State, security is everybody's
everyday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 2322 </TRAILER>
