<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1 dead, 1 wounded in Westchester Community College shooting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   VALHALLA, N.Y. (AP) - A man in the midst of a breakup with his
18-year-old girlfriend accosted her in a college hallway Monday, shot her in the
head as she tried to get away, then shot and killed himself as he ran off across
the snow-covered campus.
<P>
	   "His hand went up, then his head went back. He was still running, then he
fell," said Rayvon Miller of Greenburgh, a student who witnessed the suicide at
Westchester Community College.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting was the first in the 54-year history of the college, said
Julius Ford, vice president of student services.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not really what you expect when you go to school," said Louis Ramirez,
a student from the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
	   The wounded woman, Joy Thomas of Mount Vernon, was listed in critical
condition at the Westchester Medical Center. Detective William Rehm of the
Westchester County police said, however, that her gunshot wound - from a bullet
that glanced off her temple - did not appear to be life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
	   Rehm said the woman was in a first-floor hallway of the Academic Arts
building at about 12:15 p.m. when the man, identified only as a Yonkers man in
his 20s who was not a student, confronted her.
</P>
<P>
	   "There was an ongoing prior relationship," Rehm said. "We have reason to
believe that that relationship may have been terminated by one party or the
other."
</P>
<P>
	   They argued and she tried to leave, Rehm said, but he followed and "she
obviously felt threatened. ... She went for the first open door she came to."
</P>
<P>
	   Just as she was going through the door, the man grabbed her from behind and
fired one shot from a handgun. She fell into the room, where a staff member and
a student had been meeting, and they shut the door behind her. The bullet that
glanced off her head was found embedded in the door, Rehm said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Closing the door was good thinking on their part," the detective said. "It
ended the assault and forced the perpetrator to leave."
</P>
<P>
	   The attacker ran off along campus pathways and was near the school's
Classroom Building when he shot himself. Blood marked the snow where he fell,
the gun still in his hand.
</P>
<P>
	   Don Gregory, a journalism teacher who walked by the body soon after the
suicide, called the experience "surrealistic."
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a numbing sensation to see someone lying there. ... You feel despair
at not knowing what to do."
</P>
<P>
	   Ford said classes were not interrupted for the 20,500 students, but campus
exits were sealed for half an hour until police concluded that the dead man was
the only attacker.
</P>
<P>
	   The school offered a telephone hotline for worried parents and counseling
for any students troubled by the shootings.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford said the building where the first shooting occurred is patrolled by one
unarmed guard. The school will eventually review security, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The attack followed a likely murder-suicide at Columbia University. Police
believe former student Thomas G. Nelford slashed his girlfriend's throat
Saturday, killing Kathleen Roskot, a 19-year-old sophomore. Nelford then jumped
in front of a subway train a few hours after her body was discovered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-07-00 2325 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BP Amoco-Arco Merger Challenged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Following the federal government's lead, the state
governments of California, Oregon and Washington went to federal court Monday to
try to stop BP Amoco's $30 billion acquisition of fellow oil giant Atlantic
Richfield Co.
</P>
<P>
	   The three states filed a suit that mirrored the argument offered Friday in a
suit by the Federal Trade Commission: The new company would dominate Alaska oil
production and control West Coast supplies, with the power to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
	   The merger was to have been completed Monday, but the companies have agreed
to wait until March 10, when a federal judge is scheduled to consider the FTC's
request for a preliminary injunction. The states' suit may be consolidated with
the FTC case.
</P>
<P>
	   London-based BP Amoco agreed last March to acquire Los Angeles-based
Atlantic Richfield, known as Arco, a purchase that would create the world's
second largest non-government oil company, behind Exxon Mobil. BP Amoco and Arco
account for about 70 percent of Alaska crude oil production.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents of the merger focus on its effects on Alaska oil supplies to West
Coast refiners.
</P>
<P>
	   "The merger as presently proposed would result in a harmful monopoly of
Alaska North Slope crude oil supplied to California refiners," California
Attorney General Bill Lockyer said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
	   He said Californians are already suffering from a lack of competition among
major refiners, and the new merger could cause "a major loss of competition and
greater squeeze of the West Coast."
</P>
<P>
	   The two companies say their combination will not damage competition and deny
the existence of a specialized West Coast market for Alaska crude oil. They
contend the international oil market would compensate for any effect on the
price of Alaska oil.
</P>
<P>
	   BP Amoco has agreed with the state of Alaska to sell off holdings that would
reduce the merged company's share of Alaskan production from 70 to 55 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 2326 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Talks With Union To Continue  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SEATTLE (AP) -- Representatives of The Boeing Co. and its engineering and
technical workers' union met with a federal mediator on Monday to discuss an
impasse over contract issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Talks lasted more than 5 1/2 hours and were scheduled to resume Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
	   Union spokesman Bill Dugovich said there were no breakthroughs and strike
preparations continue.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're giving this mediation our best shot. We're hoping for the best but
preparing for the worst," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said, "Boeing participated fully in the process
and will do so when the process continues tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
	   The Society of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace voted down
Boeing's latest offer on Wednesday, but stopped short of calling a strike when
the mediator, C. Richard Barnes, agreed to intervene.
</P>
<P>
	   Barnes, head of the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service, met with
both sides for five minutes Monday to lay the ground rules for the talks, then
sent them to separate rooms and began shuttling between them.
</P>
<P>
	   At Boeing facilities, workers reacted to a company memo asking for no
demonstrations or walkouts during the talks. At least 750 employees marched in
Everett, while another 400 to 600 people marched around the Museum of Flight in
Seattle's industrial district, Dugovich said.
</P>
<P>
	   Prior to the talks, neither side seemed particularly confident about a
friendly resolution. Boeing took away its previous offer, narrowly rejected
51-49 percent, and said it would no longer collect union dues until a new
contract was approved.
</P>
<P>
	   For its part, the union spoke with picket captains over the weekend about
strike procedures.
</P>
<P>
	   "They keep trying to use these bullying tactics," said SPEEA Executive
Director Charles Bofferding, regarding Boeing's decision on union dues. "I don't
think they've shown an inkling that they're willing to negotiate with us."
</P>
<P>
	   Conte said the dues move was perfectly legal since there is no contract, and
was done to help bring leverage to bear in the talks.
</P>
<P>
	   "The union can call for a strike, and we can refuse to collect dues, which
is a courtesy to the union on our part to begin with," Conte said. "These are
pressures that both sides are bringing."
</P>
<P>
	   Bofferding said the members of the union are ready to strike, despite the
slim margin of the previous vote. He said the union was willing to give
mediation a try, but would walk out and strike if Boeing proved intractable on
its positions regarding pay raises and benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 2331 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indiana OK's Ten Commandments Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE SMITH Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indiana House approved legislation Monday that
would let government entities, including public schools, post the Ten
Commandments in their buildings.
</P>
<P>
	   The House approved the bill 92-7. The Senate already has approved a similar
measure, and it seems certain that one of the bills will end up on the desk of
Gov. Frank O'Bannon. O'Bannon has said he would sign the bill if it was
constitutional, and he believes the current versions are.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the bill, the commandments could be posted in schools, courthouses or
on other government property if displayed with other documents of historical
significance that have formed and influenced the U.S. legal system.
</P>
<P>
	   The debate comes amid a nationwide push to display the commandments in
public venues. Supporters say America based its system of laws on the 10 rules
the biblical Book of Exodus says God gave to Moses.
</P>
<P>
	   The Indiana Civil Liberties Union and its national counterpart, the American
Civil Liberties Union, say that's not a good reason to post the commandments in
public buildings.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1980, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that posting the commandments in
schools violates First Amendment protections against a government's promoting
religion. But new lawsuits are pending.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Vernon Smith, D-Gary, said the bill made sense, especially given crime
rates and violence in schools.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We cannot separate the religious history of this country from the
government history of this country because they are intertwined,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think God is everything to this nation. I think the reason our nation is
in trouble is because we have cut off our roots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 2335 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000207.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: 19 Dead in S. Africa Floods  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NELSPRUIT, South Africa (AP) -- Floodwaters caused by torrential rains in the
northern part of South Africa left at last 19 people dead as they washed away
roads and bridges and snarled traffic, news reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   South African Broadcasting Corp. said that 15 people drowned when they tried
to cross a swollen river in Northern Province. Two others drowned in the same
province, while details of the remaining deaths were not reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Parts of the popular Kruger National Park were isolated because of flooded
roads. Parks customer relations manager Chris van der Linde said 18.4 inches of
rain had fallen in 18 hours. A restaurant's windows were broken and furniture
was floating away, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The rain continued Monday evening but was expected to tail off, the weather
bureau said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-07-00 2335 </TRAILER>
