<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-07 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search Continues in German Wreck  </HEADLINE>
   By JOACHIM SONDERMANN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRUEHL, Germany (AP) -- Authorities struggled on Monday to identify
mutilated bodies pulled from the wreckage of a weekend train crash, saying more
victims might still be found.
</P>
<P>
	   Three of the eight confirmed dead -- one woman and two men -- were
identified as Germans. A police spokesman in Cologne said the severe injuries of
the other five, all male, was hampering efforts to determine their names or
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
	   Another 149 passengers were injured shortly after midnight Sunday when the
train, en route from Amsterdam, the Netherlands, to Basel, Switzerland, derailed
just south of Cologne.
</P>
<P>
	   Workers managed to cut apart one of the two most severely damaged cars from
the nine-car train and remove it from the tracks. ``It is possible we will still
find more bodies,'' police spokesman Juergen Goebel said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I was sleeping and woke up minutes before the crash -- maybe less than
that -- because I heard I think when it derailed,'' said one passenger, Daniel
Susskind, 22, of North Potomac, Maryland. ``It was very loud and it was also
shaking a lot.''
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities said the train was going too fast -- 76 mph in a 25 mph zone --
when it hit a switch and went off the tracks.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Wille, a spokesman for the federal railway oversight office, said there
was no apparent technical reason why the train would have speeded up by itself,
especially considering it had braked normally just a few minutes earlier before
entering the station.
</P>
<P>
	   The head of Germany's Deutsche Bahn rail system, Hartmut Mehdorn, also said
Monday that mechanical defects played no role in the crash.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue of train safety is particularly sensitive after the June 1998
derailment of a high-speed train near Eschede that killed 101 people --
Germany's deadliest train accident ever. In a report released last month, the
cause of that crash was found to be a broken wheel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
